<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950919-000009</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950919-000009</DOCID>
<DATE>950919</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Psycho-thriller still enthralls</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CAROLE WODDIS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>24</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>REVIEW</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>976306299</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
CAROLE WODDIS finds contemporary resonances in a new theatre
production of the Patrick Hamilton, Broadway classic Gaslight
AS director Keith Baxter puts it: ''There's something in human nature
that we never lose about enjoying being frightened.''
Talking about his new production of Patrick Hamilton's classic
Gaslight Baxter adds: ''Of course audiences have changed in the 50 years
since it was first seen, but I think -- I hope -- they'll take it as
something more than simply a thriller.
''I hope they'll see that it has something to say about sexual
perversity and thralldom -- as a story of two, or rather three people,
locked into an emotional crisis that has as much to say as Pinter's The
Birthday Party.''
Hamilton's Gaslight is nothing if not an exercise, like Pinter, in
atmospheric horror -- the manipulation of a vulnerable woman by a cruel,
if charming husband with a very specific plan in mind. Pinter, of
course, is of another world to Hamilton.
But in a strange sort of way, perhaps Hamilton with his fascination
for the perverse workings of the mind (he himself suffered from deep
depressions) is a forerunner of the Pinter who has an uncanny knack also
of tapping into the darker reaches of the unconscious.
At any event, Hamilton, author of the equally eerie Rope, managed with
Gaslight -- revived by Baxter in a new production starring Frank Finlay
and Jane How and opening in Glasgow next month -- to write one of the
most popular thrillers of the 40s and immediate post-war period.
Certainly it ran on Broadway for three years, the longest running
foreign play at the time, 1941, to do so and was quickly turned into a
film, after its 1938 London premiere (when the part of the terrorised
Mrs Manningham was taken by Gwen Ffrangcon-Davies) with Anton Walbrook
and later in the US by director George Cukor when it starred Ingrid
Bergman as the unfortunate Mrs M and Charles Boyer as her sadistic
husband.
Hamilton's knack was to mix several ingredients: marital insecurity, a
spooky sense of foreboding together with straightforward Victorian
melodrama and add an inspirational bit of stage business, the lowering
of the drawing room gaslight at certain strategic moments -- a
combination in the right hands calculated to create tension and
apprehension in most audiences.
Baxter remembers the films dimly, but says it wasn't until he re-read
the play that he realised he didn't really know the story at all.
''Hamilton was such a wonderful writer but he also has such a wonderful
sense of theatre.
''Re-reading the play and his novels, you also realise there's a
tremendous sexual pulse -- a very dark one -- running throughout his
work. In the film, Bergman is a young woman being terrorised by an older
husband. It's quite clear in the play though that the woman is in thrall
to her husband who in his turn has begun to show affection for a much
younger maid.''
Chiming in with our own times, Baxter's sees Mrs Manningham's
predicament as much more to do with a woman almost fatally undermined by
her fear of losing her husband's affection. ''We know enough now,'' he
says, ''about emotional -- and physical -- abuse and how a woman will
cling to the man who is abusing her. For Mrs Manningham there's no place
to go.''
Baxter's Mrs Manningham is Jane How, a tall statuesque beauty with
Scottish connections on both sides of the family (Ayrshire and St
Andrews). Best known, apart from her time as Jan Hammond, Dirty Den's
girlfriend in EastEnders, for light comedy and indeed, with more than a
touch of the Maria Aitkens about her, How recognises other contemporary
parallels.
She says: ''The psychological games are really quite applicable in any
relationship that's gone very sour. Patrick Hamilton's parents were
alcoholic and so was he. You can see all those alcoholic, manipulative
games coming into play in this. It's quite credible what he does, how he
treats her.''
Baxter is perhaps taking slight liberties with Hamilton by making the
husband considerably younger than Mrs Manningham. But it intensifies her
psychological dependence -- both in late Victorian and modern terms: the
need for any show of affection from him on the one hand and as a woman
grateful to have been finally saved from ''being on the shelf'' on the
other.
''I think though,'' says How, ''Hamilton had really latched on to
that Victorian obsession of 'women going mad' -- you know, the Mrs
Rochesters going mad once a month who could probably now be cured with
hormones. There is, too, that terrible thing of when you're in a really
bad relationship you know it's all heading towards something -- but you
can't actually get off that road.''
* Gaslight runs at the Theatre Royal in Glasgow from October 2 to
October 7.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
