<DOCNO>GH950919-000010</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950919-000010</DOCID>
<DATE>950919</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Orange glow at BAe</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>26</PAGE>
<FLAG>BUSINESS COMMENT</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>976306300</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE City will be on tenterhooks this morning as it awaits confirmation
that Hutchison Telecom will float the Orange mobile phone network in
perhaps six months time.
Almost all the attention is understandably focused on British
Aerospace, which holds a minority 31.5% stake. BAe's shares spurted
ahead another 36p to 735p yesterday to make a total gain of 85p since
the good half-time figures last Thursday, boosting the overall market
capitalisation to #3600m.
An Orange market value of well over #2000m is on the cards, which
would be worth perhaps #750m to BAe. After a slow start the system now
has more than 230,000 subscribers. That may be small beer compared with
the two million of Vodafone -- Cellnet has a similar number -- but
thanks to later start-up, its system is entirely digital and has more
capacity than the now somewhat dated analogue technology of its two
giant rivals.
So far Orange has invested about #450m and it is thought that by the
time the remaining gaps in the system are filled the overall bill will
rise to almost #1200m. BAe has so far lent about #300m towards the
development but telecoms cannot be seen as a core actvity for the
aerospace group, which in the last couple of years has found itself
piloted more surely than at any time in its existence by chief executive
Dick Evans.
Hence the decision to have a public flotation with Goldman Sachs and
Kleinwort Benson appointed as advisors.
Yesterday morning Hutchison said an anouncement would be made in the
afternoon but that was postponed -- presumably until today.
The holding will be a useful defensive weapon in the armoury that BAe
needs to build up against the probable bid from GEC, although there will
in all likelihood be a breathing space until the Weinstock succession
problem has been resolved and a new managing director who has the
support of the whole GEC board has been installed.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950919-000011</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950919-000011</DOCID>
<DATE>950919</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Trust support</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>26</PAGE>
<FLAG>BUSINESS COMMENT</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>976306301</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE investment trust sector has seen a huge expansion in the number of
companies quoted. The 1993 market upsurge and a general re-rating of
trusts spawned a multitude of specialists covering virtually every
equity market in the world from Chile to Korea and several market
sectors like environmental and pharmaceutical shares.
It was not so long ago that the old generalist trusts were widely
considered obsolete and only fit for breaking up so that investors could
put their money in the real growth stories of tomorrow. Trusts like
Alliance and its sister Second Alliance have seen many investment
fashions come and go. After all they have been in existence since the
1880s.
What they and others like them have tried to do is to provide
consistent sound performance not just over years but over decades. In
the past 10 years, each #1000 of assets in Second Alliance has increased
to #3600 and #1000 invested 10 years ago would now be worth #4530 if
income was reinvested. These results were about in line with the average
for its sector.
The performance compares favourably with most other trusts which go
back that far, with the exception of the Far Eastern specialists which
exclude Japan.
No serious investor is going to risk putting a high proportion of his
funds into a single country or even a single geographical region. He
will want a spread which is exactly what the generalists provide, though
admittedly they do have a bias towards the UK and US, which reflects the
need to supply a reasonable dividend income.
There is a lot to be said for investors and regular savers wishing to
put money into stocks markets for the long-term -- meaning five years
minimum -- simply to ignore all the competing investments and put their
money in the tried and tested formula of the general investment trusts.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950919-000012</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950919-000012</DOCID>
<DATE>950919</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Decision time</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>26</PAGE>
<FLAG>BUSINESS COMMENT</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>976306302</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE ScottishPower assault on Manweb has now entered the last lap and
the final bid and defence terms are on the table. So the time for a
decision has finally arrived for the latter's shareholders.
There certainly is merit in Manweb's objection that the price does not
contain a high enough premium for control or for the integration
benefits which ScottishPower will derive.
Clearly the price cannot fully reflect these factors or there would be
little point making the bid in the first place. The point is how long it
might take for Manweb shares to surpass the value of the bid should the
group remain independent.
The defence package from Manweb is said to be worth 926p but this
depends on the rump share price being 376p, based on a comparison with
Norweb. However, whether they would command a similar rating is
uncertain to say the least given that Manweb's financial position would
look even more stretched.
Faced with this doubt and the certainty of a capital gain by accepting
the revised bid terms, the latter look the best choice. The whole affair
leaves a slightly unpleasant taste in the mouth though. The other bids
in the sector have all been agreed deals and ScottishPower's aggressive
approach does indeed smack of an attempt to secure control of one of the
weaker English distributors on the cheap.
At least an attempt at an agreed deal could have been made before the
first full onslaught, which is bound to have upset Manweb employees,
with whom ScottishPower will have to work if it wins the battle. It is
also likely to have caused some ill-will among customers. The
contemptuous dismissal of the abilities of Manweb's top management can
only have made them more determined to fight to the bitter end. The
small extra expense of an agreed offer would have been well worth it.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
