<DOCNO>GH950919-000014</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950919-000014</DOCID>
<DATE>950919</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Computer help centre expands</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>26</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976306304</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
GREENOCK is to become a unique computer help centre for the whole of
Europe, it was revealed yesterday. And it will mean 200 new jobs as
computer giant IBM expands its customer services unit.
By the end of next year, people with computer problems throughout
Europe will receive help from multi-lingual experts sitting in Greenock.
State of the art technology will divert auser in difficulties to a
fluent speaker of his or her native language.
IBM Help Centre manager Paul McNutt said people phoning 24 hours a
day, 365 days a year would never suspect they were calling abroad. ''We
can take calls from parts of Europe and transfer them here and the
object is the customer does not know that. For the price of a local call
it is tranferred here to Scotland,'' he said.
So far this year computer users from across the UK, Ireland,
Switzerland, Belgium, Luxembourg and France have been slotted into the
centralised system. The Netherlands, Spain and Austria will join before
December, while Germany, Italy and Portugal are further down the line.
David Winn, IBM's general manager for Europe, the Middle East and
Africa, said Greenock had been selected because it already had a
manufacturing base employing 3000 people. This would allow a greater
concentration of expertise than if IBM employees were scattered in
pockets across Europe.
Mr Winn revealed that 70% of the operators would come from Scotland
and hopefully 40% would be from the local area. ''The reason we are
taking the trouble -- because it is trouble to run a multi-language
helpline -- is because of the better service we can provide.''
On average, he said, 1000 calls were already being received every day
which should increase to around 3000 once the service is fully
operational. Mr McNutt said it was possible IBM would take on more
employees in the future.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
