<DOCNO>GH950919-000016</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950919-000016</DOCID>
<DATE>950919</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Burns needs his striking partnership up front</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>IAN PAUL</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>36</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976306306</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MAYBE it will turn out to have been a forlorn wish but Tommy Burns was
entitled to declare his hope that the first Old Firm meeting of the
season will be a game of good, entertaining football.
''Rangers have some super players and so do we,'' he said, ''I would
like to think we could entertain the fans. They pay so much money
nowadays and incur such heavy travelling costs that they deserve to see
something special. Our intention this season certainly is to give them
that.''
He was not alone in suggesting that the baddest game in town might,
for a change, be a goodie. His experienced international defender, Tommy
Boyd, thought so, too. ''It should be an open game, with plenty of good
football. There is plenty of quality in both teams. It can be too hectic
at times, and no doubt the pace will be the usual, but there is talent
in the sides and they could make it an entertaining night.''
Both Celtic men fervently want victory first and foremost, like every
Parkhead or Ibrox sympathiser, but they would rather like it to be
accompanied by a performance which pleases the eye. They can be sure
Rangers would feel the same but on all known track records this is not a
likely bonus.
Burns has to make decisions about his line-up this morning. Three
players have to be assessed before the team is picked. All three --
Pierre van Hooydonk, Phil O'Donnell and Andreas Thom -- will play if
they are ready, and Burns is hopeful all of them will get clearance to
take part.
O'Donnell, scorer of the goal in the 1-1 draw with Motherwell,
suffered what he called a ''niggle'' near the end but seemed confident
enough he would be fit to play. Van Hooydonk missed that game and the
midweek trip to Batumi after having been injured against Aberdeen last
Sunday, while Thom was left out of Saturday's side because of a knock.
Ideally, Burns would want the two foreigners up front, considering how
well they have combined to date, but he has the experienced Andy Walker
ready to carry on if required. He also has John Hughes back after
suspension ready to sample his first Old Firm match, like Thom, if he is
fit.
If O'Donnell is OK, Burns may consider putting Paul McStay on the
bench, and bringing him on later. However, McStay made such a pleasing
return after an absence of four months that the chances are the manager
will prefer to see him on from the start.
McStay and his team mates have been relishing the prospect of the
first meeting with Rangers at the revamped Parkhead this season, but
they had anticipated it being the league match a week on Saturday. Now
it is a play-to-the-finish Coca Cola Cup, quarter-final 10 days earlier.
Burns pointed out that his team were said to be going through a test
at Pittodrie last week, again against Batumi and then, after their
travelling marathon, against Motherwell. They won two and drew won, with
the manager pleased with their efforts all through.
Other than score more goals, he didn't think his team could have
played any better than they did in the first half against Motherwell,
considering the week they had tackled, but admitted that the two missing
men, van Hooydonk and Thom, might have provided the goals.
O'Donnell has played in three Old Firm games, and experienced every
outcome, one loss, one draw and one win. His advice to the newcomers
would be to expect an incredible noise, a hectic pace and an almost
indescribable 90 minutes (or more).
''I thoroughly enjoyed them, even although we lost the first but it is
very hard to tell anyone else what it is like. This time it is at our
new stadium, it is a cup quarter final, and there are a lot of new
players.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950919-000017</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950919-000017</DOCID>
<DATE>950919</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Old Firm expect quality to be streets ahead. No worry as Gascoigne will be in from the start</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>KEN GALLACHER CHIEF FOOTBALL WRITER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>36</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976306307</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
PAUL Gascoigne will play for Rangers from the start in his first Old
Firm game at the new Celtic Park tonight.
And no one at Ibrox yesterday was worrying over either his ability or
his temperament as they prepared for the Coca Cola Cup quarter-final.
Obviously, it was manager Walter Smith who declared that Gascoigne,
the supposed enfant terrible of the game, would be making his Old Firm
debut. And it was Smith, as well as a veteran of these matches, Ally
McCoist, who made little of the problems which might afflict a player on
such occasions.
Said Smith: ''Paul Gascoigne will play from the start of the game and
I have absolutely no worries about that. The only concerns any of us
have is the amount of newspaper attention which is devoted to this one
player.
''After three months of that kind of coverage, we would surely all
hope that he can be judged solely about what happens on the field. As
far as giving advice to players new to this game and its atmosphere, I
leave that to the lads who have experienced it all before.''
McCoist clearly is one who has tasted the unique atmosphere more than
most, and he had his own words on the Gascoigne adventure.
''He has gone through Rome derby games, all kinds of other big
matches, so what, really, can we tell him?
''All I would say is that there is no way at all we would want to curb
him. We don't want to put the reins on him because he was brought to
this club to express himself, and if we want to have the kind of
expression he can bring, then we let him show it.''
While Smith was happy to say that Gascoigne would begin the game, he
would go no further on his team selection. He did say that the 14
players on duty at Falkirk at the weekend, when Rangers won, would all
be listed and he added Stephen Wright and Brian Laudrup to his list.
He also made the point that he had no injury worries left after that
last game, and the only ones which did still concern him were those
long-term blows which Rangers have already suffered this season.
Smith did add: ''The first Old Firm game of the season is always
important -- though not always as decisive as the supporters of each
team might think. They look on it as being a guide to how their team
will do for the rest of the season, but it does not always work out that
way.
''This one is slightly different in any case because it is a one-off
cup game, and we both realise that. It will be interesting to get back
to Parkhead and see what the atmosphere is like but, then, there is
always an atmosphere about this game. No one can ever deny that.
''That is what makes the game what it is. I have seen seasoned
international players find this game hard to handle. It all depends on
how you approach it. We want to go into it in the right manner.''
His players seem to feel the same way. Goalkeeper Andy Goram, for
example, insisted yesterday: ''We have to go there looking for a win
but, then, that is always the way in these games. If you go to Parkhead
with a negative outlook, then you might come back with a negative
result. There is no way that we will look at this game in any other way
but a positive one.''
Goram is so positive about everything that he is already promising to
take any deciding penalty kick if that is called for.
''I have done it before,'' he remembers. ''I did it for Hibs against
Clydebank the first year I joined them. It went to a shoot-out and I
took the one which won the game. I'd be happy enough to do that again.
It would not worry me at all.''
Whether it goes that distance or not will be decided tonight. Whether
the new-look Parkhead will give Celtic an added edge will also go under
the Old Firm microscope.
Said McCoist: ''I hear it is very impressive, but I have to say that I
am happy to be back there. It was never quite the same playing Celtic on
league business at Hampden. There wasn't the same feeling about it.''
What the irrepressible Ibrox striker did not add was that Rangers'
record on their oldest rivals' ground is better than it has been at
Ibrox in recent years. That may have influenced his thinking.
</TEXT>
