<DATE>950919</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Bryant in bearish mood</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ANDREW WILSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>26</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976306308</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
NO-ONE loves housebuilders at present and there is little prospect of
any improvement in sentiment until the Budget in November. That may
reveal some goodies to encourage house purchase -- or it might not.
Certainly Midlands-based Bryant Group was bearish yesterday, with
chief executive Andrew MacKenzie saying that in the three months to
August reservations were 15% down on a year earlier.
However, one saving grace has been the Scottish operations which, in
their first full year, saw sales of 150 units at an average price of
#120,000. That compares with a group total 15% higher at 3735 units
sold, with the average price almost 13% greater at #107,000 as Bryant
moved further up market. The result is a UK average of around #110,000.
Scottish sales in the current year are expected to advance to about
180 units and sites are being developed at Milnagavie, Newton Mearns and
Paisley in the West, in addition to the two more mature Edinburgh
operations, one overlooking the Pentlands, the other in Morningside.
Chairman Colin Hope added that since December there had been a
significant loss of consumer confidence and there had been another
setback since June as fears over job security increased while potential
buyers held back for the Budget.
In the year to May pre-tax profits rose 25% to #45.8m, with overall
house margins actually showing a small improvement to 11.5%. The second
half was helped by the first downward renegotiations of building
materials prices. The dividend total has been marginally increased to
5.05p but the final has been only maintained -- at 3.6p -- in view of
the future uncertainty and the desire to keep a cover of two times.
The construction side saw its profits dip #3.1m to #2.5m, but there
were no exceptional settlements this year and it has a good order book.
There is some #12m still to come from the now terminated property
activities.
The shares fell 8p to 109p where they yield 5.8%.
