<DATE>950919</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Faldo's still in good nick, says Monty</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>36</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976306309</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
COLIN Montgomerie had a message for Europe's Ryder Cup fans as
Concorde flew into Rochester, New York, yesterday: ''Don't worry about
Nick Faldo.'' The Englishman, who finished outside the top 20 in all
four majors this season, and a fortnight ago pulled out of the Lancome
Trophy in Paris with wrist trouble, has been in America for the past
week working on his game with coach David Leadbetter.
However, before he linked up with the rest of the side at Oak Hill
amid reports that his marriage is on the rocks, Faldo received a vote of
confidence from the man he is expected to partner again on Friday and
Saturday.
Montgomerie said: ''There are no worries about Nick Faldo as regards
the Ryder Cup. No worries. There's more pressure in the Cup than any
other tournament, even the majors, and Nick handles pressure better than
anybody I've ever seen.
''When Nick and I were put together at The Belfry two years ago, he
played terrific. He kept the whole team together. He was the most
experienced one of the whole lot. And that will be the same again this
time. He is an excellent partner and I'm happy for him to take control
of the partnership again.
''There'll be pressure on us because we'll be expected to win, but
that's okay. I'll play my stuff and him playing his normal game will be
fine by me.
''In foursomes play, I think we are as strong as anyone because we
play that type of game. In four-balls we're possibly not as strong, but
we can get it round.''
Montgomerie accepts that much is expected of him this week. He may
have lost the European No.1 spot when Sam Torrance lifted the British
Masters on Sundaty, but it is only a month ago that he lost a play-off
for the US PGA championship and he has won twice since then.
''This Ryder Cup is different for me,'' said the 32-year-old Scot,
about to collect his third cap.
''The first away and the first at home are daunting, but now I'm in a
position where I'm one of the players we're looking to get some points.
''Say I play five times, then I've got to be looking at three points
minimum for it to be a good Ryder Cup for me.
''I think that it's more of a situation this time where the Americans
know they're going to be in a tough match if they are drawn against me.
''They know that, because of my consistency, nobody should get an easy
game. I'm not going to throw anything away. I'll always be there.
''I'm a gritty competitor and I'm determined to do well, not just for
myself, but for the team. I look forward to it. It's a great
challenge.''
The Montgomerie-Faldo partnership -- they won two, halved one and lost
one last time -- is the only one that can be safely predicted.
Captain Bernard Gallacher has to decide who to put with Seve
Ballesteros now that Jose Maria Olazabal has withdrawn injured, but Ian
Woosnam's late call-up as replacement could see him reunited with
Bernhard Langer. They won twice as foursomes partners two years ago.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
