<DATE>950919</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Second Alliance warning</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>IAN MCCONNELL</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>26</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976306310</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
DUNDEE-based Second Alliance Trust believes sterling could plunge on
the foreign exchanges if the Conservatives try to boost their political
standing with swingeing tax cuts in November's Budget.
Second Alliance managing director Gavin Suggett, who also heads the
#1100m Alliance investment trust, the UK's third largest, believes there
may be some ''subtle'' tax cuts in the Budget but does not think the
Tories can give very much away. He said: ''I think we would be upset if
there were big giveaways.
''Nobody can escape the markets these days. If it looks like the
shackles are coming off, you will see the effect on the pound very
quickly.''
Treasury Chief Secretary William Waldegrave has pledged that the
Government will not abandon its commitment to long-term fiscal
discipline for short-term political advantage.
The powerful performance of major world stock markets in recent months
enabled Second Alliance's 10.2% increase in net asset value to 1918p
during the year to end-July, a record year-end valuation.
Net asset value was down 4% at the halfway stage, pretty much in line
with the All-Share index. The #369m fund's buoyant full-year performance
was bang in line with that of the resurgent All-Share.
However, Second Alliance's North American holdings advanced only 13%,
significantly adrift of the 23% gain posted by the Standard &amp; Poor's
Composite Index. North America accounts for 24% of the fund.
Second Alliance's total dividend is 9.5% higher at 46p, after a final
payout of 32p.
Earnings per share rose 13.5% to 48.2p, although some of this increase
was the result of exceptional payouts from cash-rich UK companies, such
as major holding Great Universal Stores.
Although the underlying revenue trend remains positive, Second
Alliance said shareholders should not expect a repetition of last year's
13.5% growth rate in the current 12 months.
Second Alliance shares, which yesterday added 4p to 1818p, are trading
at a 5% discount to net asset value.
