<HEADLINE>Stirling ready for their glamour match. Barbarians will present a stern test for County</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DEREK DOUGLAS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>35</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976306311</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Barbarians will be at the gates of Stirling next week, but for
once they will be welcome guests as champions Stirling County entertain
the glamourous invitation side for a rare and Royal encounter with a
Scottish club.
Retired Scotland captain Gavin Hastings will lead the Baa-Baas who
include five members of the Scotland World Cup squad. Craig Chalmers,
Bryan Redpath, Eric Peters, Iain Morrison, and Cameron Glasgow are the
Scots in the party named yesterday, although there is an immediate
injury doubt over Glasgow.
The side, which will provide a stern test for County, also includes
four Irishmen, three Welshmen, an Englishman, and the Canadian flanker,
Al Charron.
Glasgow, who damaged ankle ligaments while bowling in the cricket nets
at the end of the summer, has not played since the start of the season.
Yesterday, Heriot's coach John Foster said that 10 days ago, when
presumably the team was selected, Glasgow had been making good progress,
but the recovery had not gone as well as expected.
''I'd love to have him back in our side and I would be delighted if he
were to be playing for the Barbarians next week, but I can't see it,''
said Foster.
The game is being staged at Forthbank Stadium on Tuesday in the
presence of SRU Patron the Princess Royal, and as a taster for the main
event the Stirling County under-18 side will play Gordonstoun School,
which will be captained by the Princess Royal's son, Peter Phillips.
The normal Forthbank capacity of 4000 is to be boosted by an extra
2000 for the day by means of extra seating.
The match, which is being backed by the Barbarians' regular sponsor,
Scottish Amicable, represents only the third time -- seven-a-side
appearances excepted -- that the Baa-Baas have played a Scottish club
side, the only other occasions on which they have ventured north of the
Border on club business being for celebration games against Glasgow
Academicals and Melrose.
The sponsors are to extend what is termed the Amicable Gesture for the
day. Each Barbarians' try raises #300 for their opponent's national
youth coaching programme, and the home unions have already benefited to
the tune of #61,200. On Tuesday, the facility has been widened to
provide a similar amount for each try scored by County, the proceeds
going to the Bridgehaugh youth programme.
Barbarians' president, Mickey Steele-Bodger, said yesterday the club
had been delighted to accept the invitation, he added with a wry grin
and with reference to Kenny Logan's spasmodic appearances in the
tabloids, he assumed that County's international winger would be given
the day off because of all his ''night work.''
''Sorry Kenny,'' said Steele-Bodger to the listening Logan, ''news
travels fast and far.''
The president said that even with the game on the brink of
professionalism he saw no reason why the future of the Barbarians should
be placed in jeopardy. ''I don't think that anybody really knows where
the game is going, but I see no reason other than to be optimistic about
the future role of the Barbarians,'' he said.
Stirling County also announced their team for the show game, and
injured scrum half Kenny Harper reappears in place of Murray Fraser.
Coach Brian Edwards said it was the team which would take the field
against Boroughmuir on Saturday as the champions seek to set to rights
their record of three premiership defeats in four outings.
''The players have had one eye on this game since the start of the
season,'' he said. ''It's a big day not just for us but for the
development of rugby in this area. Maybe at the back of their minds the
players have been keen not to get injured before such a big show game.
''The problem for us has been getting the players' focus back to where
it was last season. Hopefully on Saturday and especially against the
Barbarians, we can use the occasion as a springboard to get us back up
there challenging for the title.''
Stirling County -- C M Sangster; A S M Turner, I C Jardine, N M
McGrandles, K M Logan; M McKenzie, K Harper; J J Manson, K D McKenzie, G
B Robertson, M Norval, J S Hamilton, D Elliot, J Brough, B Ireland.
Replacements -- A M Fraser, J Gibson, G Flockhart.
Barbarians -- A G Hastings (Watsonians and Scotland); S P Geoghegan
(Bath, Ireland), J Bell (Northampton, Ireland), G Thomas (Bridgend,
Wales), I C Glasgow (Heriot's FP); C M Chalmers, B W Redpath (both
Melrose, Scotland); K Colclough (Swansea), T J Kingston (Dolphin,
Ireland), G F Halpin (London Irish, Ireland), P Arnold (Swansea, Wales),
S D Shaw (Bristol), A J Sharron (Ottowa Irish, Canada), D W Peters
(Bath, Scotland), I R Morrison (London Scottish, Scotland).
* THE eight clubs in Premiership Divisions I and 2 meet at Murrayfield
tonight behind closed doors in an attempt to hammer out guidelines for a
professional game.
The fact that, on a show of hands, all 102 clubs in membership of the
Union voted on Friday night for a non-binding moratorium on payments to
players at all but national squad level, need not necessarily mean that
the country's top clubs will be of a similar mind.
Certainly, with the ambitious Watsonians club, for one, indicating
that they are at variance with the Union on the the recommendation that
Scotland be represented in next season's European championship by
districts and not clubs, it would, perhaps, be not too wide of the mark
to suggest that player-payment could be on the Myreside agenda.
</TEXT>
