<DOCNO>GH950919-000022</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950919-000022</DOCID>
<DATE>950919</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Walton is target</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>35</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976306312</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
PETER Walton, still recovering from a knee injury, has confirmed that
he has become the first Scottish player to sign for Newcastle Gosforth,
the English club that has been bought by millionaire businessman Sir
John Hall.
''I have been to see them and I have signed papers to be on the safe
side,'' said Walton. ''In England you get 120 days to make up your mind.
They have been in touch with me over the summer and I see no harm in
signing.''
Walton played for Gosforth before moving to Northampton but left the
club because of disagreements with the management, since replaced by
Hall. However, despite signing papers, Walton says he may play his rugby
in the Borders when he resumes playing, which should be at Christmas,
should the Newcastle deals fall through.
''I work beside Stuart Bennett, the Kelso wing, here in Wooler and I
would like to play for a Border club when I am fit,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950919-000023</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950919-000023</DOCID>
<DATE>950919</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Hasting's grid iron link</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>35</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976306313</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
FORMER Scotland and British Lions captain Gavin Hastings has joined up
with the Scottish Claymores American Football team.
However, he has no plans to be involved in a playing capacity and the
relationship will be strictly business.
Careful not to rule out the possibility of playing totally, Hastings,
nevertheless, underlined it would be a ''long shot'' given his
commitments business-wise and to Watsonians.
His new company, Hastings International Ltd, has been contracted by
the Claymores as management consultants to help talks with the Scottish
Rugby Union. ''This doesn't mean I'll be playing for the Claymores,''
said Hastings. ''All the discussions I've had in the last few weeks and
months have been on marketing and sponsorship.
''It's not something I've thought about at this stage, nor will I be
doing so in the next few weeks. Maybe I'm not ruling it out as I could
say definitely no at this stage and then in a year's time, or whatever,
things could change. But it would be a long shot if it happened.''
On a business front, he added: ''The Scottish Claymores are an
exciting client for me. They are a professional and innovative
organisation and I am looking forward to working with them in a positive
way.''
The Claymores' new general manager, Mike Keller, said: ''Gavin has
tremendous talents that will enhance the marketing and sales of the
Scottish Claymores. He is a natural bridge for the positive evolution of
the Scottish Claymores as well as for the World League of American
Football.''
</TEXT>
