<HEADLINE>Adam Smith reengineered for the nineties</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JIM WARNOCK</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>26</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>BOOK REVIEW</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>REVIEW</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976306314</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WHAT is the successful manager and entrepreneur in Scotland reading
these days? Whose business tips are helping him and her outperform their
colleagues on the way to the top of the executive pile?
Does such literary tic-tac really deliver the goods from the corporate
gods . . . or does entertainment value outstrip educational potential on
the best sellers list?
Stuart Paul, lecturer in Business Studies at Paisley University, will
turn the spotlight on the business book industry and discover what's
really worth reading.
Scotland's business elite will share with Herald readers the secrets
of their own bookshelves. We'll be looking at new releases, established
best-sellers, and maybe turning up a few surprises as well!
Today to launch the new series, Jim Warnock (left), group personnel
director with High Street retail giant John Menzies, takes a look at one
of the most influential books on the international market.
BUSINESS Process Reengineering appeared on the corporate agenda at the
start of the nineties and it has been Reengineering The Corporation*,
more than any other book, which has kept it there.
This year's publication of the paperback edition of what has become a
worldwide bestseller nudged me into re-assessing this well-written and
challenging book.
Michael Hammer and James Champy take issue with what they see as the
characteristics of many modern companies. They argue that most ''can
trace their work styles and organisational roots back to the
prototypical pin factory that Adam Smith described in The Wealth of
Nations''.
In the modern organisation, they contend that Smith's principle of the
division of labour and task specialisation results in work fragmentation
and complex management structures which, in turn, make co-ordination
difficult.
Too much company time and too many resources are today spent inside
the organisation and not enough dealing with external customers. The
result is inflexibility, unresponsiveness, the absence of customer focus
and a lack of innovation. ''Adam Smith's world and its way of doing
business are yesterday's paradigm.''
Hammer and Champy's prescription is reengineering -- ''the fundamental
rethinking and radical redesign of processes to achieve dramatic
improvement in critical contemporary measures of performance such as
cost, service or speed''. To meet ever increasing customer demand for
more customised goods and services requires a process focus.
When it comes to reengineering there are no sacred cows and no
processes that should stand in the way of satisfying the customer. In
one of the most famous sections in the book, the authors argue that it
is about ''beginning again with a clean sheet of paper: it is about
rejecting conventional wisdom and assumptions of the past''.
Reengineering is not changing what is, but creating what isn't. When
British Airways declared itself the world's favourite airline in the
eighties, it faced the challenge of becoming a different company, not
just a better one. It turned its thinking and processes on their heads;
staff were energised with a new vision, old ways scattered to the winds.
The same held true when Europcar decided to become the most
user-friendly and efficient rental car company in Europe and not an
omnipresent one. And when Haagen Dazs chose to make a visit to its
European ice-cream shops an exciting experience, the company did not
just change what it did or how work got done, it also had to adjust all
the well entrenched assumptions on which its previous decisions and
actions were based.
So what are the characteristics of reengineering? They include
multi-skilling jobs; giving individual employees more authority to take
decisions; replacing more traditional functional teams with process
teams, and managers taking on more of a coaching as opposed to a
supervisory role.
To reengineer successfully, you need to have in place employees who,
above all else, are flexible enough to grapple with new directions of
the business.
Why has reengineering attracted so much interest not only in America
but also in the UK? There are two main reasons: the inability of many
business processes to meet customer demands and satisfy needs, and
disappointment with the benefits stemming from the application of
large-scale IT systems in the eighties. It is not surprising
reengineering with its focus on processes as a powerful change mechanism
to align the operations of the business with customer demands, found a
ready audience.
A word of caution: senior management has frequently underestimated the
trauma -- internal conflict and soul searching -- that goes hand-in-hand
with the break from the present way of thinking and operating.
Unless managers orchestrate the creation of a new context, all the
work the organisation is doing to improve its competitiveness will at
worst yield unproductive effort and at best produce meaningful but
episodic change.
The attractiveness of this book is its conciseness, readability and
clarity. The case studies are well set out and relevant, though it is a
little short of ideas on how to tackle successfully the complexities of
culture change which come with reengineering. In my view it has not
dealt with the key issue of how to change well entrenched work
behaviour.
Nevertheless, it is a most interesting read. Companies cannot ignore
reengineering, lest they find themselves staring down the barrel of a
competitor's superior processes.
* Reengineering The Corporation, Michael Hammer and James Champy,
#9.99
