<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950919-000029</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950919-000029</DOCID>
<DATE>950919</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Politicians warned over farm policy</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ROY GREGOR</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>29</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976306319</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
POLITICIANS were warned yesterday that they must deliver a long-term
farm policy framework that would keep Britain's rural economy as a major
and sustainable wealth generator.
At a fringe meeting during the Liberal Democrat Conference in Glasgow,
John Ross, president of the National Farmers' Union of Scotland, said
that a freer global market would occur in the years ahead but in
Scotland the rural and environmental role of hill farming was crucially
underpinned by hill compensatory payments.
''This sort of support is simply not negotiable if we expect to keep a
rural population in Scotland's less-favoured areas.'''
He pointed out that hill and lowground farming were interdependent and
that ''simplistic targeting of aid is not a sensible option for UK
agriculture''.
Ben Gill, deputy president of the NFU of England and Wales, said there
was a risk of ingorning the role and value of the agricultural industry
when the debate turned to landscapes and wildlife habitats.
''People in rural areas are in danger of becoming threatened
species,'' he said. ''In acknowledging the wider agenda we must not
forget the continuing importance of agriculture in providing good
quality food.
''Farming and its associated activities play a crucially important
economic and social role. Whatever the direction of agricultural policy,
a key role of farming and farmers will continue to be the creation and
management of a working countryside.''
Paul Tyler, MP for North Cornwall, said there was a growing problem of
leisure and access demands and that agricultural policies must ensure
farmers had a return on their efforts to meet these demands. He said
there should be no ''right to roam'' policy and farmers should be
recompensed for any increased costs in managing access land.
Scottish Liberal Democrat leader Jim Wallace MP suggested that in
Scotland the Government had underspent #10.5m on payments for
environmentally-sensitive areas and had overlooked the social objectives
that farmers play.
Mr Ross said the Common Agricultural Policy had coped with the
over-supply situation and added: ''There will continue to be
agricultural support in the foreseeable future. Farmers in remote areas
cannot survive on environmental support.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950919-000030</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950919-000030</DOCID>
<DATE>950919</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Walker drops in to calm storm</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>35</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976306320</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
JACK Walker, Blackburn Rovers' millionaire owner, will fly in from his
home in Jersey to link up with the Blackburn Rovers' management team at
Swindon tomorrow for the Coca-Cola Cup second round clash.
But the Premiership champions have dismissed suggestions that a
''crisis meeting'' had been planned amid mounting speculation that Kenny
Dalglish could be about to leave Ewood Park.
Blackburn have been blasted from all directions, with pundits and
rival managers among their fiercest critics after four defeats in six
League games. But assistant manager Tony Parkes yesterday retorted: ''We
have seen it and read it, but, if anything, it could have the reverse
effect -- it could just fuel our fire.
''We are only six games into the season and there is no great
depression on the training ground. We have to be big enough to take the
stick and strong enough to overcome it. It's a matter of us getting our
house in order as quickly as possible and the players are just as
determined.''
Meanwhile, Rovers midfield player Mark Atkins could be offered the
chance to join Wolves within the next few days. Atkins has been a
potential target for manager Graham Taylor for several months.
The former Scunthorpe defender, who cost Rovers just #45,000 seven
seasons ago, now commands a fee of around #1.5m.
* MORTON are to appeal to FIFA to help acquire clearance for Cameroon
keeper Andre Boe. The Greenock club's manager, Allan McGraw, said:
''Every day Andre comes in and asks if we have heard anything.
''He is training hard but without international clearance he cannot
play even in our reserves. What is even more worrying is that he cannot
earn his living. The SFA have done everything possible and I know they
have faxed and phoned the Cameroons asking for a clearance
certificate.''
Boe has asked for political asylum in Britain and his request is at
present in front of the authorities.
* TOMMY Svensson, who guided Sweden to third place in the 1994 World
Cup, has agreed to extend his contract as national coach until the end
of 1998.
</TEXT>
