<DOCNO>GH950919-000032</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950919-000032</DOCID>
<DATE>950919</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Anglia purchase pays off for MAI as financial services division suffers</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CHRISTOPHER SIMS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>25</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS TABLE</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976306322</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MAI'S purchase of Anglia Television 18 months ago has proved well
timed in view of a downturn in its money broking business.
Profits from the latter tumbled 30% to #42.9m in the year to June, but
media profits, taking in a full year from Anglia, came to #43.7m. The
overall result was that the group pre-tax figure was 20% ahead at
#115.6m before exceptionals. Dividends are raised by 12% to 8.7p after a
final of 6.7p. MAI points out that dividends have increased by 12%
compound over the past five years.
Anglia performed strongly, helped by cost-cutting, with employee
numbers down a third to about 400, and integration of MAI's other
franchise, Meridian.
The acquisition brought in other interesting media investments such as
TSMS which handles airtime sales for Grampian, Scottish and other
television companies, and Village Roadshow, an Australian cinemas and
theme parks company which is expanding aggressively into the Asia
Pacific region.
The Anglia purchase was considered quite pricey at the time but cash
and other assets accounted for half the #290m purchase cost.
MAI bought Pearson's 15% stake in Yorkshire Tyne-Tees and the
investment is now worth more than it cost. MAI managing director Lord
Hollick reckons the company is still undervalued as it has the highest
operational gearing of all the television companies and has a very
valuable library. He would consider bidding for the whole company if the
restrictive ownership rules were relaxed, which is quite likely.
He is keen to expand MAI's media business and has some #200m available
for this. He is more interested in starting new ventures in-house or
with partners than in major acquisitions. He is keen on satellite
broadcasting and on expanding production interests for television and
new media such as CD-ROM, as well as providing on-line services through
the Internet.
Moneybroking was hit by lower volumes as a result of the 1994 bear
market in bonds but maintained its profits in the second half after
cost-cutting and expansion into Japanese fixed-interest markets.
The opinion research operation, which includes leading pollsters NOP
in the UK and MRI in the US, saw profits rise 20% to #13m, with customer
satisfaction surveys a growth area.
MAI chairman Sir James McKinnon said the current year had started
satisfactorily and that many new investment and profit opportunities
were opening up.
MAI shares gained 2p to 298p and are rated below purer media stocks on
account of the money-broking business, though they are gradually being
re-rated.
FACT FILE
......................1994-95....1993-94
Turnover..............#813m......#710m
Pre-tax profit........#115.6m....#96.7m
EPS...................20.1p......18.4p
Dividend..............8.7p.......7.8p
</TEXT>
