<HEADLINE>Maradona kicks off new football union</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>35</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976306323</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
DIEGO Maradona, backed by some of the world's leading footballers --
including Manchester United's Eric Cantona -- yesterday announced the
creation of a world footballers' union.
Maradona -- who was sent home in disgrace after having failed a dope
test at USA '94 -- and Cantona, whose ban for attacking a fan at Crystal
Palace ends on October 1, were joined by Italy's Gianluca Vialli,
Brazil's Rai, Michael Rummenigge, of Germany, Sweden's Tomas Brolin, and
Abedi Pele of Ghana at the launch in Paris.
A statement issued on behalf of the players read: ''The International
Association of Professional Footballers has been created to promote and
safeguard the interests of all professional footballers in the whole
world at the professional, as well as social, level.''
</TEXT>
