<DOCID>GH950919-000035</DOCID>
<DATE>950919</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Playing the power game. ScottishPower raises Manweb bid to #1100m</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ROBERT POWELL</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>25</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976306325</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SCOTTISHPOWER has raised its hostile bid for Manweb by a modest #60m
to #1100m, further weighting the scales that were already tipping in its
favour.
''We think this is a realistic price to win,'' said chief executive
Ian Robinson as ScottishPower bought a further 2.5 million Manweb shares
on the open market, taking its overall stake in the company to 17.25%.
Manweb predictably rejected the revised offer, describing it as
''mean'', but City analysts said it should be enough to clinch the deal.
''They are pitching it rather finely,'' said Andrew Wright, an
electricity analyst at Smith New Court in London, ''but I think it has
got a good chance of succeeding.''
The revised offer narrows a price gap that had opened up between
ScottishPower's main shares-plus-cash offer and its all-cash
alternative.
The Glasgow-based company added 10p to its main shares-plus-cash
offer, but increased the all-cash alternative by 75p.
For good measure, it also promised a 13.6% increase in the dividend
for the current financial year to 15.5p per share, providing the bid is
successful.
Bill McCall, at Tilney in Edinburgh, described the latest offer as ''a
goodwill gesture'' rather than a substantial improvement of terms.
But he was confident that Manweb was now in the bag. ''I think it's
about as far as they have to go,'' he said. ''The film is coming to an
end and you can virtually roll the credits on it.''
ScottishPower announced the improved offer, which it described as
final, after deciding that a fresh attempt to start talks with the
Manweb board at the weekend was getting nowhere.
Manweb said it was ''mean by comparison with most other recommended
offers in the sector'' and rejected it out of hand.
ScottishPower may only modify the terms of its latest offer if a rival
bidder emerges for the Chester-based company which distributes
electricity in Merseyside and North Wales.
But with six regional electricity companies still untouched by the
takeover frenzy in the privatised utilities sector, a contest for Manweb
is unlikely.
Manweb shareholders must, therefore, decide by October 6 whether to
accept the ScottishPower terms that are now on the table.
Beneath the argument over Manweb's real value lies a more fundamental
debate over the strategy necessary to make it a successful company in
the long term.
ScottishPower says the way ahead is to combine power generation with
electricity distribution and to diversify into new areas such as gas
supply and telecommunications.
Manweb, on the other hand, wants to concentrate on its core activity
of electricity distribution, shedding all other commercial interests.
ScottishPower says that approach offers limited potential for
long-term growth and the signs are that most investors agree.
Manweb shares came under heavy selling pressure yesterday and closed
down 3p at 1007p after nearly 6.5 million changed hands.
ScottishPower meanwhile fell 6p to 365p as investors factored the cost
of the revised bid and the dividend forecast into their earnings
expectations.
ScottishPower's is now offering #61.70 in cash, up from #60.70
previously, and 11 ScottishPower shares for every 10 Manweb shares.
In view of yesterday's fall in ScottishPower's own share price, this
revised offer is currently worth 1018[1/2]p per Manweb share -- only
3[1/2]p more than the ScottishPower's original offer was worth on
Friday.
But the all-cash alternative has been raised to 990p from 915p.
The result is a narrowing of the gap which had opened up between the
two offers since ScottishPower launched its bid for Manweb on July 24.
A steady rise in ScottishPower shares had increased the value of the
original shares-plus-cash offer by 9.3%, while the value of the
cash-only alternative remained static.
''They had to bring the cash offer into line. There was a gaping
differential that had almost reached 10%,'' said Mr McCall at Tilney.
ScottishPower said its improved offer for Manweb would not lead to any
increase in debt beyond the gearing level of 75% already forecast for
March 1996, assuming the takeover bid is successful.
ScottishPower finance director Ian Russell, described such a level of
gearing as ''reasonably prudent'' and said the debt level would be
progressively reduced after 1996..
ScottishPower had been expected to improve its offer this week
following the publication of a Manweb defence strategy on Friday which
promised shareholders a benefits package worth 550p per share.
</TEXT>
