<DOCNO>GH950919-000037</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950919-000037</DOCID>
<DATE>950919</DATE>
<HEADLINE>PowerGen secures agreements from Midlands Electricity</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>NICOLA REEVES</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>25</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976306327</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
POWERGEN confirmed yesterday that it is interested in securing its
future earnings by entering the electricity distribution market
alongside it existing generation activities.
It has secured a board recommendation from Midlands Electricity (MEB)
for its offer valuing the company at #1950m, inclusive of a special
dividend. The merged group will have a 15% share of the electricity
supply market and 20% of the power generation market.
The offer is 800p for each MEB share which, taken together with a
special dividend of 200p (net), values each share at 1000p. In addition,
certain shareholders will be entitled to reclaim the tax credit relating
to the special dividend, implying a gross value for them of 1050p a MEB
share. Shareholders will also be entitled to retain their right to the
final dividend of 20.45p (net) to be paid on October 2.
The 1000p-a-share offer represents a premium of 12% over the closing
price of shares on September 14, the last dealing day prior to the
announcement of a possible offer from PowerGen. MEB shares responded to
news of the agreed bid by jumping 33p to 971p, while PowerGen's rose
6[1/2]p to 585p.
Sir Colin Southgate, chairman of PowerGen, said the acquisition of MEB
''enables us to build here in the UK a dynamic, broadly-based energy
group positioned for the fully competitive domestic market post 1998''.
He added that the deal was in the best interests of shareholders, staff
and customers nationwide.
Bryan Townsend, chairman of MEB, said the board welcomed ''this
strategic and financial partnership which will create a strong
Midlands-based energy group with benefits and safeguards for both our
customers and staff''. MEB's domestic customers have seen their
electricity bills fall by 15% in real terms since 1991 with prices
frozen at their April 1994 level until March 1996.
If the offer goes ahead unconditionally, Mr Townsend will join the
board of PowerGen as a non-executive director, and Mike Hughes will join
the board of PowerGen with responsibility for distribution and supply.
In a busy day for the company, PowerGen also announced that it had
agreed to sell two of its power stations to Eastern Group, the
electricity company recently acquired by Hanson. Eastern is buying
2000MW of coal-fired plant, High Marnham and Drakelow C, for in excess
of #200m.
The disposal, at the behest of the industry regulator, Offer, is aimed
at opening up the power generation market to competition. It is expected
to reduce PowerGen's earnings per share by around 2% to 3% a year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950919-000038</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950919-000038</DOCID>
<DATE>950919</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Glamour event appears safe</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>34</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976306328</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IT looks as if the biggest basketball event to come to the UK so far,
the McDonald's Open Championship, which was scheduled to take place at
the London Arena next month, will go ahead following the near 2-1 vote
by NBA players in favour of keeping their union.
Although there is still the fear that the dissident players, including
Michael Jordan, and their agents, who were in favour of decertification
of the union, might go to court to appeal against the verdict, the size
of the vote, nearly a 90% turn-out, and the margin 226-134, means that
most favour an end to the dispute.
The owners are expected to approve the deal and lift their lock-out
which threatened the start of the regular season on November 3 as well
as the pre-season showcase event, which will feature the NBA champions,
the Houston Rockets, alongside the champions of Australia, Europe,
England, Italy and Israel from October 19 to 21.
Had the lock-out continued and the season been delayed, then the
McDonald's event was certain to have been cancelled.
There is another, happier, problem for the organisers following last
weekend and that is that the London Arena's 8000 capacity is quite
clearly not enough to cater for the growing basketball demand in this
country.
Over 12,000 spectators, easily a British crowd record, attended last
Saturday's Budweiser league match between the home club Manchester
Giants and London side Leopards at the Nynex Centre in Manchester.
The arena there can hold 16,000 and is one of the biggest in Europe
and, in retrospect, the NBA must be wishing that they had taken the
event to Manchester for its first visit to Britain.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950919-000039</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950919-000039</DOCID>
<DATE>950919</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Players must cope with partisan pressure of cup. Europe expects a serious contest</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>RAYMOND JACOBS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>34</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976306329</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A SCEPTIC looking towards the Ryder Cup match at Oak Hill this week
observed: ''Outside the gallery ropes it's a circus, inside them it's a
zoo.'' Both judgements are true, but only because over the last 12 years
Europe's biennial encounter with the United States has been transformed
from the meaningless to the meaningful.
The happy coincidence of a forceful captain in Tony Jacklin and the
simultaneous evolution of the Big Five -- Severiano Ballesteros, Berhard
Langer, Nick Faldo, Sandy Lyle, and Ian Woosnam -- meant that after a
one point loss in 1983, victories followed in 1985 and 1987 and a tie
two years after that.
The appeal of the match has been by no means diminished by Europe's
narrow defeats in the last two confrontations.
If anything, those results have stimulated interest even further, to
the extent that in the Rochester area hotel rooms, private houses and
the best restaurant tables are fully reserved.
Such devotion to the cause by golf followers has its oppressive effect
on the players, pressurised as never before by both supporters and
media. The teams prowl the fairways like felines in cages -- as if
either development could be mutually exclusive given the match's revival
as a serious contest.
Even the European players' caddies yesterday flew out with their
employers on Concorde to the upper New York State city, hitherto better
known as the headquarters of Kodak, Xerox and Bausch &amp; Lomb -- all very
different from the arrangements experienced by this observer on his
first Ryder Cup venture to America.
In 1971, a chartered Boeing 707 of British Caledonian Airways left
Gatwick Airport in broad daylight, but in the then sporting equivalent
of under the cover of darkness, so indifferent to the enterprise was the
world at large. Players, officials, supporters and media were at one in
the acceptance of another inevitable loss.
A respectable five-point defeat at the Old Warson Club in St Louis was
the outcome yet, paradoxically, a thoroughly relaxed time was had by
all. Another eight years would go by before continental professionals
were admitted to share in the ritual slaughter before the balance of
power began to shift.
In the four matches over which Jacklin presided he succeeded, by the
example and precept of his own career, in giving Europe's players a
deservedly greater conceit of themselves. Nothing but the best in
travel, clothing, and equipment would do. No harm in that.
Unfortunately, triumphalism went to Jacklin's head. The defeat in
1991, agonisingly down to Langer's miss from six feet -- the last stroke
on the last green in the last game -- was just about acceptable to
Jacklin. Not so two years later, when he was seen actively to be
counting to regain the captaincy from Bernard Gallacher.
The distortion of the match's ethos, most evident at Kiawah Island in
Corey Pavin's Desert Storm camouflage cap and the stridency of the
American support, extended to Jacklin's criticism of what he perceived
to be Gallacher's deferential attitude to the demands of Ballesteros and
Langer not to play on the second afternoon.
Their absence was widely held, particularly by the metropolitan media,
to be responsible for a three-point advantage being reduced to one with
the singles to play.
Conveniently overlooked was the fact that, in three of these games,
Barry Lane was three up with five to play, Woosnam two up with six to
play, and Costantino Rocca one up with two to play -- and none of them
won.
Of course, the mere fact of the match having become more closely
contested, and even the trophy itself having changed hands, has
intensified the attention of the golfing world at large. It would surely
erase the burden of captaincy if Gallacher were given a fair wind, short
of a total disaster.
At any rate, now that Jacklin is out of harm's way, securely ensconced
in his third career as a member of the US Senior tour, perhaps Gallacher
will be allowed to get on with the captaincy unencumbered with
gratuitous comments that do not stand reasonable examination.
Maybe in the home town of the flambouyant Walter Hagen, one of the
prime instigators of the match and six-times captain of the United
States team, a further degree of the unexpected will, with luck, invest
the result -- of course, in Europe's favour. The three US Opens played
at Oak Hill might represent a portent.
In 1956, Cary Middlecoff won his second title, beating Ben Hogan and
Julius Boros into second place and outlasting Australia's Peter Thomson
who led by two strokes after 36 holes.
In 1968, Lee Trevino gained his baptismal professional victory as the
first player to score below 70 in all four rounds, and in 1989 Curtis
Strange became the first since Hogan in 1951 to retain the title.
In the aftermath of his victory, Trevino was asked what he would do
with his $30,000 first prize, less than ten times this year's
equivalent, by the way. He replied: ''I'll buy the Alamo and give it
back to the Mexicans.'' The sooner the Ryder Cup is given back to the
game the better -- no matter the result.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
