<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950919-000041</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950919-000041</DOCID>
<DATE>950919</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Glory seekers flying a flag of convenience</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>IAN PAUL</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>34</PAGE>
<FLAG>IAN PAUL VIEW</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976306331</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IN a few days time, something unique in sport will be seen, the waving
of a blue flag decorated with a yellow circle of stars, signifying
Europe as an entity, as a community, as a team.
If it happens at any major sporting occasion other than the Ryder Cup
then it has escaped my notice and, in any case, it will not be hoisted
with greater depth of feeling than at Rochester, New York, when the old
US of A jingoists wind up the visitors from the other continent.
It is one of the most bizarre developments of the last decade or so
that patriotism, always presumed to be a country-bound emotion, has been
broadened effortlessly under the continental golf umbrella.
The major reason for this, if we have to be truthful, is that the
Brits suddenly saw a chance of beating the Yanks after decades of
drubbings. There ain't nothing like the smell of victory to warm the
patriotic breast and endear the flag, any flag, to the beholder.
At any rate, the wee blue flag with the starry circle has become
necessary luggage for Ryder Cup supporters from this country. It is the
case, too, that we willingly let Swedes, Italians et al have a shot if
they feel so inclined.
It may not be as wholeheartedly European as Edward Heath longed for
all those years ago, but it might be as good as he is ever going to get,
in any circumstances.
What has truly enlivened a hitherto rather unexciting competition is
the uncertainty of its outcome. Not for a dozen years has the match been
easy to predict and that has given it the stimulus that any serious
competition requires.
This remains the case this year, although there is a strong body of
opinion that says the US is in a stronger position than for some time.
Be that as it may, the fact is Europe badly needs to bring the old
trophy back this weekend.
There are a number of reasons for saying so, not least because the
home side has not had the Ryder Cup on display for four years. Victory
has eluded our lot in the nineties after the glorious revolution of the
eighties.
It is that statistic which has ominous undertones if we are to
maintain the prestige of the European Tour which reached top of the
world status in the previous decade.
Those were the days when Faldo, Ballesteros, Woosnam, Langer and Lyle
were among the best players in the world and, indeed, dominated the
major scene in a way Europeans had never done before.
When you add Seve's protege, Olazabal, the ever eager Sam Torrance and
the brilliant Colin Montgomerie, you can see why this was one
magnificent era for the continental tour.
Looking at them on the eve of the 1995 battle, you may find it
dificult to generate the same tingle of confidence.
Nick Faldo has been a long way short of the man who was unquestionably
the world's No.1 a couple of years ago. Even his switch to America to
play in consistently good conditions has not yet produced the standard
that was his hallmark. Putting seems to be letting him down more often
than in the good old days.
Seve, the great Seve, is only a shadow of the wonderful cavalier who
intimidated the Americans by dint of his immense will-to-win and self
confidence. He can still play a bit, but the certainty that he would
beat anybody they cared to stand on the first tee with him is no longer
there.
Ian Woosnam has been going through putting fluctuations like a man who
no longer knows what it is like to stand up and pop the ball in the
hole; Sandy Lyle is not even in the team and Berhard Langer, who is
suffering from a back injury, has lost his early season sparkle.
Olazabal had to withdraw injured.
Torrance has a poor record in the competition, but is in the best form
of his life, while the best and most consistent player in the squad is
Montgomerie.
The others -- Mark James, Costantino Rocca, David Gilford, Howard
Clark, Philip Walton and Per-Ulrik Johansson -- will win some, lose
some, but none of them is likely to be the inspirational leader that
Ballesteros or Faldo could be. That is why a resurgence of the Faldo
magnificence or the Ballesteros brilliance seems a pre-requisite of
European success.
What is for sure is that Europe badly needs this victory. The Tour has
been less than riveting for the past couple of years, the forays into
the great majors have not brought any success at all this year. In fact
Americans Corey Pavin (US Open), Ben Crenshaw (US Masters) and John Daly
(The Open) have won three of the four, with a regular on the US Tour,
Steve Elkington of Australia, taking the fourth, the US PGA title.
The US team does not even make room for Daly and, while it is not
packed with awesome superstars of the Nicklaus-Watson-Palmer school,
they are better than average and hungry to prove themselves better than
Europe.
Now you know why we need to wave those wee blue flags.
</TEXT>
