<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950919-000044</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950919-000044</DOCID>
<DATE>950919</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Draw is enough for Middlesex</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>34</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976306334</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MIDDLESEX duly sealed second place as the 1995 Britannic Assurance
County Championship programme reached a soggy conclusion yesterday.
Mike Gatting's side could only manage a draw with Somerset at Taunton,
where rain prevented an interesting finish. But they were already
guaranteed runners-up spot to Warwickshire because no play was possible
at Hove, where Northamptonshire, who must make do with third place, had
needed a win over Sussex.
Middlesex, chasing 350, were on 262 for six -- Paul Weekes made 79 and
Mark Ramprakash 73 -- when the match was brought to an early end.
Veteran off-spinner John Emburey, who is considering a string of
coaching offers for next season, was at the wicket for the final ball in
what could prove his last championship appearance for Middlesex.
Jeremy Hallett had earlier capitalised as the home side were fed quick
runs, reaching an undefeated 111 after resuming on 22.
The day's only other century maker was Paul Prichard, who took his
overnight 27 to 104 as Essex beat Yorkshire by 89 runs at Chelmsford to
clinch fifth spot.
Essex had started the day looking likely losers -- just 92 runs ahead
with five second-innings wickets left -- but were boosted by Prichard
and Robert Rollins, who added 77.
Peter Such then took five for 89 as Yorkshire, needing 275 to deny
their hosts a fifth successive championship win, were sent back for 185.
Lancashire finished a place above Middlesex, but their season finished
on a sour note with a final day collapse at Derby, where the home side
romped to a 282-run victory.
Skipper Mike Watkinson saw his side slump from 19 without loss to 155
all out in 100 minutes and admitted: ''That was a last day of the season
performance. There are no excuses -- it was terrible.''
Derbyshire's victory represented a fitting end to 13 seasons of
captaincy by Kim Barnett.
Surrey's disappointing season came to a frustrating end when rain
deprived them of a win over Hampshire.
Having declared overnight, 114 behind, Surrey bowled well to dismiss
Hampshire for 152 and create a target of 267.
They reached 175 for two with the help of an unbeaten 77 from Nadeem
Shahid and 75 from Darren Bicknell.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950919-000045</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950919-000045</DOCID>
<DATE>950919</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Nike soars</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>27</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976306335</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
NIKE profits soared in the latest quarter as worldwide orders for its
athletic footwear and apparel jumped to record levels.
Nike stock jumped $7.215 to $99.625 on the New York Stock Exchange
after the company reported the earnings, which were well above analysts'
highest expectations.
The company also announced a two-for-one stock split, which was
approved by shareholders at the annual meeting held at Nike's corporate
campus in suburban Portland.
''It's clear that we had a fantastic quarter and a fantastic last 12
months,'' Nike Chairman Philip Knight said in a conference call with
analysts and reporters.
Nike said its profits rose 55% to a record $164.8m, or $2.26 per
share, in its fiscal first quarter ended August 31, from $106m, or $1.43
per share, in last year's first quarter. Sales rose to $1610m from
$1170m.
Industry analysts said that even more impressive was Nike's report
that orders for its athletic footwear and apparel scheduled for delivery
between September and January rose 32% to a record $2300m.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950919-000046</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950919-000046</DOCID>
<DATE>950919</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Argument over relay medals</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DOUG GILLON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>34</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976306336</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SOUTH African officials said yesterday they may try to hold on to
All-Africa Games medals which they should forfeit because they were
achieved thanks to the efforts of a woman who tested positive for a
banned stimulant.
Karen Botha, wife of former Spingbok rugby captain Naas Botha, won
long jump bronze and ran in the heats of the sprint relay in Harare. The
South Africans took silver without Botha in the final before she was
found to have taken pain-killers containing dextropropoxyphene.
Under international rules her relay involvement disqualifies the whole
team. Despite this, officials say they may appeal against the ruling.
Maria Mutola, winner of the International Amateur Athletic Federation
overall grand prix title, was embraced by Mozambique president Joachim
Chissano after her 800m win in 2-01.06, while Nigerian Mary Onyali,
hinting at a doping witch-hunt against her compatriots, took the women's
200m in 22-75.
Nicholas Nyongera (Zimbabwe) won the men's marathon in 2-20-08, while
South African Jowaine Parrott won the women's marathon in 2-55-09.
Another South African, Okkert Brits, took the pole vault with 5.50m.
On the last day of the athletics programme, cross-country
internationalist Ruth Cheruiyot won the women's 5000m in 15-37.73, while
another Kenyan, Josephat Machuka, disqualified for hitting a rival at
the world junior event, came good by completing the 10,000/5000m double.
But his country could manage only eight golds, behind Nigeria, with 13.
However Mutola's world 1000m record (2-29.34) set in Brussels, is one
of three which the IAAF yesterday said they have yet to ratify. Fernanda
Ribiero's 5000m mark (14-36.4) and six pole vault bests in excess of
4.15m also await approval. The best of the latter is 4.22m by Daniela
Bartova.
Nine men's world records were set in 1995, plus five indoors, and one
junior best. Women established 21 world bests (14 and 3 in new events
the pole vault and hammer respectively), plus eight indoors, and one
junior.
* THE Scottish Athletics Indoor League for young athletes will again
be staged this winter in the Kelvin Hall. West division matches begin at
10am, and East matches at 2pm, on December 10, January 7, and February
25. The final is on March 3. All interested clubs are invited to a
meeting at the Kelvin Hall on September 30 at 2pm.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950919-000047</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950919-000047</DOCID>
<DATE>950919</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Pensioners recruited to save doorstep pinta</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>VIC ROBERTSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>29</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976306337</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
BRITAIN'S growing army of old age pensioners is to be mobilised to
help save the doorstep pinta delivery service.
Aid is also being sought from Brussels to ensure the survival of the
environmentally friendly recyclable glass milk bottle.
Unveiling this two-pronged approach in London yesterday, Dr Gavin
Strang, Shadow Agriculture Minister, said that European farm policy
spending on the dairy regime amounted to #3000m a year, much of which
was not well spent.
''But there is actually a subsidy in that regime for milk in schools
and we think that is a useful model. We want to see the CAP support the
doorstep delivery service, and the way we suggest they do it is to
subsidise the bottle.
''There is a tremendous drive in Europe on this packaging directive to
avoid waste and use recyclable materials. The milk bottle is ideal from
that point of view as it is used time and time again.''
He was supported by Andrew Dare, chief executive of Milk Marque, the
farm co-operative which controls the majority of the liquid milk market.
He said the European farm regime was becoming more environmentally
orientated so it was not unreasonable this drive should be extended to
other aspects of life.
David Moxon, chief executive of the National Dairymen's Association,
said there was a key social need for doorstep deliveries -- which
account for just under half of all liquid milk sales across Great
Britain, although much less in Scotland -- to remain, particularly for
the old, the isolated and the disabled.
Leaders of the 1.5-million strong National Pensioners' Convention,
Jack Jones and Margaret Wytham, also pledged their full support to the
House of Commons' petition which was launched yesterday. Mr Jones said
that contact with the outside world for many was only maintained by the
milkman or the postman.
Dairymen and pensioners and others are being asked to collect
signatures for the petitions which will be handed to local MPs with a
request to bring the campaign to the attention of the Commons and to put
pressure on the Government to act. Dr Strang stressed it was a non-party
campaign.
Doorstep sales have dwindled in recent years largely due to
cost-cutting by supermarkets which sell at an average 28p per pint as
opposed to 40p for delivered milk. Mr Moxon said there were other
factors, such as time of delivery and range of goods offered, but these
were being addressed by deliverymen.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
