<DOCID>GH950919-000048</DOCID>
<DATE>950919</DATE>
<HEADLINE>McRae a world title contender</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JOHN HORTON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>34</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976306338</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
RALLYING
COLIN McRae, driving an Impreza for the 555 Subaru World Rally Team,
has leapt from fourth to second in the world championship after having
finished runner-up in Rally Australia, which finished in Perth, Western
Australia, yesterday.
With two of the eight rounds remaining, the 27-year-old from Lanark is
now one of four drivers with a realistic chance of winning the
championship.
His rivals are the current leader and four-times world champion Juha
Kankkunen, from Finland, the reining champion, Frenchman Didier Auriol,
and McRae's Subaru team-mate, Carlos Sainz, from Spain.
Rally Australia was won by Sweden's Kenneth Eriksson driving a
Mitsubishi Lancer, who beat McRae by 19 seconds after 500 kilometres of
competitive driving over gravel roads.
These two were joint leaders starting the fourth and final day when
Eriksson produced an uncatchable performance and moved into the lead.
McRae, navigated by Glasgow's Derek Ringer, responded with a
counter-attack but a spin in the 30th and final special stage put paid
to his bid for victory.
David Richards, head of the 555 Subaru world rally team, said: ''It
was a fantastic drive by Colin. It's disappointing he didn't finish
ahead of Kenneth, but he couldn't have driven any harder and I'm
delighted.'' Results (British unless stated):
1, K Eriksson/S Parmander (Sweden) (Mitsubishi Lancer) 4-53-59; 2, C
McRae/D Ringer Subara Impreza 4-54-18; 3, J Kankkunen (Finland)/ N Grist
(Toyota Celica) 4-55-54; 4, T Makinen/S Harjanne (Finland) (Mitsubishi
Lancer) 4-57-26; 5, A Schwarz/K Wicha (Denmark) (Toyota Celica) 4-58-10;
6, B Thiry/S Prevot (Belgium) (Ford Escort Cosworth) 5-10-51.
FAI World Rally Championship -- positions after six of eight rounds --
1, Kankkunen 62 pts; 2, McRae 55; 3, D Auriol (France) 51; 4, C Sainz
(Spain) 50; 5, Eriksson 58.
</TEXT>
