<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950919-000051</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950919-000051</DOCID>
<DATE>950919</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Take the pain out of the game. Lessons to take as well as learn</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DOUGLAS LOWE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>31</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>976306341</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
''UP THE stakes,'' is often the cry upon learning that an opponent is
taking lessons. There might be a sneaking admiration at the effort being
made to improve, but we all know that to get better, you have first to
get worse and that knowledge is usually worth a pound or two.
Those who consider a visit to the club pro in the same category as an
appointment with the dentist, might be interested, however, in the
findings of the latest PGA Game Improvement Report.
The pain factor among the great untaught is not as pronounced as you
might think. Of those not currently taking lessons, only 13% said it was
because it upsets their game. The highest category, 26%, simply weren't
interested, 24% said they didn't have enough time -- presumably an
acknowledgment that to gain the full benefit from instruction, you must
practise as well -- while 19% felt they were too expensive.
At an average of #12.37 a lesson this last group might be regarded as
niggardly, but even here there is a surprise. The cost factor is a
significant drawback only for the socio-economic groups C2 and DE, yet
those least able to afford lessons are the ones who take the most.
For example, 37% of men in group DE have taken a lesson in the last
six months, compared with 17% in group AB, where the time factor was
more important.
Our golf tip feature, it seems, has some way to go. Only 2% regard
newspapers as the place to go for help, but to be fair we have regularly
pointed out that while tips are fine, they are no substitute for the
real thing.
The figures in general make gloomy reading for pros. Only 26% of
golfers in Britain and Ireland had taken at least one lesson in the last
six months, but the good news is that it is still a rise on last year.
The breakdown of this figure is 23% for men, who are more likely to rely
on advice from unqualified friends, and 43% for women. No attempt is
made to explain why women should be more interested in instructuion, and
suggestions are welcome.
There is also a sign of philanthropy among club pros in that a larger
overall figure, 40%, regard their main source of help to be their club
pro. In other words quite a large number ask for advice and receive it
without paying a penny.
Yet there is evidence that club golfers would benefit from a more
enlightened approach in that the lower the handicap, the more likely a
player is to take a lesson. Of those with handicaps of four or better,
73% had been under recent instruction, and this figure falls to 8% for
the group with no handicap, a case perhaps for insisting that new
members take a minimum number of lessons before they can set foot on the
course like they do on the Continent.
There are some points not covered in the survey which might be
important. If practice facilities which, generally are inadequate or
non-existent but the newer course, were better, there is a good chance
more would take lessons. A cramped area is a discouragement, especially
when much of the time is going to be spent sorting out your balls from
those of the other people sharing it with you.
Equally, if a player has taken a series of lessons, and at a later
date needs an adjustment, there is always the likelihood that the pro
who has earned the player's faith has moved on to a different club. How
many of us who took lessons in our formative years no longer have access
to our trusted guru of yore?
Still, club pros can take assurance from the report finding that only
2% of those who don't take lessons simply don't like the pro. If you
consider the converse, a 98% popularity vote for the PGA Party is high
by any standard. What would the Tories give for that result in a poll?
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950919-000052</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950919-000052</DOCID>
<DATE>950919</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Don't keep your head still</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>31</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976306342</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
GOLF TIP
This week's tip comes from MAURICE MOIR, professional at Hamilton Golf
Club.
''KEEP the head still'' is probably the most common piece of advice
given to all standard of golfers. But my advice is don't anchor the head
-- there has to be a slight movement to allow for a proper turn on the
backswing.
If the head is stuck, the weight stays too much on the left side and
the swing will be very flat. The player will be unable to get back to
the ball properly, and will also fail to swing right through the shot.
As a result, the ball is likely to be pushed or sliced to the right.
Players tend to think that they have to fix the head to avoid swaying
on the backswing. But, again, this is not the case. Obviously, there
shouldn't be a huge movement of the head, but there has to be some
slight give.
Desperate attempts to keep the head still is a fault that afflicts all
golfers, from the beginner to the low handicapper. But it really is the
wrong piece of advice.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950919-000053</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950919-000053</DOCID>
<DATE>950919</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Arianna, Royal Opera House, London</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>BENEDICT BROGAN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>24</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>REVIEW</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>976306343</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE award-winning team of director Francesca Zambello and designer
Alison Chitty has scored another exhilarating success with its treatment
of Arianna, the lost opera by Monteverdi re-composed by Alexander Goehr.
Visually refreshing, emotionally taut, flawlessly staged, this world
premiere sweeps aside contemporary challengers.
With no intervals in two hours, it tells the tale of Ariadne, princess
of Crete, her betrayal by Theseus, vanquisher of the Minotaur, and her
subsequent seduction by Bacchus. Susan Graham is a noble Arianna,
poignant in her grief. She heads a uniformly strong cast, with notably a
moving, powerful performance by baritone Gidon Saks as the fisherman
messenger.
Some of the staging flirts with silliness, but manages to pull back in
time: the host of boy cherubim descending from the heavens on bright red
wicker chairs, is fun; the fishermen depositing their silver catch in
their shimmering net, beautiful; Arianna entangled in the fishermen's
lines as she struggles against their efforts to save her, captivating.
If the colouring is a suspiciously '90s Conran aqua and blue, the design
with its visual tricks and refeshing simplicity -- no sets, just props
and Alan Burrett's excellent lighting -- gives uninterrupted pleasure.
There are no foot tapping melodies in Goehr's resurrection, just a
beautifully judged construction of emotional layers, building to
Arianna's devastating lament. Ivor Bolton, principal conductor of the
Scottish Chamber Orchestra, leads a small period ensemble set in
informal 17th century fashion in a shallow pit in the middle of the
stage. It is a new, yet delightfully familiar Arianna.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950919-000054</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950919-000054</DOCID>
<DATE>950919</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Giants of Jazz, Pavilion</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>STEPHEN MCGINTY</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>24</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>REVIEW</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>976306344</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
JAZZ and sex have always mingled well: a lone saxophone and a torrid
cinema love-affair. You just don't expect a big bloke in a stripey
yellow suit, snap-brim fedora and taste in workingmen's club humour to
burst into the bedroom.
But like a Viz cartoon character -- George Melly, the man on the telly
-- raised the steamy stakes. Previously we had funked along nicely as
Humphrey Lyttelton had schmoozed his band through Strange Mr Peter
Charles. Described as Hitchcockian, it was more a tramp through the
nightclubs of Starsky and Hutch. An aural realm where our pair would
chase dope dealers in seventies thrillers. Smokin'!
Then Mr Melly cracked the audiences mouths open with saucy jokes
before stretching them into wide smiles with his renditions of
Underneath The Arches and I Want My Fannie Brown. There is some-thing
decadent about an elderly man who should know better choosing not to.
It should have been announced during the interval that Battle Of The
Drums was to follow. Supping time was lost. Everyone hates drum solos.
Though under-attended, the evening was rounded off by Kenny Ball who
ensured everyone had their turn in the spotlight, even directing the
lighting himself. The genial atmosphere and laid-back tunes created by
previous acts was shaken up by his gleefully wicked approach.
</TEXT>
