<HEADLINE>Babel before pulp</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>SARA VILLIERS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>24</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976306345</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Sara Villiers prefers the palapable genius of new company Theatre
Babel to the tortured mimicry of movie culture, Tarantino-style
DAMN the hide of Tarantino. The geeky smartie might have given
Hollywood a much-needed kick up the pants with his clever-dick catering
to the po-mo gerbil's-attention-span generation -- but his influence on
culture, popular or otherwise, has become so over-hyped and overstated
as to be pernicious.
It's a case of gimmick overkill; suddenly everthing's Reservoir
Kittens or Reservoir Bitches and nothing, from club nights to soundtrack
albums, is deemed hip unless it's been well and truly Pulp-ed.
The most irritating example of this trend is the phenomenon known as
Pulp Shakespeare, with the marketing bods assuming that the Tarantino
association gives the Bard a dose of street cred. Ugh.
It's so preposterous, considering William Shakespeare perfected a
thrilling blend of bawdy buddy-humour and high-octane violence, spilling
guts and blood across the stage with dispassionate regularity long
before Quentin's grand-daddy was a twinkle in his
great-great-great-great-grandparents' eyes. Perched on a celestial cloud
or burning lump of sulphur, Shakespeare probably greeted the Pulp
Fiction furore with a yawning ''Huh, been there, seen it, done it all
before''.
Even more exasperating is the fact that the term Pulp Shakespeare is
so often a lazy description for incoherent productions characterised by
dance music and quasi-Gaultier costumes. Having sat through the
excruciating dramatisation of Venus and Adonis by the Actors' Touring
Company and the Hairy Marys earlier this year, I determined that the
next time I received a press missive promising a Pulp Shakespeare
production I would slice the ears off the perpetrator.
So the mention of a Tarantino movie in a press release from Theatre
Babel, Scotland's only small-scale touring company specialising in
repertoire performances of classical theatre, quickly set my
blood-a-boiling.
But Graham McLaren, co-founder of the company with Rebecca Rodgers,
denies they are leaping aboard the Pulp bandwagon, pointing out that
they merely claimed they were for ''people who would rather go and see
Pulp Fiction than pay to see another ill-conceived Shakespeare
production.''
Splitting hairs perhaps, but he insists that they are just as appalled
by trendy productions. Set up last year by McLaren and Rodgers, both
graduates from the RSAMD, Theatre Babel's intention is to produce
dynamic productions of classical works with an emphasis on a clarity and
precision which does not sacrifice the text to style over substance.
Last year they debuted with repertoire productions of Twelfth Night
and Romeo and Juliet and they are now touring with a repertoire bill of
Hamlet and another production of the star-crossed lovers. McLaren might
feistily declare an abhorrence for theatres ''preoccupied with putting
bums on seats'' but it seems likely that Romeo and Juliet's status as a
fixture on the school syllabus makes it a pragmatic choice.
McLaren's opinions on the state of Scottish theatre are refreshingly
spunky -- I enjoyed our verbal spat about the role of critics -- if a
tad conceited.
His view that while companies like Red Shift and Cheek-by-Jowl had
revitalised Shakespeare in England, no company in Scotland had dared to
do the same, ignores the celebrated history of controversial
interpretations by the Citizens' Theatre.
When pressed, he acknowledges this then makes cryptic comments about
the decision of ''another Scottish company'' -- it is the Royal Lyceum
-- to stage Hamlet after Theatre Babel had announced they would perform
the play, which has not been staged in Scotland for some years.
Such ferocious loyalty to Theatre Babel demonstrates the commitment
necessary to get a company off the ground and McLaren is certainly
impressively organised, managing to sell out last week's visit to the
Belfast Arts Centre weeks in advance.
Maggie Kinloch, former artistic director of the Byre Theatre who is
currently teaching at London's Central School of Speech and Drama, is
directing Romeo and Juliet, and speaks of her tremendous relief to be
unburdened by McLaren of financial and administrative concerns to
concentrate on directing.
''I think what Babel are trying to do is similar to what Ian Brown was
doing with TAG in the mid-eighties, to give classic productions an
energy and accessibility that speaks to a younger audience. Until now I
don't think anyone else has followed that through,'' she says.
''We've been working in a collaborative way, discussing the text in
depth, exploring personal relevance, and I really believe this young
company are breaking new ground, working in a way I am convinced is the
right way.''
Peter McAllister, current Head of Acting at the Samuel Beckett Centre
in Dublin having previously taught at the RSAMD, who is directing
Hamlet, agrees. ''They're more concerned with process rather than
product which leads to interesting and original work. Many young
companies are too intimidated to tackle Hamlet although it says a lot to
a young generation about the responsibilities inherited from
forefathers, and many young actors are too frightened by the leading
role. It can seem like a mountain but the challenge is in trying to make
that climb.''
It is a climb which McLaren is undertaking; originally he had his eye
on Laertes but took on Hamlet after other actors approached expressed
trepidation. Unintimidated by perceived benchmark performances he is
attacking the part with gusto. ''It's a role which is both brilliant and
terrifying but you can't be afraid of not giving the definitive
performance,'' he says.
McAllister is confident that their production is a vital, streamlined
one, which speaks directly to a supposedly disaffected youth about the
business of doing the right thing. ''We're addressing a generation which
finds words difficult. In Shakespeare's time school children learned 230
different rhetorical figures but we can only mention metaphors and
similes. Modern audiences do have trouble with language and we have to
be as clear as possible. I think we've succeeded, but it's not Pulp
Shakespeare, it's palpable Shakespeare.''
</TEXT>
