<HEADLINE>Scottish Asian benefits from Far East recovery</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>IAN MCCONNELL</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>25</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>TABLE</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976306347</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A UPTURN in Far Eastern stock markets towards the end of its financial
year allowed Murray Johnstone's Scottish Asian Investment Company to
recoup virtually all of its earlier losses.
Management of the #57m trust is being moved to Murray Johnstone's
recently-opened Singapore office and Scottish Asian's investment
director, Peter Montgomery, has moved there from Glasgow.
The Glasgow-based investment management group's new
Singapore-incorporated subsidiary, Murray Johnstone (Asia) Pte, will
manage not only Scottish Asian but also some other existing client funds
in the Asia-Pacific region.
In all, Murray Johnstone manages about #480m in the region and it
believes its presence in Singapore will enable it to attract more funds
from the US and Middle East.
Peter Linthwaite has moved to Singapore from Murray Johnstone's London
office, where he ran the private equity operations for five years, to
take up responsibility for developing business in the Asia-Pacific as
managing director of the new subsidiary.
Scottish Asian's fully-diluted net asset value was off only 1.2% over
the year to end-July, at 292p, having been down 16.2% at the halfway
stage. Its performance was only marginally worse than that of its
benchmark MSCI Combined Far East Free ex-Japan index, which lost 1%
during the 12 months.
During the year to end-July, Scottish Asian's shares rose from 263p to
299p but they have since slipped back to be at a marginal discount to
net asset value.
Yesterday, the shares lost 2p to 289p, with net asset value little
changed from July 31.
During the year, exposure to Singapore was increased from 13% to
21.5%. Scottish Asian has invested heavily in property related stocks,
believing they will benefit from the country's low interest rates and
continuing move to owner-occupation.
Exposure to Hong Kong, which had been reduced from 25.5% to about 15%
by the halfway point, had been increased to 30.1% by the year-end.
The trust's other major market is Malaysia, which accounted for 27.4%
of shareholders' funds at July 31.
Scottish Asian was top of its eight-strong peer group in terms of
share price total return and net asset value total return for the five
years to end-July. Over 12 months, it was fourth in terms of net asset
value total return, out of a larger peer group of 10.
