<HEADLINE>Multi-faceted lustre of a sparkling career</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ERIC KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>19</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>MY JOB</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976306349</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IS being a jeweller a gem of a job? Does the working day have sparkle?
Fraser Buchanan might say the answer to both question is yes. He is
lucky, mind you, in that he now owns his own business, designing and
manufacturing high-quality jewellery to order.
He is happy at his Glasgow jewellery design studio but acknowledges
that not everyone would be suited to such tasks. ''You have to have
confidence in yourself,'' he says. ''A sapphire worth many thousands of
pounds could shatter. You have to know what you are doing, and not be
afraid to do it.''
Buchanan, who left Woodfarm High School, Thornliebank in 1981 with
five Highers before studying electrical and electronic engineering at
Strathclyde University, had no notion of being a jeweller.
As his course proceeded, however, he came to realise that electronic
design might not offer him the independence and freedom of expression he
needed. He had also been doing a Saturday job in a big Paisley
jeweller's shop throughout his course, and this taught him a lot about
the trade.
He felt he had a natural flair for jewellery design and manufacture
and that there was a niche for him in the business.
By the time he graduated with a BSc Hons in 1985 he had made up his
mind. He took a full-time job with the Paisley firm and spent seven
years there, polishing his skills and knowledge, handling gold, silver
and precious stones with confidence, and establishing a working pattern
where he discussed repairs and design jobs personally with the customer
rather than leaving it to the salesman.
The firm went out of business in 1992 and he took two years out to
think things out, sailing around Skye and the West Coast and reflecting
that the stock, materials and equipment he had amassed over the years
would be not a bad launching pad for a business of his own.
His design studio was launched just over a year ago in Glasgow's South
Side where he is now building up a faithful clientele through
word-of-mouth recommendation -- ''the best way'', he says.
In addition to the usual rubies, emeralds, diamonds and sapphires he
likes to introduce less well-known precious stones such as tanzanite (a
stunning violet blue), tsavorite (a vivid electric green) and rhodelite
(brilliant burgundy).
A more common way into jewellery is, of course, one of the degree
courses in design and manufacture available at a number of colleges, or
to go straight from school into an eight-year apprenticeship with a
major manufacturer and repairer.
This last-named can lead to a place on a degree course but in either
case, says Buchanan, it is an idea to seek a temporary post -- even
unpaid -- with a top manufacturer in order to learn the fundamentals of
the design and construction of mainstream jewellery.
''No-one else is going to give you their jewellery to play around
with,'' he says. ''But as you acquire expertise and confidence, and
discover an ability to give the customer exactly what is wanted, this is
certainly a challenging and rewarding profession.''
</TEXT>
