<HEADLINE>Hays liftsearningsto #110m</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ANDREW WILSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>25</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>TABLE</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976306350</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
DISTRIBUTION and records storage group Hays turned in excellent
full-year results with pre-tax profits rising 26% to #110m partly
because it gained substantial amounts of new business. That was achieved
on overall turnover increasing by 28%, excluding acquisitions, to #808m.
Chairman Ronnie Frost is still very much on the acquisition trail,
with two deals amounting to #9m since the June year-end, one for a Dutch
commercial records management company, the other for Apollo Despatch
courier services which has 14,000 business customers.
Profits were also helped by improvement in the global chemical
business which helped boost margins in Hays' chemical distribution
operations. Document exchange also expanded, helping profits in the
commercial division rise 19%.
But the greatest gain was seen in personnel. The 73% surge in profit
reflected the increasing emphasis on temporary staff by employers
reluctant to take people on permanently. Hays is now expanding into IT
placements to complement its existing accountancy employment activities.
Mr Frost said the new year had started well and prospects continued to
be encouraging both in the UK and overseas.
The dividend total has been raised 15% to 7p with a 4.75p final.
The shares closed unchanged at 359p and yield 2.45 while trading at
19.2 times historic earnings.
