<HEADLINE>Touch of Hitchcock and a sprinkling of Gazza and Burns</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>TOM SHIELDS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>23</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>DIARY</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976306354</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
LIBERAL Democrat president Robert Maclennan is famous for making
speeches which are worthy but dull. He admitted as much yesterday in his
address to the faithful at the party's annual conference in Glasgow.
''You know me,'' he said. ''Cautious till you could scream. Very
slightly pedantic.'' His speech yesterday was worthy but far from dull.
The style of delivery, like a zombie on speed, was fascinating enough.
But it was the sheer variety of source material that kept listeners on
the edge of their seats waiting to hear what reference was coming next.
Oor Bob gave us Abbe Sieyes who said of the French Revolution: ''I
survived.'' This was a reference to John Major who might say something
similar about his time as leader of the Conservative Party.
Then we had a touch of Alfred Hitchcock as the present Tory Government
was likened to the Bates Motel: ''I don't say they actually stab you in
the shower but most people want to get out.''
The Labour Party, said Bob, reminded him of Debussy's comment on the
works of Edward Grieg: ''Pink bonbons stuffed with snow.''
Onwards to quotes from E M Forster, Jerome K Jerome's Three Men in a
Boat and a poet called Roy Campbell.
It was across the Atlantic for a daud of Jeffersonian theory (''he
governs best who governs least'') and Theodore Roosevelt talking about
''the malefactors of great wealth''.
And there was the ubiquitous Gazza. President Bob bemoaned the fact
that while society suffers so many ills, the headline news is ''Gazza
dyed his hair blue for his England game''. It was black, Bob, but never
mind.
In one dazzling section of the speech, Bob made passing references in
consecutive sentences to Oscar Wilde, Rabbie Burns, and Danton (another
chap from the French Revolution, Georges-Jacques of that Ilk, who was
famous for his audacity).
Having brought his Lib Dem colleagues all the way to Scotland, the MP
for Caithness obviously felt compelled to give them a bit of the local
lingo. The Scots having their own parliament but maintaining the same
level of representation would be buttering our bannocks on both sides.
Bob even tried to get his refined tones round some Rab C Nesbitt-style
Glesgaspeak. Britain was ''goin' doon the stank'' he said. ''But haud
on, Jimmy. There is another alternative.''
Yes, vote for a Liberal Democrat MP in Govan.
Curious kitty
BACK on familiar territory was Lord Jenkins of Hillhead, gracing the
platform at the SECC. Lord Jenkins also graces the headed notepaper of a
Lib Dem initiative called the Dagger Wine Club.
The dagger bit is less sinister than it sounds. It stands for the
Democrat's Action Group for Gaining Electoral Reform. The wine club is a
fund-raising venture which involves members lobbing #1 a month into a
kitty.
Half of the cash is spent on an upmarket case of wine, which goes to
whoever's name comes out the hat. The rest goes to the campaign to
secure the group's aim of having the single transferable vote used in
all British elections. We'll drink to that.
Early warning
BUT it's not all devolution, single transferable votes, and listening
to Bob Maclennan at the Lib Dem conference. There is also the early
morning sex.
Well, sex education to be exact, which is or was (depends when you're
reading this) the subject for debate at a fringe meeting at 8am this
morning in the Moat House Hotel. A continental breakfast will be or was
served, presumably followed by a cigarette.
The event is chaired by the exotically named Baroness Hamwee. It is
organised by the Sex Education Forum who refer to their work in schools
as the ''Fourth R''.
What is the fourth R? No, you filthy child at the back, it is not
rumpy-pumpy. The R stands for relationships.
Biting humour
SPOTTED on the cafe menu at the David Livingstone Centre in Blantyre,
a dish called ''Kwasongs'' served with side salad at #1.95. Some exotic
dish to celebrate the great explorer's African connections? No. Closer
inspection by our informant, Margaret Gray of Glasgow, revealed the item
to be what our French cousins have for breakfast.
Now you know
DEPT of Potentially Acrimonious Acronyms: Glasgow City Council has
been given Euro-funding for a project called RESET. It is nothing to do
with dodgy car radios, videos, or other stolen goods. The initials stand
for Renewable Energies Strategy in European Towns.
Chorus of approval
DIARY reader John Boyle of Ardrossan, perusing the Victoria &amp; Albert
Museum Christmas catalogue, comes across the perfect present for
Monklands Man. You have drunk the strong wine, had the hangover, and
perhaps served the 30 days for the breach of the peace.
Now listen to the CD. We are talking about Carols from Buckfast, sung
by the choir of the abbey where they make the wine that made Monklands
famous. Available by mail order from the V &amp; A at #10.95.
Unlucky bag
IT is back-to-college time and a chap called Gerry is in touch with
details of the goodie bag which Kilmarnock College is handing out to its
students. The bag for male students contains a free sample of Insignia
aftershave, a Lion bar, a Drifter bar, a packet of Chinese-flavour
noodles, a free Bic razor marked ''free only with McDonald's breakfast,
drugs helpline information, and a leaflet called A Whole New Ball Game
on how to check for testicular cancer.
The bag for female students had a free sample of Witch Doctor gel
instead of the aftershave and all of the rest of the above-mentioned
goodies. Including the Whole New Ball Game leaflet.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950919-000065</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950919-000065</DOCID>
<DATE>950919</DATE>
<HEADLINE>No Headline Present</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ANNE SIMPSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>23</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>976306355</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
CAN there be a more poisonous pen club than that which brings together
a quarrel of crime writers? If anything this rumpus between P D James
and her funkier contemporaries demonstrates a long-held suspicion that
when it comes to criticism neither type of mystery scribe is tolerant.
Instead they all believe that the first rule of the craft, because I say
so, is an explanation which sufficiently covers everything.
But what we have here now is snobbery versus gritty realism; blood on
the carpet versus blood in the urinal. The trouble began with that
statement given by the Baroness of Holland Park to the BBC World Service
in which James implied she believed moral choice belonged only to the
middle class.
Immediately this triggered outrage among the street-fight literati who
anyway consider James's thrillers to be over-cerebral, contrived, and
lost up their own imperious line of inquiry. James's response has been
to threaten her resignation from the Crime Writers' Association, but now
comes news of another snub.
The word from the Boucheran -- the World Mystery Convention which is
to be held in Nottingham at the end of this month -- is that James has
removed herself from the guest list. No official motive is evident and
the organisers insist her withdrawal was communicated before the row
developed into a story of insult and envy, privilege and slumming.
But now instead of examining the body of crime fiction in all its
guises in Nottingham, ''her eminence'' -- as James is known in the book
trade -- will address a British Council gathering in Greece. Still, her
absence from the convention is unlikely to close the file on that
interview with the World Service.
''If you set it (a detective story) in the pits of the worst possible
inner-city area, where crime is the norm, you don't get moral choice,''
she said. ''You don't get contrasts between good and evil.'' Well, tell
that to Ed McBain, whose criminals and snitches, good cops, rotten cops,
whackos and uprights have given us the jagged parade of humanity which
makes him one of the best thriller-tellers in the world.
Practically every line of McBain expresses the morality of social
anger; the blazing disgust at neglect and collapse within our cities, at
the ratty stench of squalid housing, at the rubble of loneliness and the
no-hoper ambushed by hell.
Every page smells of New York. The man may fudge actual location but
it is there, that metallic thwack against the nostrils, and the dry,
yeasty whiff of bagels. The sweat of warm flesh in the subway and the
tar-inhalant of fire burning in oil drums along the Bowery on
zero-temperature nights. By expanding the boundries of mystery so that
his work is not merely a whodunnit, McBain convincingly brings us the
hades of the universal city.
None of this need concern James, of course, because her detective Adam
Dalgliesh seems designed principally to inhabit the Gothic imagination
of the English bourgeoisie. James began in the tradition of detective
novelists who dwell in an artificial milieu of suave dissemblers. The
villain never lives below stairs or in the vulgar world. Like Dalgliesh,
the villain might be dressed by Savile Row.
Dorothy Sayers fell in love with Lord Peter Wimsey. Ruth Rendell's
Inspector Wexford, from stolid beginnings, has become increasingly
bookish. Inspector Morse, with his endless agonising, is an
embarrassment. And Adam Dalgliesh belongs in the drawingroom, not the
interrogation cell, a pretentious and unbelievable creation. His first
appearance was as a plain detective inspector but he soon became
commander of a new squad investigating cases which required a special
sensitivity.
This allowed Dalgliesh to indulge his poetic soul: ''After four years
of silence, his new book of poetry, A Case To Answer and Other Poems,
had been published to considerable critical acclaim which was
surprisingly gratifying, and to even wider public interest which, less
surprisingly, he was finding more difficult to take . . .'' As Dalgliesh
has become loftier so James has perhaps come to believe herself more
novelist than crime hack, more Trollope than Christie.
Adam Dalgliesh would never cause his author the seedy problems McBain
encounters with his cops. But McBain is not a man for smug red herrings
or precious conversation over claret. He is too busy snooping about the
sidewalks, in and out of strangers' shadows, collar upturned, and ear
cocked for the heist rap. And then he goes home and talks to himself,
jotting down the conversation . . . until a shot rings out.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
