<DATE>950919</DATE>
<HEADLINE>When the Tories were torn apart</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JOHN MACLEOD</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>23</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>976306357</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
YESTERDAY I put on the TV and watched Malcolm Bruce make a bad speech
to the Liberal Democrat conference in Glasgow. It was read, every line
of it; it had every political cliche I had ever heard, and a few more
besides; the Gordon MP spoke in a quick monotone, punctuated by a
tubercular cough. Yet, at regular intervals, they hailed him in bored
applause.
Politicians still pretend -- and we journos play along with them,
being kind -- that these autumn events matter; that, if Bournemouth
sneezes, Britain will shortly share the Lem-Sip. But party conferences
no longer wield power. They now serve to treat faithful party activists,
and as a PR showcase for the nation. So the patter of applause, the
potted flowers, the tilted perspex of the ''sincerity machine,'' the
Churchillian cadences of the leader's speech -- these are, today, as
much a part of autumn as bonfires and conkers.
This autumn, however, signals a shift in gear. Three and a half years
have passed since the last General Election and, once these jamborees
are over, we will be increasingly gripped by the polls to come. In
normal times we would expect them in the spring or summer of next year.
These are not normal times. Most expect a General Election in the spring
of 1997, about as late as it can be postponed by law.
What has taken on the air of certainty is that the Conservatives will
lose. Only miraculous rejuvenation could renew this lot's lease on
power. Conservatism has achieved nothing in this Parliament apart from
some panic legislation, ill-conceived attempts to privatise trains, and
a fraught unity over Europe.
They have run out of new blood. The back benches bristle with the
sacked, retired, and resigned has-beens of men failed in government or
smeared by scandal; besides them, there are a few greenhorns (like
Sebastian Coe) and the unemployable, like Tony Marlow. Time, too, has
drained leaders of credibility. Does anyone really believe, say, Kenneth
Clarke's mouthings on recovery, or Malcolm Rifkind's views on Scottish
home rule? Do we sense that they believe them themselves?
For the Tories, once history is written, the infamous Black Wednesday
may be seen as the nemesis. That day in September 1992 blew Major's
economic policies apart and ravaged his personal credibility. It ended
the Tories' greatest electoral asset: the reputation as the party of
sound money. Its huge costs -- Norman Lamont squandered more, in one
day, vainly trying to save the pound than the Kinnock Government would
have spent on the NHS in four years -- forced new and hideously
unpopular taxes. Not least, Black Wednesday tore the Tories apart on
Europe. Until this July Major was racked, and racked again by his own
back benchers. The Prime Minister, with sharp judgment and desperate
courage, has for the moment emasculated the power of his anti-Europe
lobby. But he has failed to renew his party or revive his Government. He
holds only the honour of losing the next election.
The Tories seem set to fall, come polling day, but that does not mean
that Labour are set to win. The swing required for a Labour victory --
6% on the 1992 result -- is, in fact, a tall order. Besides, Labour is
still haunted by its past. The national folk memory fears the trade
unions and does not trust Labour on money. It is haunted by the present,
where big-spending, entrenched Labour still wroughts much of our local
government. This late in Parliament, Labour has yet to articulate clear
policies or outline anything beyond high-sounding principles. Blair,
like Smith before him, has spun out time in leading Labour to reform
itself. Of this the nation is wearying.
At least Blair is not Neil Kinnock, a man the public never trusted.
But neither is he John Smith, with experience of Government. Blair is
charming, confident, and elegant. So was Anthony Eden; but No 10 proved
a step too high for his talent.
Of this Labour may be sure. The Tories will shortly offer us all tax
cuts, and such middle-class goodies Labour will be unable to threaten.
Further, many who have made Major's life miserable for the past three
years -- the cheap Tory press, the CBI, the major financial
institutions, Baroness Thatcher -- will, come the dissolution, go
scampering home to mummy. One should not over-rate the power of the
press. But the tabloid onslaught on Kinnock in 1992 may well have made
the difference that cold April, between power and oblivion.
Then, of course, there are the Liberal Democrats. For them, a decade
after the alliance, the end of the century offers little. The public
cannot slide a fruitknife between Labour and Lib Dem noises. Ashdown,
our most senior party leader, sounds time-served tinny. In the tactical
squeeze of the next election, the Liberal Democrats may well emerge with
more seats, but their overall vote share seems likely to decline.
Fifteen per cent would be very good.
Later this week, the SNP is to convene at Perth. It was at Perth five
years ago, in fact, that Alex Salmond became leader. Salmond, over this
time, has grudgingly won the regard of political professionals. He may
not be greatly liked, but he is steady; he does not panic, and he
responds to abuse (of which he has had much) with calm mirth.
Perth will remind Salmond and friends of how far they have revived
over the past decade. They meet in a city with an SNP MP, an SNP provost
and under three SNP councils. But the nationalists will have to face a
General Election where the broad game is not in their interests: a Tory
Government on the way out and a new voter-friendly Labour Party fair set
for the way in.
Many Scots voters will give Labour that chance. Many defecting Tories,
indeed, who might once have gone Lib Dem or SNP in their pique, may go
straight to Mr Blair. What will not work for the SNP, this poll coming,
will be such good old lines as ''Who'll save Scotland when England votes
Tory again?'' Watch them, then, piling on the heat over Labour's
devolution commitment and, after the last debacle, a much more focused
SNP campaign with the hope of some six-to-a-dozen seats.
On Wednesday, indeed, I shall be in Perth myself, being spared, if
only for such joys as flirting with Winnie Ewing and sampling the home
baking. And the Tay will flow by, as it ran before all those politicians
and their fixes, and as it will run when they have all gone, even to the
end of time.
</TEXT>
