<HEADLINE>Lessons for the Highlands from Harlem</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>EDUCATION</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976306358</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE proposed University of the Highlands and Islands and higher
education in New York's toughest inner-city neighbourhoods are worlds
apart. But the shared conviction that higher education should not be
confined to established institutions and should be of relevance to
people in all communiites brought the two together with a bang when
three New York academics included a visit to the Highlands between
conferences in Edinburgh on access to education.
Founded in 1904 by the Ursuline Order in Westchester County, a
well-heeled suburb of New York, the college of New Rochelle has an
impeccable pedigree as the first Catholic college for women in New York
State. It shocked the educational establishment when it started
undergraduate courses in downtown Manhattan for members of the biggest
municipal workers' union. Further courses in makeshift campuses in
community centres and disused schools in the Bronx and Harlem prompted
the newspaper headline: What's a nice college like you doing in a place
like this?
The answer was bringing higher education to communities which were
previously excluded from it. By-passed is the word used by Bessie Blake,
Dean of the School of New Resources. Continuing the roads analogy, she
describes the scheme as building ramps to the superhighway of education
for communities isolated by the fast-moving traffic.
In the revolutionary years of the early 70s, many higher-education
establishments suffered identity crises. In that context New Rochelle
examined its access policies and the Ursuline sisters, having noted that
educational research showed that parental involvement was the most
important factor for children's progress in education, dedided that
working with adults was the most crucial step for social change. They
had no intention of moving outwith their own area, but a small
advertisement for adult would-be students caught the eye of the leader
of the very powerful municipal workers' union.
The result was a partnership in which the college would provide the
staff and teaching, and the union would provide the premises. It was an
act of faith which provided a liberal arts framework in which trade
union members could improve their skills for both life and work. The DC
37 Campus housed in the Lower Manhattan headquarters of the American
Federation of State, County and Municipal Employees is still the only
full-time degree offered at a trade union headquarters. It is only one
of seven campuses across New York, each serving distinct communities.
Bessie Blake thinks that one of the most important aspects of the
School of New Resources is that it not only offers courses in the
students' communities, but keeps their new skills there afterwards, as
teachers, social workers and managers. The School of New Resources is
based on the principle that entry to college should lead to employment
and advancement on graduation. Students are over the age of 21 but may
be working or unemployed, some are what the Americans call structurally
unemployed: the second or third generation to have no work.
One campus is based at the New York Theological Seminary and most of
the students are working ministers and assistants in small parishes
throughout the city. Co-op City campus is based in the biggest
concentration of skyscrapers in America and started life in a basesment
until Bessie Blake breezed in and announced it was ''Lower level Co-op
City''. The Brooklyn Campus has tapped into New York's first urban
regeneration scheme and as a result boasts an art gallery, arts centre
and theatre. In many ways, though, it is the Rosa Parks Campus which
exemplifies the potential of the School of New Resources.
''If you can tackle the problems in the Harlem community, you can do
it anywhere in New York, in the US, and I would say in the world. There
is everything you can think of -- homelessness, ill-health, domestic
violence, addiction, drug-addicted babies. Yet out of the struggle comes
amazing creativity, some of our greatest writers and musicians come from
Harlem even today. Yet the same problems exist in Westchester County.
Because it is so stunningly beautiful, people imagine there are no
welfare mothers or poverty, but it is just that the challenges are not
so apparent,'' she said.
That struck an immediate chord with people in the Highlands including
Hilary Lawson, organiser of the Workers' Educational Association in
Inverness. She invited colleagues from Inverness College and people
working on the proposal for a University of the Highland to an informal
exchange of ideas with Dr Blake and her colleagues.
Dr Blake insists that higher education can be brought to any community
if the will is there. The College of New Rochelle does not have a big
endowment. The funding for the Scool of New Resources comes from a
variety of sources: from the trade unions and the churches from Federal
sources and a variety of trusts.
</TEXT>
