<TEXT>
LOWER bad debt provisions and higher interest income helped half-year
profits at Britannia Building Society climb to #50.6m, the group
announced yesterday.
The earnings for the six months to end-June compare with pre-tax
profits of #46.8m in the first half of last year.
''Improvements to the mortgage underwriting process have continued to
reap rewards as provisions for bad and doubtful debts fell by 11%
reflecting enhanced asset quality,'' said chairman Calum MacLeod.
</TEXT>
