<HEADLINE>Young surfers head for public access</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>GERARD SEENAN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>EDUCATION</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>976306360</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Gerard Seenan finds a book shop selling hands-on training for the
Internet
AS the information revolution known as the Internet hurtles onwards,
the more traditional purveyors of knowledge have decided to get in on
the act.
John Smith &amp; Son has become the first bookseller in Scotland to offer
public access to the Internet through its Internet Learning Centre at
its Glasgow store. For #1.95 per half hour, members of the public can
surf or, for the more inept, stagger around in cyberspace.
The centre is staffed by a work force familiar with the intricacies of
Internet access and can provide the initial training needed for net
navigation. And, for those who feel the apprehension associated with
Luddite thoughts coming on, the centre's manager, Barry Fogarty, is
certain that any initial trepidation will be dispelled instantaneously.
''It only takes a member of staff around 10 minutes to teach someone
the basics of Internet access, after that they are perfectly able to
browse around themselves. But if they need any more help we are happy to
give it,'' he says.
Public access centres, such as this, afford a prime opportunity for
pupils and teachers to gain access to a vast array of information
resources that would generally be unavailble in the classroom situation.
Last week Clyde Valley High School, Wishaw, used the centre for just
such a purpose.
''We don't have Internet access at the school as yet so this gives the
kids a first opportunity to see how it works. It gives them a flavour of
the depth and breadth of information they can access and shows them that
its relevant to every subject they study,'' said Kieron Fallon, a
computing teacher at the school.
No doubt in common with many pupils, this was the first time most of
the students had had any direct contact with the Internet. ''I have seen
it on the television and read about it, but this is the first time I've
ever used it,'' said 4th-year pupil, Simon Kirkwood.
Although they weren't quite ready for waxing their boards and hitting
the waves, after the initial induction the pupils felt up to a little
trepid surfing.
''I've never used the Internet before and I didn't really know what it
was,'' said Sharon McFarlane, 13. ''But I have learned about its
history, where it comes from, how it started and how to use it. I think
I could find information I was looking for after a while.''
Another pupil Aliah Ashraf, 13, was confident that she could now make
use of the Internet in her studies. ''I think it would come in very
useful for projects and investigations in lots of different subjects,''
she said.
The Internet Learning Centre is intended primarily for individuals,
but John Smith's are happy to arrange school visits on appointment.
Telephone 0141 221 7472.
</TEXT>
