<HEADLINE>Awards body's success marked by its decision to reduce fees</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DICK LOUDEN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>EDUCATION</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976306362</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Dick Louden hears of a rare case where an educational body's cash
surplus is redistributed among its customers
IT makes a refreshing change these days to hear of an organisation
which takes steps to share its financial surplus with its customers. The
Scottish Vocational Education Council (Scotvec) -- the body responsible
for national vocational awards -- has decided to reduce by up to 10% the
fees it receives for administering its range of qualifications.
The fee for a National Certificate module or a workplace unit goes
down from #3.80 to #3.60, while the charge for a group award -- an
all-in fee including enrolment, certification and verification -- is
reduced from #77.50 to #70 for the Higher National Certificate and from
#92.50 to #85 in the case of the Higher National Diploma. For students
taking individual Higher National units but not enrolled for a group
award, each unit is now charged at #9 instead of #10. In addition, the
''annual retainer'' fee of #100 which has been levied until now on many
of Scotvec's approved centres is being scrapped.
Colleges, local authorities and many Scottish businesses will derive
financial benefit from this initiative. Tom McCool, Scotvec's chief
executive, attributes it in particular to the increased levels of
student registrations which have continued unabated in recent years.
Founded only 10 years ago, Scotvec now has well over a million National
Certificate module enrolments per year, while unit registrations for its
Higher National awards have doubled in a very short time to a new record
of over 300,000 and would no doubt have continued to soar if the
Scottish Office had not decided recently to ''cap'' them at current
levels.
It gives Tom McCool genuine satisfaction to be able to reduce fees in
this way. ''Schools, colleges, local authorities, business and industry
have been our partners all along,'' he says. ''It is thanks to them that
our awards have acquired such credibility and that their uptake has gone
on rising. It is only right that we recognise our partnership with them
by reducing their financial burden when we are able to do so.''
This happy position has arisen because Scotvec, previously financed
largely by the Scottish Office and the Convention of Scottish Local
Authorities, became self-financing in 1993 and, through a blend of
entrepreneurial spirit and efficient housekeeping, has achieved
surpluses in the last two years of #1.2m and #1.4m.
Valuable income has been built up by winning large contracts such as
maintaining the Streetworks Qualifications Register and administering
national examinations for the Police Promotions Board and, on behalf of
the Department of Transport, the marine exams for deck officers and
engineers. Publications bring in revenue of around #100,000 per year.
International consultancy work in areas like Africa and the Middle East
has also been developed vigorously.
According to Dr Don Giles, director of administration and finance,
Scotvec did not raise its fees from 1984 to 1988 and there has been no
increase since 1993. ''As well as reducing fees now -- a happy
coincidence in our tenth anniversary year -- we are also planning to
enhance our level of service by providing our centres with more support
material, especially in the area of assessment where they have indicated
that they would particularly welcome it,'' he says, anticipating that
this measure, allied to the reduction in fees, will still leave Scotvec
with ''a modest surplus''.
Colleges, which have become increasingly concerned about their
financial health since they assumed self-financing status two years ago,
will certainly welcome the smaller fees to be charged by Scotvec. Dr
Giles estimates that an average-sized establishment will save at least
#15,000, while Aberdeen College, the largest in Scotland, will benefit
by around #25,000.
It all serves to confirm that Scotvec has come a long way in 10 short
years. An organisation which rewards its customers with fee reductions
is certainly sending out the right messages. In due course it is to be
merged with the Scottish Examination Board and that should enhance
further the esteem in which its vocational qualifications are held.
Nor will it be adversely affected by the recent news from south of the
Border that General National Vocational Qualifications (GNVQs), which
were supposed to become England's ''vocational A Levels'', have come
under heavy criticism. Whereas GNVQs were introduced hastily and with
minimal preparation, Scotvec had firmly laid the ground for its recently
launched equivalents, General Scottish Vocational Qualifications
(GSVQs). National Certificate modules, from which GSVQs are formed, had
been established for a number of years and were already enjoying
enormous popularity when GSVQs were implemented on a phased and
controlled basis. Now they have been given the Scottish Office's stamp
of approval by being included in the unified curricular framework
proposed under ''Higher Still'' and their future is assured.
</TEXT>
