<HEADLINE>The cover-up job</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>HILDA MCLEAN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>AUTUMN FASHION</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976306363</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AMID a season of vintage classics, the Bentley of the fashion world
has to be the big camel coat.
Stylish and cosmopolitan, the big camel coat belongs to the great
cities of the world and can stride out to take lunch anywhere from Paris
to London, from Tokyo to New York.
It is also the perfect foil -- not to say overcoat -- for this
season's natty little suits delicately offsetting the more sombre colour
palette from plum through to grey, brown, and black while at the same
time providing a visual counterpoint to this year's sometime affair with
pillar box red and monochrome tones.
In terms of styling, the field is open from straight sixties' numbers
through to expansive swing coats meant to be worn open and flowing. In
terms of 1995 acceptability, bigger coats are all the better for
wrapping around this autumn and winter's tailored suits.
However, whatever their colour, coats will generally provide a
semblance of modernity over the range of 1940s to 1960s inspired attire
on display. Coats after all are a reasonable investment from which we
expect a return of more than a year. Generously cut the emphasis is on
bulk and warmth for a hard-working exterior which battles with the
elements and wins.
</TEXT>
