<HEADLINE>Return of the ice queen</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>HILDA MCLEAN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>AUTUMN FASHION</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976306364</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
In this 16-page Herald supplement, Hilda McLean cuts a dash through
awesome autumn and wonderful winter wardrobe essentials.
GOING into autumn 1995, it is obvious that in sartorial terms we are
entering another era.
To call it a new era would be incorrect, for many will see it as
turning back the clock to days when ladies wore gloves, hats, and
carried neat little handbags which didn't bulge with work accoutrements.
After a good few seasons, when the wearer called the shots with
slap-dash clothes, this year sees the en masse return of strict
tailoring and good grooming, last seen on any grand scale in the late
fifties; clothes this season maketh the women.
There have been a few warnings in winters past, but in 1995 the big
push towards proper dressing kicks off in earnest.
Natty little suits, in their many variations from skirt to trousers or
shift dress and jacket, neatly profile the female form and recall those
icons of chic Audrey Hepburn, Jackie O, and Grace Kelly.
All women of another era, who in their heyday were not exactly
feminist heroines, they are being held up as the way forward for fashion
this season. Their role is not as the definitive template as in the
past, but as the inspiration for clothes redolent of the structured
forties and fifties with their nipped-in waists and air of well-groomed
presentation which cuts across nationalistic boundaries bringing
together the most sophisticated of American and European influences.
As others have already stated, after decades of dressing women as
everything from starlets to harlets in pantomime or even boudoir gear,
this time round the designers are going for something a lot more radical
. . . they want us to be neat and tidy.
But they want us to be chic while we are doing it. For some this will
spell a return to the power suit. And there are a few hints of sharp
reds and scary stilettoes around. However, the look this season is more
the little woman who wields her power quietly behind the scenes; a woman
whose high maintenance costs are discreetly dealt with by the charge
card and are never arrogantly or brazenly flaunted.
Certainly it is not all about being saintly spick and span. Modern
women's recognition that she need never slavishly follow the dictates of
fashion in contradiction to her lifestyle means that the design houses
can not lay down the law. Nor can they afford to take too narrow a
perspective on any new emerging direction.
Tailored suits are not always tight; some are even kittenish with mini
A-lines and cute collars straight out of the sixties. Fake fur prints on
skirts and trimmings also increase the swing factor and pump up the fun
level. Further undermining of the pristine profile presented by the
season's outerwear comes from the lingerie section, where it is evident
decadent designers are creating some rich concoctions too precious to
keep hidden.
At the teenage/club end of the market, there is some dabbling with old
sixties' thoughts of space age clothing which in terms of the mass
market will work its way through in the acceptability of metallic and
brightly coloured gilets and puffa jackets. However, a word of warning,
these are strictly for the young at heart.
The new mood will of course have a knock-on effect across the dressing
spectrum but many favourites from the last few seasons can be reined to
accommodate this change in direction and others will remain with us as
well-loved friends.
Floaty florals can be brought into line with belts while comfy and
easy knitwear will probably always have a place in the Scottish market
-- and what could be wrong with that.
Men are also having to sharpen up their sartorial act in the new
season as structured, tailored clothes become the norm. For men this
means the re-emergence of the sharp suit for all. Part 1950s English
gent, part 1960s Mod, the 1995 suit might not demand a short back and
sides but it will require good grooming and grace.
The knock-on effect for men is that even the casual sector will
experience a change of direction with simple easy-to-wear but
essentially neat clothes taking over from layers and sporty gear.
</TEXT>
