<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>AUTUMN FASHION</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976306365</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
POWER dressing has sloped off in terms of ''superbitch'' shoulders,
but a quieter, more assured confidence is evident, particularly in the
suits inspired by Jacqueline Kennedy Onassis.
This, after all, was a woman who may not have been at the fore
heedlessly busting males' bastions like Baroness Thatcher, but as Jack
Kennedy's wife Jackie was the power behind not just a token throne but a
potentially globe-obliterating button.
Then as Jackie O, she was the channel for millions of dollars created
by the supertanker trade. The money from Aristotle Onassis and his ships
passed through her and then via the retailers into an economy lifted by
her sartorial spending sprees.
The keynote outfit for any Jackie O fan is the smart little shift
dress with matching jacket. Purists can find the essential Jackie suit
with a boxy jacket in the Olivier Strelli range, but at Pied a Terre
they have some easier-to-wear forties-style jackets which are not cheap
but in the middle range of prices.
These are teamed with more sixties-style shift dresses which are
designed to look good with or without a turtle neck underneath,
providing an outfit which can glide through the dying days of humidity
and then cope with the chill in the air. Boucle material created from
wool looped together with other fabrics provides a base for long wear
with a softer feel.
House of Fraser also has some natty matching dress and jacket suits.
Look out for Peter Pan collars for a flying-high fashion touch. Like
Pied a Terre, matching skirts are available for three-way options which
provide the most mileage.
Another label to check out for a nifty shift dress suit is the Grace
Collection, which as the name suggests is a design house which
implicitly understands elegant styles and its collections over the past
few years have borne this out.
Its Jackie O contribution is a beautiful A-line shift topped by a
wider-collared jacket which is available only in a rather appealing
dusky pink colour they call blossom.
</TEXT>
