<HEADLINE>Sound bites from the news hounds</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ROBBIE DINWOODIE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>23</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>976306366</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
CONSIDER this. There was much wailing and gnashing from within Tony
Blair's inner circle last week over the leak of the internal strategy
document which proclaimed that Labour was not yet ready -- at least at
the time of writing seven months ago -- to take over the reins of
Government.
What was interesting, however, was the direction in which this spleen
was vented. While some anger was turned inward to the more responsible,
this was not the main focus. After all, when the inner circle excludes
the deputy leader and a number of other veteran figures in the party at
a time when policies and alignment are being radically altered, a degree
of friction is to be expected. No, what caused real outrage wasn't the
source of the leak but its recipient, the Guardian newspaper.
Not only had a historically left-leaning newspaper taken possession of
such a gifthorse to the right, it had resolutely declined to examine the
story's dental health before allowing it to canter across its front
page.
The stewards in due course inquired. Employing a phrase to be used
within two days by Tories infuriated by a leak highlighting flaws in
their education policy, a Guardian reader wrote expressing himself
''incandescent with rage'' at the paper's calumny and betrayal of the
Labour Party -- seemingly oblivious to the irony of the fact that for
years fellow readers have railed against the Tory props of what used to
be Fleet Street for their dogged refusal to bite the hand that feeds.
Let's be clear. Hands that feed should be bitten from time to time, if
only to demonstrate that the watchdog is still awake and in possession
of at least some of its fangs.
But the Labour leader's camp could not see this. Mr Blair himself,
fresh from a lengthy courtship ritual involving press magnate Rupert
Murdoch, complained that the Sun had supposedly given fairer coverage to
his TUC speech than that which appeared in the Guardian.
But wasn't this the whole point of him currying favour with News
Corporation? ''It (the Guardian) is as bad as the Express and Mail,''
whinged one Blair aide. The complaint was made to the Sunday Times, a
newspaper which itself, although a bastion of the right, splashed new
revelations on the guns-for-Iraq scandal and carried another story about
the power struggle at the top of the Conservative Party. Neither Mr
Blair nor his ubiquitous aides leapt in to complain over this turn of
events.
Newspapers align and realign all the time to some degree, whether that
comes as a matter of internal policy, or external change in the
political circumstances or even down to individual commentators and
their sources. If former Tory loyalists in the press sometimes take the
muzzle off, for whatever motive, it is rich for the left to demand
lapdog complacency.
Journalists in some newspapers, and you are reading one now, are like
strays who go without muzzles at all times. Terriers rather than pit
bulls, we're expected to have regular nips at passing politicians of all
colours if only to remind them that we're there. Some other red-fanged
beasts in the press pound are fed only a certain flavour of meat so that
they acquire a particular taste.
Contrary to the saying, some dogs learn new tricks in their mature
years, managing to sit on laps licking the faces of those they used to
savage. One such is sitting just across from me as I write this in the
press area of the Liberal Democrat conference. He learned a new bark
under a new owner.
For it is the hand on the leash that remains paramount. Sometimes it
is an extending lead but by definition that still means it can be yanked
in, the hounds dragged back. At this time in the political cycle -- that
is late mid-term -- there are bones to be gnawed on and most are given a
long leash. Are Tony Blair and John Prescott falling out? What about
similar suggestions involving Michael Heseltine and Brian Mawhinney, or
Alex Salmond and some of his senior colleagues? Is Michael Forsyth's
reincarnation as a liberal innovator real?
Journalists given a long leash to sniff around questions like these
will in some cases be hauled back in when an election looms and owners
insist on a show of loyalty.
Closer to the General Election it will depend which hounds have owners
with fixed political views and at that time Opposition party leaders
will become grateful once more for the strays, even those who have
nipped their ankles.
In the case of last week's controversy the point is that Seamus Milne
got a damned good story for the Guardian and the paper ran it. Good.
Another leak on the failings of Tory education policy burrowed its way
out and newspapers of all political persuasions ran with it. Good. It is
what they are there for.
Into this fermenting late-mid-term brew north of the Border comes an
additional ingredient -- the Forsyth factor. Where before the Scottish
Office was a quiet place of which we knew little, the new incumbent
there is determined to turn St Andrew's House into the noisiest show in
town, something we cannot fail to notice. Behind this lie perfectly
sound reasons to do with his own political survival in his Stirling
constituency but it is fun none the less.
Michael Forsyth has plunged in, making him the centre of the Scottish
political scene from Day One. Cuddling up to Campbell Christie of the
STUC, saving the sleepers, plunging into controversy over drug
trafficking in tranquillisers and even turning community service into a
place on the chain gang, the former ideologue seems little concerned
about the coherence or consistency of his efforts. Pragmatism is all and
the Secretary of State may suddenly leap into the political traffic to
stop the bus and send it off to some new, unexpected destination.
All of this, of course,  makes him highly newsworthy across the media
spectrum for now but it won't be long before the hounds scent blood and
sink their teeth in.
</TEXT>
