<HEADLINE>A sporting chance of real values and goals in Paradise</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DICK LOUDEN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>EDUCATION</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976306367</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Dick Louden finds much to commend in giving pupils a taste of Celtic's
''level playing field''
CELTIC Football Club and Strathclyde region have entered into a joint
initiative under which groups of around 25 secondary pupils, accompanied
by teachers, attend Celtic Park on match days. They are guests of the
club and watch the match but the initiative is about much more. It is
about fostering values at a formative age.
It is part of an overall PR strategy, just approved by the Celtic
board of directors, which incorporates a social charter embracing the
history of the club and the principles it stands for. ''Celtic is more
than a business,'' said PR manager Peter McLean. ''It is a social
institution.'' He offers the reminder that in 1888, when the club was
founded, dreadful poverty and child mortality in the east end of Glasgow
awaited the many Irish immigrants who settled there and that the club
was set up by Brother Walfrid to feed the starving children. The name
Celtic implied a bridge of culture across the Irish Sea.
Since then, according to Peter McLean, ''Memories have become clouded
and there are sectors of the community where it is still believed that
the club stands for bigotry.'' In its new strategy Celtic is therefore
reaching out across the community, involving not only schools but also
job clubs, rehabilitation projects, hostels for the homeless and the
East End Drugs Initiative.
Last season, when Celtic was in temporary residence at Hampden Park,
it ran its innovative scheme with schools on a pilot basis, with over
200 pupils enjoying the experience of a day at the national stadium.
Interestingly, most of the schools were non-denominational. ''Our club
aims to be seen to be open to all people,'' said Peter McLean. ''As well
as promoting football and portraying the club's history accurately, we
are keen to have pupils thinking in terms of proper values. We are also
sponsoring equal opportunities and this year we shall be inviting ethnic
minority groups.''
The initiative, strongly supported by chief executive Fergus McCann,
began when Stephen Joyce, acting as educational consultant to Celtic in
a voluntary capacity, contacted Strathclyde region, which readily
offered cooperation because of the potential links with personal and
social development. ''The scheme has conditions attached to it,'' said
Stephen Joyce. ''As well as fitting in with the 5-14 Programme and with
subjects like modern studies and PE in third and fourth years, it also
complements the initiatives on values being implemented by the Scottish
Football Association with the personal encouragement of team manager
Craig Brown. Pupils are expected to undertake certain work before,
during and after their visit.''
On match days the pupils have a reception and light refreshments and
are then guided through a discussion for 20 minutes on topics of their
own choice. This is followed by the chance to meet some of the players
and a club director. Now that Celtic are back in their superbly upgraded
stadium, there is also a tour of the trophy room, currently the proud
guardian of the Scottish Cup.
Before the game the pupils are issued with matchday files, asking them
to consider the importance of positive values in football like fair
play, appreciation of skills, respect for opponents and team spirit.
They are also asked to write down their impressions of the stadium, the
atmosphere, the supporters, the entertainment, the police on duty and
the ambulance and first-aid personnel.
Back in school, they are invited to devise a ranking in order of
importance of a number of values -- not only fair play, respect and team
spirit but also success, tolerance, individuality and loyalty to your
team.
Of over 160 questionnaires returned, the values attracting the highest
levels of support have been success, team spirit and appreciation of
skills, in that order. Intriguingly, individuality has come last. That
should please Michael Forsyth in his campaign for team sports!
Celtic's school guests this year are going to find an enormous buzz
about the place. So many season tickets -- around 26,000 -- have been
sold that a waiting list is being drawn up. The new era brought in by
Fergus McCann will mean a continuous search for success, sporting and
commercial, and it is significant that, amidst this revolution, the club
is finding time to reassert basic human values.
The first school to be entertained at Hampden Park under the scheme
was Hillhead High in Glasgow, and some of the pupils were recently
invited to Celtic Park to see the new facilities. In charge was guidance
teacher Brian Griffin, who explained that some of the pupils had never
been to a football match and some staff had never seen Hampden, never
mind inspecting the press box or meeting a director. ''The pupils asked
very pertinent questions of the players, such as -- 'Do you play for the
jersey or the money?' ''
Michelle Moran, in sixth year and a Celtic supporter, felt that being
invited to sit in the directors' box ''had a good effect on you''.
''You felt you had to hold back -- it taught you not just to shout out
all the time. I can always admire good play in other teams. I think
Brian Laudrup is great.''
Rajdeep Juttlay, a fifth-year pupil, had never seen a senior football
match until Celtic invited her. ''It was a really good atmosphere,'' she
said. ''I like good sportsmanship -- like accepting decisions and
getting on with the game. Bad sportsmanship is showing anger if a goal
is scored against you.''
Fraser Steedman, also in fifth year, is a Rangers follower. ''I used
to think it was tremendous if somebody beat Celtic -- especially Raith
Rovers in last season's Coca-Cola Cup. Now, after meeting the Celtic
players, I feel it was a bit of a shame the way they lost. They're just
normal people. I've heard Rangers supporters talk appreciatively about
good play by Celtic -- they may not applaud but they say it.''
</TEXT>
