<HEADLINE>Turning them out ship-shape</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>GERALDINE ABRAHAMS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>15</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>APPOINTMENTS EDUCATION</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976306368</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Geraldine Abrahams discovers a remote further education college which
is building on the traditional seafaring skills of the Hebridean people
FOR the people of the Western Isles, as for any island population, the
sea is a major influence on the way of life, and has been a determining
factor in the economic survival of the communities there.
It is significant then that this year, Scotland's most remote further
education college, based at Stornoway on the Isle of Lewis, has provided
one of the world's largest cruise ship companies with a number of its
engineering officer cadets.
Living in a remote environment, cut off from the commercial and
industrial infrastructure of the mainland, island dwellers are likely to
view the sea as presenting a double-edged sword, both creating a barrier
which limits options and at the same time providing a vital source of
employment.
Fishing has played, and continues to play, an enormous part in the
island economies. Ferry travel too provides direct and indirect job
opportunities both on the ships as well as on shore, and for the past
two centuries, the merchant marine has been a third major employer for
many Hebrideans.
In the 1970s and 1980s however, the increasingly competitive
marketplace together with the world recession forced the shipping
companies to rationalise their crews and take on foreign recruits at
much lower salaries than their British counterparts.
This had a very serious effect on the Western Isles where there has
always been a tradition of going away to sea.
A recovery in the 1990s has meant that the merchant marine has become
a fruitful source of employment once again, and the engineering students
who have completed their courses at Lews Castle College in Stornoway,
one of the smallest and most remote colleges in the UK, have been well
prepared to take advantage of this, particularly through the strong
links that have been forged with P&amp;O Cruises.
Out of 24 Engineering Officer Cadet places offered by P&amp;O Cruises this
year, eight were from Lews Castle College -- four mechanical engineers
and four electrical engineers.
In total, 35 former students of Lews Castle now work with P&amp;O Cruises,
four are with P&amp;O Containers and another four are employed by TK
Shipping.
This sound relationship between the world-renowned marine company and
the college on the Scottish island has been built on a foundation of
mutual respect and need.
It began in 1983, when the company recruited three cadets from Lews
Castle, together with those from colleges in Hull and London. The steady
increase from that time has been a testament to the skills and qualities
of the Lews Castle College students.
''These islands have a long seafaring tradition and it is most
encouraging to see young people acquiring practical skills and
qualifications which lead to good employment with prospects, but
maintaining a home base here on the islands,'' said Kenneth Paterson,
assistant principal at Lews Castle College.
The college runs two courses which produces students technically
eligible for a career with P&amp;O Cruises. They are the Higher National
Certificate in Electrical and Electronic Engineering (via a National
Certificate in Electronics or by direct entry with Highers) or the
Higher National Diploma in Multidisciplinary Engineering (via a National
Certificate then Higher National Certificate in Mechanical Engineering
or direct entry to that with Highers). Howevere, as P&amp;O clearly state,
there are other qualities that help decide who would make the most
suitable officer cadets.
''P&amp;O look primarily for engineering skills, but we also look for
students who are able to adapt to life at sea,'' said David Colclough,
senior fleet personnel officer at P&amp;O Cruises. ''It is also important
that the officer cadets are polite, well-mannered and smart. People
going on cruises have spent a lot of money, so they expect courtesy from
the staff.''
The cruise ships usually have around 800 staff and while most are
involved in the ''hotel'' side of the operation, there are occasions
when the ship's maintenance staff will come into contact with
passengers, as David Colclough explained.
''The main part of the job is the operation and maintenance of the
ship's main and auxiliary engines, but it also entails looking after the
'hotel' equipment and air-conditioning unit.''
The starting salary for the Lews Castle College cadets is #6000 pa
plus all travelling expenses, full board and luxury liner food as well
as a full uniform allowance.
When the cadetship is completed, the salary rises to #17,000 pa tax
free, and senior engineering officers can earn up to #40,000 per year.
While it is impossible to predict the future with any real certainty,
P&amp;O are confident that jobs in the merchant marine will be secure.
''I have absolutely no doubt, the way the fleet is expanding,''
assured John Marden. ''We have just launched a new ship, the Oriana, an
addition to the fleet. This is an expanding business and P&amp;O is one of
the largest operators within it.''
And a long-term relationship with Lews Castle College? ''We have been
promoting liaison with Lews Castle, and we are very happy with
everything. They are good lads.''
</TEXT>
