<HEADLINE>SUIT YOURSELF</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>HILDA MCLEAN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>AUTUMN FASHION</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976306369</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A LONG hot summer passed natty little suits by, leaving thousands of
tightly tailored jackets and skirts hanging trim but forlorn on shop
shelves. But the time for the forties-style suit has definitely come
with the arrival of crisper mornings and darker evenings.
While they were undoubtedly too warm and constricting during the
heatwave, tailored skirt suits are just the ticket for coasting through
the last remnants of an Indian summer into a damp Scottish autumn.
Implicitly smart, they can walk out alone when the days are dry or be
gilded by a raincoat when the weather eventually turns They also work
underneath the season's big camel coats.
The raison d'etre of this season's suits is not of course just to be
neatly convenient underneath outer layers, but marks a vital turning
point in today's dressing, away from grunge into careful grooming last
seen on younger generations in the late fifties and early sixties. These
are not clothes which can be flung on, they will require to be zipped up
in some instances and will invariably need dry cleaning.
Two icons of chic hold the key to this season's suits -- Audrey
Hepburn and Jackie Kennedy . . . before she became Jackie O. Both were
fragile to the eye but strong in character without ever seeming to
chastise -- real ladies in other words.
Clever dressing which does not so much reveal one's assets as make the
most of them is the hallmark of dressing like Audrey and Jackie. In
terms of suits this means efficient tailoring which curves with the
woman, trim on the shoulders, tight to the waist and gracefully cups the
hips without any cheap sashaying.
Jackets have much tighter guidelines, being required to hug the figure
on an hourglass while ending at the hip bone which may draw some eye
lines to unfortunate ripples or rumples on less than taut muscles. The
effect, however, on svelte but womanly curves will be sensational
without straying into tart territory.
Some of the choicest jackets and suits are available from German
labels Verse and Gerry Weber, with the latter providing an array of
colours from light green to yellow, and purple to grey, to take the
wearer through the different shadings of the season, while Verse offers
some really bright alternatives.
Women who want to cut straight to the chase and go for ''knock 'em
dead'' glamour in a classic mode should check out the suits from Clasen,
which were surely never made to go to any ordinary office . . . unless
it is an office straight out of Hollywood Husbands or LA Law.
Berlin-based Clasen delivers high-voltage power suits which don't so
much recall the fragility of Hepburn as the Germanic strength of Marlene
Dietrich.
As in the last couple of seasons, Dietrich savvy is evident in a
number of trouser suits on the market. High fashion demands tight,
straight-leg trousers but the reality of the marketplace is that roomier
trews still dominate, with Planet offering some of the best no-nonsense
trouser suits around.
Another label to check out for suits is Louis Feraud, a design house
which has largely stuck by feminine but serious dressing and knows just
how to gild the lily with the right amount of contrast and trimming for.
Olivier Strelli is a design house which also understands the merit of
suits which can go the distance, with neat waists which work with or
without the belt and a variety of jacket lengths for women who play to
their strengths whatever the season's dictates.
The hottest material for the cold winter, which is bound to punish us
as a payback for the hot summer, is boucle. Boucle is often recalled as
that bubbly wool that tends to characterise clothes in second-hand
shops. As we hit the mid 1990s, however, boucle is generally smoother
and smarter -- this is boucle which reeks of unforced confidence and
dash.
Man-made fabrics certainly wear well these days and can mimic most of
the originals and produce some startling innovations nature could not
begin to replicate. For suits, wool is the word -- even if it isn't wool
in the original instance, but a man-made product. Central to this
season's suits is a lightweight but quality feel and wool is the look.
</TEXT>
