<DATE>950919</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Dust down the power puffs</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>HILDA MCLEAN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>AUTUMN FASHION</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976306370</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THERE are people who actually ask whatever became of puffa jackets?
Think about it, why would a fashion item as terminably practical as a
puffa jacket go out of style?
The answer is implicit in the tone of the question, because a lot of
its adherents were women talking across a generation gap at their
teenage daughters.
In terms of high fashion, puffa jackets really only held sway for
something like a half term in the early eighties, and then horrors of
horrors -- the ''mums'' got them. So it is a surprise to find that in
the mid nineties, to wear a puffa jacket is really to get on down . . .
This time around they either have to be bright, bright, bright or
resonantly metallic.
Occasionally puffa jackets can be moody in adolescent black but the
spectrum is largely off the wall -- and uncomplementary to shopping bags
-- in orange, silver and bronze.
The Weekender range from House of Fraser has black, gold, red and pink
for outerwear in which to really pump it up.
A new contender in the sexy suit market, Clasen even has a padded
jacket and matching skirt set, with fur trimming, available in the
juiciest orange for those who share a silhouette with Kate Moss and want
to dabble with curves.
Gerry Weber, a label which usually epitomises sensible good taste has
a padded jacket and gilet set which could stretch beyond the teen years
with aplomb but only on thirty or forty somethings who are decidedly
young at heart. At its best in deep steel, this twosome could go
anywhere and do anything on top of jeans or even pin-striped trousers.
The key is to combine the almost masculine metallic tones of the
modern puffas and gilets with feminine colours such as pink mohair and
shining bright light steel hues.
Combinations which can definitely work together and apart can be found
in the Gil Bret collection, with a gilet so shiny that it has to have
been recently polished. Other metallic possibilities crop up under the
Verse label as sexy gilets and trousers; with the latter thankfully not
padded.
Padded jackets, as opposed to puffa jackets, which have quilting, can
stretch beyond the pelvic bone but generally speaking the styling is
again more young and streetwise than practical or mumsy with fun fur
collars and slap-dash belts with shiny black the preferred colour.
The thing about padding is that it only really works on slim frames or
otherwise one has then has to resort to slimming colours.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950919-000081</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950919-000081</DOCID>
<DATE>950919</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Big softies</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>HILDA MCLEAN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>AUTUMN FASHION</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976306371</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
KNITWEAR is not really making the running this winter, but big, bold
sweaters still represent a good investment buy.
Smart little twin sets are very much in vogue. For sweaters, flash
your charge card for some beautiful numbers which will go the distance
in your wardrobe for the next couple of years.
Olivier Strelli is a label with some darkly seductive sloppy jumpers
which can be pulled on and look sultry even if it is the morning after
the night before.
Emreco, which is a Glasgow-based knitwear company, has a good slew of
chunky jumpers which look relaxed without descending anywhere near
grunge or grubbiness.
Lucia, which it has to be said is one of the more innovative names in
knitwear, is showcasing a wide variety and choice for weekending women
who want to relax but look good at the same time. Intricate patterns are
being displayed alongside a nice selection with Nordic influence with
sweater, cardigan, gilet and shawl combinations.
Start with a slim knit and then pile on a wool waistcoat and then a
matching cardigan, or go for a matching sweater and skirt (or trousers)
with shawl for top to toe warmth in or out of doors.
Big chunky-necked sweaters with matching sloppy pull-on cardies are
another attractively indulgent possibility being offered for the winter
by the Rodier label.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950919-000082</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950919-000082</DOCID>
<DATE>950919</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Legs making great strides</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>HILDA MCLEAN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>AUTUMN FASHION</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976306372</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WHEN glamour and seductive allure are to the fore, legs are invariably
part of the pretty package, either peeping out from long slit skirts or
curving gently from this autumn's trendy knee-line hem or boldly
striding out from under a pelmet.
Well-shaped legs are a bonus whatever but this season they will also
have to be groomed and impeccably turned out as the vogue for
sophisticated real dressing continues. Thankfully the hosiery companies
are turning out some of the best hose ever to grace a glamorous pin.
And getting back to cooler temperatures, tights and stockings will be
welcomed by many women who were caught out by a sticky hot summer and
confined their hose-less wally legs to the glare-free zone of long
skirts. Now that the mercury is at long last plummeting in those
thermometers, the bronzed legs of Greek goddesses are no longer required
and white or pale limbs can skip about in 60 denier uncluttered by
swathes of material.
Sixty denier is of course not the only option available. A variety of
quality sheer tights are on the market to take a leggy lady through from
an Indian summer into winter, particularly alongside the transitional
light wool suits which will be making and appearance or two on our
streets in September and the early days of October.
All the best companies from Elbeo to Pretty Polly and Aristoc are
offering sheer tights in either light or skin-tones which will flatter
the residue of pastel suits and balance nicely with the emerging camel
and chocolate coming through in the middle of the season.
Women who take their fashion seriously will of course eschew tights as
the move towards forties-style tailoring takes hold. But that does not
necessarily mean reverting lock, stock, and suspender to stockings. This
is the nineties after all and we do have mod cons.
The mod con in this instance is the hold-up, which admittedly has not
always held up well in the past. Hose makers are however these days
highlighting the extensive prettiness of the lace-tops which have grown
in size and importance to provide better staying power.
Lace tops to check out or flaunt are cheekily period nylon with Pretty
Polly and decidedly fetching and no pinching with the Italian Phillipe
Matignon label.
Daytime chic is provided by matt hose, but evenings are the time to
rev up the glam pedal and put on a show in the form of some sheen.
Glossies -- of the tight and stocking variety as opposed to the mags --
are big news this season when the sun goes down but how much light and
sparkle you shed on your legs is your choice.
Fatal glamour is a new line of sheen tights from Wolford which will be
available in stores from October. This new introduction follows on from
the unveiling of the seamless fatal line last year, with the format
extended to include special yarns which refract light producing a
lustrous sheen. Colours range from high fashion skin tones and pastels
to darker hues through to black.
Dim is a French label which has made opaque tights sophisticated but
this season it is also introducing a range of ''metallise'' tights in
lighter deniers in which a girl can steel herself for a night on the
tiles in shades of silver, black, gold and white.
Elsewhere night-time does not have to mean a journey into black with a
surfeit of light tights around, enlivened here and there with a
sprinkling of glitter that can be gold or platinum silver for megaton
1950's stardom.
Hue is a name which over the last couple of years has consistently
spelled innovation. This year it not only offers metallics and opaque
lustres but gets ultra wild with snakeskin knee-highs and tights for the
girl who really knows how to curl up in front of the fire.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950919-000083</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950919-000083</DOCID>
<DATE>950919</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Nights on the dazzle</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>HILDA MCLEAN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>AUTUMN FASHION</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976306373</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
GOING out into the night with a generous measure of sleekness is the
message for evening wear this season, but there is more than one way to
shine. Two schools of thought permeate the evening wear market -- one
very marked direction is the tuxedo line and the other is the slinky
evening dress tipped with the sparkle of sequins in which to hit them
midships. Either way the mood has to be sensual and sultry rather than
light and frothy.
Tuxedoes have been an empowering trend for working women socialising
on a network level, adding the spice of a woman challenging the status
quo in what has traditionally been perceived as male wear with the added
conundrum of the undeniably sexual appeal of a woman in men's clothing.
What they do not have to be, are trouser suits. The pioneering has
been done and now the tuxedo sector has opened up to include
satin-collared jackets which can trip the light fantastic along with
crepe skirts and seductive bodies.
From a man-style suit, the idea of the tuxedo has been expanded to
include more decidedly feminine variations and this has also allowed the
development of the evening wear market into separates which accord
better with a career woman's sensibilities and tend to have a longer
life in the limelight since separates can be mixed and matched to ring
the changes.
For separates read a wide range of night-time slants on daytime
staples from the well-established palazzo pants to leggings, A-line
skirts, and shift dresses. All of the above have this season been
drafted into the evening wear market but packaged in glamorous materials
such satin, silk, and velvet to pack a punch in luxury terms.
Again taking the cue from the tuxedo, the emphasis is on wearable
clothes which are more about how modern women perceive themselves than
garb for male accompaniments. These clothes put forward a womanly
perspective of sexy and attractive . . . without being diminutive.
Not that these garments are plain or unadorned. Women also know the
power of details, which can be played up to their full potential in
evening wear separates, with such variations as necklines picked out
with beading, scalloped edges, slit pleats and sequin additions.
All of which have also led on to the new idea of the two-piece evening
dress with a precise silhouette that is tailored yet soft; the implicit
hardness of glamour with a feminine touch. Glamour is the overt message
but it is glamour over which women have the control.
Jackets are very much to the fore either in tuxedo form or bolero over
skirt sets or cocktail shift dresses for studied elegance. Louis Feraud
backs the return of glamour with a selection of sequinned dresses
matched with nifty bolero jackets while its range of brocade print
jackets are worn with either satin or velvet skirts. Trimmings such as
beads, seed pearls, ribbon edgings and furs provide dramatic allure.
The Louis Feraud Set takes inspiration from the tuxedo with a new
twist for its cocktail creations, such as soft shouldered jackets with
satin lapels to go with narrow pants for a less rigid turn on an
established favourite, while strappy dresses have short, sharp jackets
for added sass.
Escada Couture is a new name to play with taking this label to fresh
heights of glamour which, it has to be said, still fully acknowledge
that the woman is in the driving seat while sticking some changes of
Hollywood gear.
Most definitely for the high maintenance woman however, variations it
is offering this season include Shimmering Nights with sequins and jet,
suspended on sheer silk georgette and Shooting Stars with rhinestones
scattered on taut tank dresses with tiny little boleros.
Sometimes only a full-blown dress will do for that glittering
occasion. Shimmer and lustre also hold sway on the Vera Mont label which
this year has gone for both long slimline shapes and flowing dresses in
rich velvet, crepe, and chiffon. Luminosity is provided by contrasting
panels of duchesse satin, lurex and lame.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950919-000084</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950919-000084</DOCID>
<DATE>950919</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Creature comforts</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>HILDA MCLEAN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>AUTUMN FASHION</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976306374</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ANIMAL prints and fake fur are not exactly an innovation but it is
interesting to note the times when they come around and are accorded
acceptability. Certainly the heyday of animal prints always seems to
coincide with moves by designers to steer women towards tailored
clothes.
What are they giving us? A chance to project animal magnetism and wild
abandon within the confines of sharply tailored lines? Then again, furs
go hand in glove with the days of tight suits and zipped dresses when
chic females were seen as cosseted little women.
It is to be hoped that the psychology this time around is to let women
have a little fun and be a touch wild. There is more than a glint of
Marianne Faithful running with the Rolling Stones in the sixties in the
emphasis being given to the leopard spots and cheetah prints for autumn
1995, while marabou edging on knits places the wearer firmly in the days
of the baby boom generation.
A classic little suit of our times was knitted to be wild by Fenn
Wright &amp; Manson with a fake fur collar and a silk A-line animal print
skirt which is decidedly swinging sixties.
Betty Barclay lets rip this season with a highly fashionable offshoot
collection called Secret Agent Girl, for women who can outgun 007 and
whose tailoring and good taste is their bond. Smart but intrinsically
fun, this collection includes some of the sassiest animal prints around
on tight short skirts in striking black and white, for girls who don't
want any grey in their lives. Perspective and greater wearability is
delivered with black jackets which only go to the edge with matching
animal print on the collars.
More subtle wild women should consider the Marc Cain collection, which
is relatively new to Scotland. Amid a collection which delivers
brilliant brights and working greys on this season's natty suits, it
also has some untamed dresses and jackets in primeval dark fake fur,
with which the wearer can inject some life into more standard shift
dresses or suits.
With black on black, these prints can live either in the daytime or at
night with the ease of a slinking panther, taking the wearer for a walk
on the wild side without requiring a whole-hog safari into the jungle.
A sophisticated take on animal magic is delivered by Louis Feraud,
which this season has the essential chic three-piece suit for maximum
clawing power. Comprising a three-quarter length A-line jacket trimmed
with leopard print cuffs and pockets, this suit goes with a totally
leopard print wool mix skirt and silk blouse.
You can, however, feel wild without going out looking like an animal?
The re-emergence of fake fur may be too heady for many, but an easy and
inexpensive way to run with the pack is to add accessories in animal or
snake print. Bags, hats and even gloves are all available in ''beastly''
forms but the simplest addition could be a leopard or snake print scarf
to imply understanding of the season's essential mores without going the
whole hog.
