<DOCNO>GH950919-000085</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950919-000085</DOCID>
<DATE>950919</DATE>
<HEADLINE>The thing to top it all</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>HILDA MCLEAN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>11</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>AUTUMN FASHION</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976306375</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AUTUMN is the season of all seasons, when a week can include anything
from a summer day to the coldest of afternoons. Its changeability can
make steering a sartorial course difficult when rain and shine compete
for dominance often within the same half hour.
Pastel hues and white are de rigueur for the emerging sixties look.
Cotton tops in pastel hues can also help ring the changes without any
loss of face or tanned advantage. It is more than acceptable this season
to wear traditional autumnal clothing enlivened up by light summer
colouring around the face. Tones which will do the business include icy
pinks and mint greens as well as the odd splash of yellow.
September is usually the month for packing our summer gear away and
bringing out the heavy duty wear, but thankfully a few items can stay
out of the trunk for a month or so without looking completely passe.
A little belt will provide an amazing amount of additional mileage for
fitted floral dresses though an A-line roped in with a belt may threaten
to look more 1950's teenager than sophisticated siren. Another essential
little extra is the short cardie which ends at the waist.
The long floral satin skirt is one for the trunk, but its shorter
sister can easily come out to play. The cue is again to recall the
forties by topping it with a woollen twin set and then use some
colourist nous to link it to the floral theme. Sweet pink jumpers are
honeys over black satin skirts printed with roses. But always remember
the essential slim belt for that vital waisted appeal.
Though it is officially dead and buried, the legacy of grunge is the
acceptable mixing of different weight fabrics, which means frothy
knee-length skirts can do another turn in the company of the chunkiest
of knits as the weather turns cooler.
Close knit bodies with high necks and long sleeves will earn their
money thrice over this season with the emergence of the shift dress and
jacket suit. Such bodies can obviously go out on their own upfront with
a standard skirt or trouser suit but they will be a vital extra when it
comes to allowing shift-struck women to wear these dresses as November
and December take hold.
Sports-inspired gear offers the best and laziest options for weekends
of uncertain weather, with an initial lycra layer close to the chest and
then baggy oversweats. Tight sports clothing still gets the nod at clubs
and some of the most ladylike labels around, such as Escada, now have
sports ranges making this kind of gear more than acceptable.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950919-000086</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950919-000086</DOCID>
<DATE>950919</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Into the blue</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>HILDA MCLEAN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>11</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>AUTUMN FASHION</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976306376</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A SHORTHAND staple which will instantly revitalise any dowdy old skirt
or trouser suit is the blue satin shirt.
It can be no coincidence that some of the top fashion magazines have
featured the shiny blue shirt on their front covers. This is a shirt,
which in fashion parlance, has legs and will be the one to wear.
Satin or otherwise, it is essential that the shirt is dark blue but
lustrous and has the crucial pointed collars.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950919-000087</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950919-000087</DOCID>
<DATE>950919</DATE>
<HEADLINE>On the curve</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>HILDA MCLEAN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>13</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>AUTUMN FASHION</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976306377</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
HIGH-octane lingerie which has to be seen to believed -- and
frequently will be -- is being offered this season.
Amid classic collections of respectable allure, the top design houses
are also trailblazing with what have to be some of the most brazenly fun
pieces this side of Jezebel's heyday . . .
Then there are the completely see-through items, which lingerie houses
openly admit are truely chatelaine.
Valisere this year presents its first seamless cup bra, Vincennes, in
semi-transparent, feather-light crepe trimmed with Swiss guipere, but in
complete contrast it also has the pre-formed cups of the Gambetta bra
and body.
Charnos is a label which talks about ''underwear as outerwear for
vampish versatility'' in its press release for autumn/winter 1995, which
is a fair indication of where most of its range is coming from.
Even its Arcadia range, which is lingerie designed along sporty lines
for underwear which moves with the wearer, is described as ''ultra
sensuous'' and it is, using a shimmering Tactel fabric which gives
sporty shapes a forties-style femininity.
This year Gossard introduces a startlingly simple idea -- the
cami-bra. Essentially this garment has the cut-across chestline of a
camisole with bra seaming for support round the sides, effectively
replacing two garments with one, which is altogether more practical and
comfortable.
Elsewhere, interesting colours have been conjured up by Lovable and
include chestnut and rose for its delicate Gemme-Ambra range and its
special Giada range, aimed at the Christmas gift market, which is
available in sultry hues of blue, ivory and jade.
Ballet this season introduces its Jewel range which heightens its
Hollywood style allure by working two sexy shades alongside each other.
Its silver/black colourway is particularly effective in recalling the
silver screen.
Bodies have long crossed over from underwear into an essential
component part of most working women's outerwear wardrobes but a new
move by Wolford this winter will throw the role of bodies -- the
garments that is -- back into confusion.
A good selection of its bodies are wholeheartedly sturdy outerwear
which will do a good job, keeping the wearer in check under business
suits and with jeans.
But the Wolford range also includes some cutting-edge transparent
numbers -- with matching hose -- which have the panache required for
outerwear but may be just a tad too see-through for women who don't want
to reveal all outside the boudoir.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950919-000088</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950919-000088</DOCID>
<DATE>950919</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Scarlet fever</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>HILDA MCLEAN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>AUTUMN FASHION</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976306378</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
GIVEN that the pen is mightier than the sword, the way this season to
be decidedly deadlier than the ''mail'' is to wear pillar box red and
underwrite your visual pulling power.
Incontrovertibly this season's hottest colour is red -- a no-punches
pulled red which will sock any viewer in the eye. A very shocking
contrast to the neat lines of this season's tailored skirts and jackets,
this kind of red surprisingly works best on suits -- where it turns up
the volume on demure tailoring.
Great blocks of red across matching skirts and jackets are the route
to take for women who want to blast their way through the office
politics and take no prisoners in their wake.
But thankfully it is not all about being red or dead. One screaming
red suit should be in every wardrobe, but the real standby staple of the
season is the good old tartan or plaid jacket, which to be at its most
effective should include a touch of blood to remind the red coats of the
250th anniversary of Culloden.
Tartan cannot however just be romantically inclined to be a hit this
season. To be in vogue, tartan jackets -- whatever the clan -- still
have to follow the season's tight tailoring with neat waists.
Betty Barclay and Mondi -- names which originate in Germany -- have
some of the best tartan jackets and other bits and bobs, including the
essential mini kilt, for autumn 1995.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950919-000089</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950919-000089</DOCID>
<DATE>950919</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Action man bows out. . .</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>HILDA MCLEAN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>AUTUMN FASHION</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976306379</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MEN'S suits this season are a hard-working amalgam of two distinct
styles, which may well have been seen as incompatible in previous years.
After all how could a distinguished English gentleman possibly
associate with an Italian-influenced Mod? It may have taken the
sartorial equivalent of the melting furnace -- going back to the drawing
board -- to do it, but that is obviously what this season's designers
have done.
The result is a season of suits which are impeccably English and
delectably rakish and will need grace and a galley-load of good grooming
to carry them off.
The essential emphasis is on a straight lean body with two-piece suits
doing the business without any recourse to a waistcoat, coordinating or
otherwise.
The English influence means that these suits do not then descend into
parody, with the proportions kept sensible and unobtrusive. Shoulders
are stout but not in the Sylvester Stallone mode; trousers are straight
but not calf or thigh hugging while never getting overblown or
billowing.
This may sound like the suits the ''suits'' have been wearing for the
last couple of years, but this time round the influence is certain to be
wider spread, cutting into the territory of casual man in unstructured
outfits in areas more usually associated with freer styles such as the
arts. Suits this autumn are a style statement rather than a uniform for
the boardroom.
The styling of the suits will undoubtedly recall the sixties for many
but the colours are anything but psychedelic with standard black,
browns, and dark blues the backbone of the choice available. A slim and
youthful outline is offered but this is a very straight-edged look.
When suits become a shade lighter in tone they tend to be tweed but
like the women's sector this is not the tweed of the country but the
city with subtle striping and herringbone emphasising the English gent
effect. The colouring is, of course, gently grey.
This being Britain -- and Scotland in particular, rain and overcoats
are part of the package. Indisputably wool overcoats are in, straight
from the sixties and straight in line, while raincoats are
quintessentially Anglo and masculine, meant to be worn loose rather than
tightly belted.
Smartly pressed shirts are de rigueur but again we are talking nothing
loose, but the slightly tailored shirts which run alongside the body and
moulded collars provide the right straight edging.
Where men can afford to lighten up is with their ties, which have been
reserved as an area for Mediterranean flair and fancy. Brighter colours
which can sit well against navy and black shirt and suit combinations
strike a blow for liberty and the rights of the individual. Just about
everything is up for grabs though the pairing will have to be done with
flair and style. Ties provide an opportunity to lighten up the overall
effect but they should not drown the inherent English gent within this
season's suits.
Men's casualwear is also sharpening up this winter with the emphasis
less on the sporty, big, and baggy and more on refined textures and
softer fabrics.
The new accent is on clothes which are comfortable and easy to wear
but essentially neat and tidy and certainly not hanging out.
Sportswear generally gets short shrift with lycra and sweat materials
losing sheen away from the gym or the football park. Even golf
references are this season looking stylistically under par for the man
of the moment.
Nor does it remain acceptable to go for the wild man of the mountains
look; this season the note to hit at the pub or the country hotel is not
Iron John but urbane man taking time out from any rigorous activity.
These are clothes in which to walk and talk, but not necessarily
conquer mountains or run with the deer. But at the same time, these
clothes have the energy for daily life and do not look like unmade beds.
Overcoats are functional in muted forest tones but they no longer
belong lock, stock and barrel with the huntin', shootin' and fishing
fraternity or with those who want to appear so, while knits are simple
in earthy or no-nonsense tweed tones made to be pulled over a hidden
T-shirt but not part of an assembly of ever-emerging layers.
In effect, what is happening is a simplification of garments and a
pull-back from the overdressed or all-action look without cultivating a
totally lived-in look.
Simple, understated casual clothes are the way forward for the season
with less emphasis on flash dressing up or snazzy waistcoats, or for
that matter crumpled cottons.
Plaid shirts are with us forever, it seems, when it comes to the
casual sector, but again this season they have been refined and are no
longer from lumberjack country but are often smaller and more discreet
checks in finer materials.
The Classic range from Mudie is a diverse selection of separates with
a large range of fabrics and yarns in earthy neutral colours cleverly
blended with Oxford stripes and jacquard designs for a more
sophisticated take on country shirts.
Double Two this winter is introducing a small amount of wool into its
shirt styles to give a warm handle to plaids and checks in seasonally
correct shades. In addition, the Double Two collection also offers a
herringbone design in soft tones for the cold winter nights has
introduced baby cord in shades of wine, cream, navy, chocolate and olive
for added warmth and comfort.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950919-000090</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950919-000090</DOCID>
<DATE>950919</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Mother's pride</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CHRISTINE FOX</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>AUTUMN FASHION</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976306380</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE day when any mother watches her daughter glide elegantly down the
aisle and into the arms of her husband is a day to remember.
Mother-of the bride outfits have always been important, but now that
the video age is in full swing with a cameraman as much part of the
proceedings as the ordinary wedding photographer, outfits for the mother
of the bride, groom. . . and all the other guests, are chosen even more
carefully. It's not only the wedding album that capture them for
posterity -- it's a living, moving videotape which can, and probably
will be, played on numerous occasions.
With the relaxation in dress code for the bride and groom and the rest
of the wedding party, mothers can also feel more comfortable if they
choose to go out on a limb from the usual type of dress or skirt suit.
It's fair to say that some outfits which suit the big day, have as
much use afterwards as daughter's floaty fairytale number.
Practical mothers will go for something classic which can be dressed
up with the obligatory hat and perhas gloves for the wedding, but worn
comfortably afterwards.
Autumn and winter weddings don't have to mean thick woollen outfits
for warmth as mothers will spend most of their time outdoors in the
comfort of a chauffeur-driven limousine.
Something more substantial than light summer fabrics will be needed,
and mothers who shudder at the thought of wearing pastels will be happy
to choose from richer colours in the winter ranges.
The choice of what to wear is almost overwhelming. There are skirt
suits, with skirts of all lengths -- the Jackie Kennedy look so
prevalent at the moment will suit most ages, although older mothers will
probably comment that they remember having things like that in their
wardobes ''first time round''.
Suits composed of a dress and jackets can be even more graceful, with
the added bonus of being able to forgo the worry of the right top.
Mothers who prefer trousers can also find suits of all styles and
colours to blend in with the occasion.
For traditionalists, there are time-honoured mother of the bride
outfits to be found in most collections. Plain colours are usually most
flattering, and easier to find accessories for, but there's no harm in
venturing into a colourful tartan or a plain colour teamed with black
for emphasis. Everyone knows -- the idea is to shine without taking the
spotlight away from the bride.
Those as a first-time mother of the bride should remember an important
part of any outfit -- somewhere to keep the all-important tissue.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950919-000091</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950919-000091</DOCID>
<DATE>950919</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Public agony in bid to unmask killers</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JAMES FREEMAN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976306381</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Home Affairs Correspondent James Freeman asks whether the television
appeal by relatives in murder cases is becoming too exploitative
TELEVISION still has the capacity to shock us, whether it is with
images of famine victims, the shattered bodies of ordinary Sarajevo folk
hit by a mortar round -- or, just as topical, the distraught relatives
of a young murder victim appealing for information.
Despite the modern syndrome of compassion fatigue, few of us fail to
be moved when a youngster like 15-year-old Emma Jones looks out at us
from the screen and describes how she found the mutilated body of her
best pal, Naomi Smith. A potent message comes across which, hopefully,
will help bring the killer to justice that much more quickly.
It is little different when the son of the Inverurie social club
murder victim broadcast last night, the major difference being that he
pleaded for his father's killer to give himself up, which is unlikely to
happen.
The idea is the same, however: that those suffering perhaps a conflict
of loyalties will be swayed by the obvious image of suffering and will
either turn the killer in or supply vital information which helps the
jigsaw pieces fall into place.
The appearance of emotional relatives has, however, now become
more-or-less an everyday occurrence, giving rise to at least some
disquiet that detectives now see such media appearances as a convenient
shortcut or that television has become a substitute for the real thing.
Has the whole idea become too exploitative?
The reality is that while the exact origins of the high-profile
appearance of relatives is lost in the mists of television mythology, it
was very probably not the detectives who first thought it. The received
knowledge is that they merely responded to pressure from the media and,
principally, from the insatiable maw of television which requires
round-the-clock sensation to fill the yawning hours of air time.
There is another aspect which should not be dismissed and that is that
very often the relatives of the murder victim, while clearly traumatised
and grief stricken, are as often as not eager to assist in bringing the
killer, or rapist, or child abductor to book.
The National Association of Victim Support Schemes reflects this when
it points out that it responds to the needs of victims and some -- it
does not know exactly how many -- are keen to enlist media help.
''We try as best we can to reduce the trauma to relatives of victims.
Our policy is not to tell people what to do but we can help them to make
an informed choice. We give them as much practical help as possible,''
the spokesman adds.
The police are largely unrepentant about the use of victims' relatives
in murder hunts and it is difficult to fault their logic. One senior
detective with a long record of tackling intractable cases in Glasgow's
toughest areas said really effective policing was only possible with the
wholehearted support of the communities affected. The use of television
is, in these terms, just an extension of the appeal for witnesses in the
local paper of 20 years ago.
Detectives tracing a murderer still use the more conventional means,
of course, such as door-to-door inquiries, and these still account for
much information. That intelligence, often low-level, often anonymous,
is vital in piecing together the movements of key players, and once the
field has been narrowed down some of the other techniques may then turn
up trumps.
Recent advances have meant, for example, that the automatic
fingerprint recognition system installed at the Scottish Criminal
Records Office increasingly comes up with ''cold hits'' -- unknown
prints left at a crime scene matching those left at another crime scene
where there is a possible suspect.
One force in the South of England is pioneering a data bank of 30,000
prints of shoes of different types and manufacture to narrow the field
down quickly when a shoe print is found at a crime scene. The English
DNA data bank which holds ''genetic fingerprints'' of known criminals
recently came up with its first random match. Practically the only brake
on the perfecting and wider application of such swiftly advancing
forensic technology is the reluctance of government to resource costly
programmes.
These tools can only come into play when there is a suspect in the
frame and the major problem facing detectives these days is the
reluctance of people, particularly in high-crime housing areas, to stand
up in the witness box and say what they have seen or what they know.
The police, particularly in Strathclyde, are tackling that problem
head on. Only last week the chief constable, Leslie Sharp, placed
Michael Forsyth, the Scottish Secretary, on the spot on this issue
during his Paisley visit, eliciting a very public pledge from Forsyth
that he would raise the issue with the Lord Advocate.
One suspects he can raise witness protection until he is blue in the
face but the Lord Advocate's dusty answer will be something along the
lines that it is everyone's public duty to give evidence regardless of
intimidation, real or imagined.
Professor Steve Bruce, the Aberdeen University sociologist, agrees
that ''information received is still the main way of pointing the police
towards the likely suspect'', so that the television appeal is a
legitimate tool. He agrees that it can bring a sense of purpose and
usefulness to traumatised relatives at a time of maximum stress.
In Scottish terms, there is no argument that the media's fight for
market share has played a part in making the up-front television appeal
a common occurrence.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950919-000092</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950919-000092</DOCID>
<DATE>950919</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Party game cocktails</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>GEOFFREY PARKHOUSE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>ANNUAL CONFERENCE</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>976306382</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Geoffrey Parkhouse examines the possible Labour/Liberal Democrat
concoctions that could make the next General Election go with a swing
for Blair and Ashdown.
PICTURE a scene in Tony Blair's office at the Commons in about a
month's time. Whiskies poured, Blair and Paddy Ashdown begin to talk
about how they might combine their efforts to get the Tories out. At
once they hit a problem -- the most important policy question of all,
the timing of the next General Election.
If the two leaders are really talking seriously they will address the
next big problem with co-operation. Ashdown's party needs proportional
representation voting reform to give it substantial political clout.
Blair is not that keen on abandoning first-past-the-post to decide the
government of the country.
He is committed by his predecessor, John Smith, to hold a referendum
on the issue. Ashdown will want to know who is going to write the
question for the referendum and what it is going to say.
The Liberal Democrats are acutely conscious that any government can
pose a referendum question to get the answer it wants. Ashdown is
already appalled that Blair's commitment to devolution will not now
extend to England. If there is any meaning to Labour and Lib-Dem
co-operation the question posed for the PR referendum is vital.
About this time next month, when the party conference hype is out of
the way for both Blair and Ashdown, would be the earliest that the two
men might have a get-together.
Blair's Shadow Cabinet decided yesterday that they would start to
detail Labour policy at their conference in Brighton next month. They
will need to float a few details to see how they go before the November
28 Budget when the lines of battle for the next General Election are
likely to be drawn.
Over the past three years in particular the Labour Party and the
Liberal Democrats have between them taken over local government in
Britain and learned on the ground to run councils to the exclusion of
the Tories. But there is no sign that Blair and Ashdown are ready to
enter into a General Election pact -- neither of their parties would
stand for it.
For one thing, the Labour Party thinks it's going to win anyway, and
for another, Ashdown has only 24 MPs, although he boasts that this is
the most powerful third party representation in the Commons for decades.
Ashdown has declared that he could not work with another Tory
Government and that the old policy of ''equidistance'' between the two
major parties is dead. Blair mischievously applauds this on the eve of
the Liberal Democrat annual conference in Glasgow. It does him no harm
to do so, but it causes, as usual, a frisson in the Liberal Democratic
Party which is in two minds about how to get a stake in power.
Actual policy evolution in the Labour Party has brought the two
together more closely. Blair's New Labour is very close to the policies
of the now defunct Social Democratic Party on defence, Europe, and the
re-establishment of trade union recognition. They are very close on what
the old SDP used to call the ''social market partnership'' and
unwillingness to renationalise basic industry.
Party democracy -- one member, one vote -- is more or less in place
and Labour and the Lib Dems agree on the Bill of Rights, a freedom of
information Act.
For the old SDP founders like Shirley Williams, Labour and the Lib
Dems are perhaps a trifle too close in general policy. Lady Williams
found it necessary to state yesterday that the Lib Dems are not up for
grabs. Constitutional reform still leaves the two parties apart. Ashdown
and his followers want devolution in England as well as Scotland and
Wales. They want an elected Second Chamber, whereas Blair is talking
only of abolishing the voting rights of hereditary peers.
The bald fact is that, despite what Blair and Ashdown might want to
concoct together, their parties may be closer to the reality. There can
be no shake-down deals until the electorate has declared its view on
General Election day. This does not stop Blair and Ashdown meeting to
talk, and their first opportunity would be mid-October when the Commons
returns for the final sittings of this session of Parliament.
By then Ashdown will have absorbed the policy utterances at the Labour
Party conference.
There is a lot that should attract both Labour and Liberal Democrat
policy makers in an honest approach to the electorate. But the old devil
of party politics always intervenes.
What is in it for devout Liberals or the rump of the SDP if their
electioneering efforts are only to ensure a Labour government without
them having a stake in it?
Already, yesterday, the Tory Party was making trouble for Blair and
Ashdown, with the party chairman, Dr Brian Mawhinney, claiming that both
Blair and Ashdown are already talking about a hung Parliament next time.
In short, any talk of Labour/Liberal-Democrat co-operation is exploited
as defeatism by the Tories. Underlying this is a similar view taken
particularly in the Labour Party at this stage in the political cycle.
We return to the two items that really count. The Prime Minister has
geared up for an election in 1997 -- or so he says. It must suit Blair
to try to force him to the polls before that -- next spring, or next
autumn. What timing suits Ashdown, who has declared that his number one
priority is to get the Tories out?
Can the two of them devise a tactical deal, perhaps involving the
Ulster Unionists and their new leader David Trimble, to force Major into
an earlier General Election. Would Ashdown abandon the holy grail of the
Liberal Democrats -- PR voting -- to do so? It is unlikely that the
putative Prime Minister Blair would concede to Ashdown the posing of
that PR referendum question.
By next March, with these constraints on co-operation in mind, it
could turn out to be every party for itself in a General Election again.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
