<DOCNO>GH950919-000093</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950919-000093</DOCID>
<DATE>950919</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Eye injury fails to defeat shinty star</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976306383</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
INTERNATIONAL shinty player Gordon MacIntyre yesterday refused to give
up the game, despite a horrific eye injury.
Although the Oban Camanachd defender concedes his playing career is
over, he plans to move into refereeing and coaching, even though he has
lost the sight in his left eye.
He was struck in the face at point blank range by the ball during last
Saturday's match at Kingussie.
Surgeons at Raigmore Hospital in Inverness were unable to save his eye
and he was yesterday recovering from the operation and coming to terms
with having to finish playing the game he loves.
One of his first visitors was Michael Clark, the Kingussie player who
struck the ball in Mr MacIntyre's face, and was deeply upset at the
outcome.
''It was a complete accident. I have no hard feelings towards him at
all, it is all part of the game,'' said the injured player.
But the 29-year-old admitted that the injury would now prevent him
playing at the highest level.
With his wife, Sharon, at his bedside, he said: ''I could carry on
playing if I wore a protective faceguard, but that would be more
frustrating than anything. You have got to meet a standard. If you can't
meet that, there is no point playing.''
But such is his love for shinty, Mr MacIntyre has vowed to continue
being involved in the game, either through coaching or refereeing. ''It
is too much a part of my life to let it go,'' he said.
He began playing at the age of 14, and had established himself as one
of the top players in Scotland. He was due to play for Scotland against
Ireland at Fort William on September 30.
An electronics engineer, Mr MacIntyre was so committed to the game he
had been commuting from Londonderry in Northern Ireland to play each
week for his home town.
He even decided to change jobs so he could be closer to home, and is
due to begin work in Livingston next Monday.
Mr MacIntyre expects to leave hospital on Friday.
Shinty has been one of Scotland's fastest growing sports, and head and
hand injuries among players have soared in recent years.
Medical experts were so worried about the trend that they commissioned
a special survey.
Although it is not clear if a headguard would have prevented Mr
MacIntyre's injury, detailed research has shown that injuries to players
are more frequent and severe than in any other sport.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950919-000094</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950919-000094</DOCID>
<DATE>950919</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Dentists seek to extend low cost scheme</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ALISON DANIELS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976306384</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
DENTISTS who launched their own private dental care scheme in the
Highlands two years ago now hope other Scottish dentists will form
similar schemes in an effort to provide low cost treatment for patients
in the face of proposed NHS cuts.
Yesterday in Glasgow, directors of the Highland Dental Care Plan
described the success of the Highland scheme, which includes 58 of the
region's 63 dentists and has more than 7000 patient subscribers.
They warned of further Government plans to cut NHS treatments -- such
as crowns on back teeth and bridge work -- and said their scheme was the
only way forward for dentists who found themselves increasingly
frustrated with such cuts and crippled by escalating materials costs.
At a meeting with dental practitioners from across Scotland at the
weekend, the Highland dentists announced the formation of IndepenDent
Care Plans UK, which will offer other groups of dentists back-up and
advice. The organisation also intends to meet with English and Welsh
dentists later this year.
Within Highland region the plan offers patients a preventive care
scheme at a cost of around #10 a month and an annual insurance premium
of #7.33 to cover emergency treatment anywhere in the UK. In addition,
patients are also charged dental laboratory costs.
One of the plan's directors, Mr John Jamieson, acknowledged the scheme
had come in for criticism but said the alternative for patients was
expensive private dental care or, in Highland region, up to nine month
long waiting lists for those seeking NHS treatment from Highland Health
Board's eight salaried general dental practioners.
However, a Highland Health Board spokesman blamed long waiting times
on the decision by the region's dentists to cease taking on new NHS
patients.
He added that the board had made a commitment to reducing waiting
lists to eight weeks by the end of the year, and he refuted the
suggestion that NHS dentistry was cheap, hole in the wall dentistry.
However, the IndepenDent Care Plan move was welcomed by the British
Dental Association's Scottish secretary, Mr Alistair MacLean, who said
the advantage of the scheme was that it was run by dentists and was
non-profit making.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950919-000095</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950919-000095</DOCID>
<DATE>950919</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Forsyth's pleasant housing surprise</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976306385</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A PLAQUE was unveiled by Scottish Secretary Michael Forsyth yesterday
to mark the #12m regeneration of a housing scheme.
It officially marked completion of the final phase of redevelopment at
Dundee's Mid Craigie estate, a change which, he admitted, was beyond
what he thought was possible.
The project, providing 255 new two and three bedroom homes for sale,
has won awards from the National House Building Council. It is jointly
funded by Wimpey Homes, Dundee District Council, and Scottish Homes
housing agency.
Mr Forsyth toured the development, speaking to local people. ''There
is a spirit of discovery in Dundee and a willingness to embrace change
rather than stand against it,'' he said.
''We will attract investment to Dundee by showing them the success of
housing developments of this kind. Frankly, not even I, who have been
arguing for these things for years, would have been persuaded that it
was possible to produce such a transformation as I have seen here.''
Scottish Homes chairman Sir James Mellon said it was an excellent
example of ''what we are trying to achieve: the development of
self-sustaining communities in the urban environment.''
</TEXT>
