<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950919-000096</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950919-000096</DOCID>
<DATE>950919</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Dounreay will not face pollution prosecution</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DAVID ROSS, HIGHLAND CORRESPONDENT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976306386</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
DOUNREAY will not face prosecution for discharging nitric acid into
the Pentland Firth after Highland River Purification Board yesterday
cleared it of damaging marine life.
The Herald revealed in February the nuclear facility had been making
daily discharges through a radioactive outfall for a decade, in
contravention of the Control of Pollution Act which carries a maximum
penalty of a #20,000 fine and three months in prison.
The board has no power over radioactive emissions, that being the
remit of HM Industrial Pollution Inspectorate, and in this case had been
concerned about acid in the discharges.
It did not know of the acid until 1993. Its annual report carried the
only public mention of the acid and said the Atomic Energy Authority was
told it must neutralise the acid or a report would go to the
procurator-fiscal.
It emerged it would take Dounreay nearly four years before it could
neutralise the acid. HRPB's director, Mr Duncan Buchanan, was not happy
with this time-scale and said he was preparing a report for the
procurator-fiscal.
Yesterday, however, the HRPB gave Dounreay a clean bill of health on
the discharges. Mr Buchanan was on holiday but a statement was issued
saying he had consulted the fiscal in March.
''Following advice from the procurator-fiscal the board appointed
private consultants, Environment and Resource Technology Ltd, to carry
out a survey into the impact of the acid effluent on marine life in the
vicinity of the plant's 'low radioactive' outfall pipe. The survey was
successfully completed in August this year,'' it said.
''The results of the marine survey and associated laboratory tests
have confirmed that there is adequate dilution and rapid neutralisation
of the acid provided by the outfall diffusers and effective mixing with
the salt water as the buoyant effluent plume floats up to the surface.
''No significant acidity was detected by the consultants at the
surface or a depth close to the outfall pipe. The results of the survey
work indicate clearly that there is no significant damage done to marine
life from the discharge of acid in the effluent from the plant and
therefore no breach of the board's discharge consents.
''As there was no evidence that an offence under the Control of
Pollution Act 1974 had been committed, the procurator-fiscal has
confirmed that he does not intend to initiate legal proceedings against
the UKAEA in this case.''
Mr Ian Shepherd, UKAEA spokesman at Dounreay, welcomed the report
saying it vindicated the plant's activities.
However, Mr John Martin, the Highland Green Party's nuclear spokesman,
condemned the announcement as a ''whitewash''.
</TEXT>
