<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950919-000097</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950919-000097</DOCID>
<DATE>950919</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Greens' ethics</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>CORRESPONDENCE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>976306387</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ALF YOUNG seems a little confused about the difference between
pressure groups and political parties (Jaded ethics of the Greens,
September 15).
He says he has not signed up as a Friend of the Earth or Greenpeace
supporter ''partly because . . . journalists owe it to their readers not
to carry any party card''. As far as I am aware neither of these
organisations is a political party.
It may interest Alf Young and your readers to know that the Scottish
Green Party developed from the UK Green Party which itself was
originally called the People Party. The environmental emphasis grew with
the realisation (at which some parties have yet to arrive) that an
ailing environment cannot support a healthy thriving population or a
healthy thriving economy.
Green politics (as opposed to green pressure activities) is about
addressing social and environmental problems in a commonsense manner. To
that end the Scottish Green Party has radical proposals to alter the tax
system from taxing work, as at present, to taxing resource use; to
replace the present cumbersome and divisive benefits system by a basic
income scheme; to replace local taxation which penalises development by
land value taxation which encourages proper use of land, to name but a
few.
Our concerns and those of pressure groups may coincide at times but
are not identical because as a political party we have a complete
manifesto not just a set of environmental policies.
On the issue of the Greens ''losing support'', I should point out that
across Europe Greens have enjoyed great electoral success at all levels
of government, and the Green group is the fourth largest in the European
Parliament.
In Scotland our membership is rising faster now than at any time since
our best electoral showing of 1989.
The issues are still there, and so are we.
Eleanor Scott,
Social Affairs Speaker,
Scottish Green Party,
8 Culcairn Road,
Evanton,
Ross and Cromarty.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950919-000098</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950919-000098</DOCID>
<DATE>950919</DATE>
<HEADLINE>First stage of NHS defence</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>CORRESPONDENCE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>976306388</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
I NOTE with interest that in your leader column (September 18) you
identify the Liberal Democrat commitment to raise income tax by 1%, if
necessary, to provide better education as the best-known Liberal
Democrat policy. You also suggest that the party does not have a
revulsion for higher taxes for a good cause and that this may apply to
the National Health Service.
You are indeed right to say that that we are committed to defending
Britain's public services. We do not like high taxes but we recognise
that quality public services need proper funding. This may require
higher tax or may be obtained from other sources.
However, we also recognise that we have to set priorities and that we
need to seek imaginative solutions. We cannot raise income tax to
provide new funds for all government departments.
This week the Liberal Democrats will discuss a proposal for the
earmarking of increases in tobacco tax to the NHS. It is a policy I
wholeheartedly support. It is not only an effective preventative measure
-- the success of which can be seen in Canada and Australia -- but it
will also provide valuable resources for an underfunded NHS.
A 5p increase in tobacco tax would pay for our commitment to free eye
and dental checks alone, a policy you will be hard-pressed to find in
Labour or Conservative documents. This would be the first stage of our
defence of the NHS.
Alex Carlile, QC, MP,
Liberal Democrat Health Spokesman,
SECC, Glasgow.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950919-000099</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950919-000099</DOCID>
<DATE>950919</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Alcohol warnings</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>CORRESPONDENCE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>976306389</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE article headed ''Euro MP in drink health warning'' (September 15)
contained some interesting comments from Dr Rae of the Portman Group.
First, Dr Rae does not disclose the fact that the Portman Group, his
employer, is financed by the eight largest breweries and distilleries in
the UK. I suspect there might be some self-interest in trying to play
down my attempts at labelling alcohol containers.
Secondly, Dr Rae indicated it is premature to look at the question of
labelling as there is little research into the topic. He ignores the
fact that labelling is the norm in the USA and Canada and extensive
research into this issue has confirmed the benefits of labelling.
Dr Rae further states that 70% of alcohol consumed will be in glasses,
therefore a warning label is ineffective. While this is true, the
''designer drinks'' promoted by the industry and consumed by younger
people tend to be drunk from the bottle. The important point it that all
alcohol would be required to carry a warning. This is the issue worrying
the alcohol industry.
Dr Rae, I believe, is being somewhat economical with the truth. While
it may be true that the distillers/brewers spend #2m a year on health
education, they spend #200m on advertising their products. A bit of an
imbalance, don't you think?
Bill Miller, MEP,
9 Chisholm Street,
Glasgow.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950919-000100</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950919-000100</DOCID>
<DATE>950919</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Benefits from Temazepam</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>CORRESPONDENCE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>976306390</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
I'M very perturbed about the campaign now being operated against
Temazepam. If one only reads the headlines and lurid stories about the
addiction, it would appear that the villain of the piece is Temazepam,
instead of it being those who misuse it.
I've not read or heard one word of praise for the help it has been to
thousands of users, like myself. I had one problem -- my sleep pattern
was atrocious.
I'd be pleasantly tired, fall asleep almost at once, and waken about
3.30am, absolutely wide awake and quite unable to get back to sleep. I
don't catnap during the day to compensate.
On mentioning this to our caring and diligent doctor, he prescribed
one 10mg Temazepam at night, and from the very first tablet I've slept
right through till about 7am with no drowsiness during the day and no
side effects. So far as I'm concerned, the benefit has been tremendous.
It now seems to me that the usual old horror story is, once again, in
full cry. I can think of many substances once available and now banned,
not because of their danger but because some indulgent careless fool
misuses them and raises the hazard which would not apply if used
properly.
The majority suffer because of the carelessness of the minority!
Helen Neilson,
Ballewan Lodge,
Blanefield.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950919-000101</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950919-000101</DOCID>
<DATE>950919</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Punishment was not exemplary</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>CORRESPONDENCE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>976306391</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WE have just seen the end of a trial involving Nuclear Power and the
Nuclear Inspectorate. The judge said that he was awarding an exemplary
punishment and fined Nuclear Power #250,000.
Nuclear Power is a publicly owned company and any profit goes to the
Treasury. Likewise any operating losses are made good by the Treasury. I
understand the fines are also paid by the Treasury. Thus any shortfall
in profit is made good by the fine. Clearly you cannot withhold funding
from Nuclear Power for that may jeopardise safety.
Now both parties to this dispute are owned by the taxpayer and yet all
the taxpayer sees is a net outflow of his funds to lawyers. All the rest
is just book-keeping. At least that is how I see it and that view is
shared by those with whom I have discussed it.
I think we are owed an explanation why this is considered exemplary
punishment. If I were found guilty of an offence and the punishment was
to take money from my account and put it into my wife's, I would laugh
all the way to the bank.
Chris Parton,
40 Bellshill Road,
Uddingston.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950919-000102</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950919-000102</DOCID>
<DATE>950919</DATE>
<HEADLINE>In defence of waterskiers</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>CORRESPONDENCE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>976306392</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
JAMES Freeman had a fairly lengthy telephone conversation with me a
few days before his article, A wave of acrimony (September 11), and I am
surprised he did not refer to any of the points I made, for example, our
support of a compulsory boat driving test, which is not included in the
proposed by-laws.
Waterskiers are probably now the second biggest user group on Loch
Lomond and the vast majority of us are ordinary, decent folk going about
our recreation in an inoffensive way, often skiing as families. There is
certainly a small minority of hooligan waterskiers but they must not be
allowed to spoil things for the majority. The majority would very much
like to see the offending minority off the loch.
The Loch Lomond Waterskiers Association, which was formed last year
and now has some 480 members, is not opposed to the content of the
proposed by-laws except for one item which we consider is most
inequitable, the 7mph speed limit to a distance of 150 metres (almost
500 feet) which would apply to about 90% of the loch's shore.
This would unnecessarily, unrealistically, and unreasonably restrict
the opportunity of many local folk to enjoy their recreation of
waterskiing, a natural, exhilarating sport for people living in this
area.
To have a more or less blanket restriction round the shores when there
is hardly anyone about for so much of the time is most certainly an
unreasonable and unwarranted restriction on people's freedom, and
amounts to restriction for the sake of restriction.
In our view it would be much more appropriate if the few areas which
are subject to peak-time congestion were restricted, instead of the
unnecessary and unreasonable wholesale restriction of most of the loch's
shoreline. It would also be much more enforceable. How many folk can
accurately judge 150 metres over land, never mind water?
We appreciate certain areas also need to be restricted for
environmental and fish breeding considerations, and, given such
restrictions, it is not true to say waterskiing is environmentally
unsustainable.
Alternatively, if for some reason a near blanket shoreline restriction
must be introduced, we suggest the 150-metre distance is reduced to 50
metres. This would allow people looking for sheltered water to spread
around the loch while keeping fast craft, and waterskiers, away from the
shore.
Additionally, and importantly for family skiers of whom there are
many, the lesser distance would suit most children much better bacause
they often feel insecure and frightened far out from the shore, even
though they can swim, are properly kitted out with wetsuit and
lifejacket, and are not in any danger.
There are major items not included in the proposed by-laws which in
our view are very much needed: the compulsory boat driving test already
mentioned; compulsory third-party insurance; and a quantified
drink/drive limit the same as applies on the roads.
Boating of any sort and alcohol do not go well together. In the USA
80% of boating accidents involve drink -- a sobering statistic for many
loch users.
Ian Davis,
Chairman, Loch Lomond Waterskiers Association,
16 West Stafford Street, Helensburgh.
</TEXT>
