<DOCNO>GH950919-000103</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950919-000103</DOCID>
<DATE>950919</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Question about role of Sports Council</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>CORRESPONDENCE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>976306393</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
I READ with interest James Freeman's article on Loch Lomond by-laws,
in particular about the role of the Sports Council as surrogate objector
on behalf of a single minority group of loch users (September 11).
The Sports Council was established by Royal Charter in 1972 and the
objects are ''to foster the practice of sport and recreation among the
public at large and the provision of facilities therefor''.
By taking up cudgels on behalf of one sport which is regrettably
bedevilled by a minority hooligan element, how can this action be
reconciled with the charter object of fostering sport and recreation
among the public at large?
I would be most interested to know the answer, as I am sure would be
the many others who use Loch Lomond as a sporting or recreational
facility and whose enjoyment of that facility is marred by the
misbehaviour of the irresponsible elements among the power-craft
fraternity.
If the Sports Council is truly representative of all sports and
recreation, and it wishes to retain credibility, it must withdraw its
objection to the proposed by-laws immediately.
C T Keracher,
Ravenswood, Arrochar.
</TEXT>
