<DOCNO>GH950919-000105</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950919-000105</DOCID>
<DATE>950919</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Discordant note on finalists</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>CORRESPONDENCE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>976306395</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
I WRITE as one of many who left the Glasgow Royal Concert Hall on
Sunday night in a sense of rage and dismay at the impetuous and
ill-considered decision of the jury to change their own published rules.
On stage, in the presence of the four concerto finalists, the jury
chairman, Philip Ledger, inexplicably announced that the decision to
share a joint third prize of #4000 had been changed to third and fourth
prizes with respective amounts of #3000 and #1000.
As a consequence, a competitor who believed she had won #2000 was
placed fourth and publicly kicked in the teeth with her prize money
halved.
With the benefit of hindsight this decision must be regretted. If the
competition is to have any credibility in the future, a new chairman of
the jury must ensure that they agree to abide by their own decisions.
What a shame that a marvellous week of music and an evening of superb
performances from all four gifted soloists should end on such a note.
Ernie Smyth,
10 Cedar Court,
Kilbarchan.
</TEXT>
