<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950919-000106</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950919-000106</DOCID>
<DATE>950919</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Integration but not assimilation</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>CORRESPONDENCE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>976306396</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
CONGRATULATIONS on Peter Lynch's Herald essay ''A Scots Mosaic''
(September 9). The writer focuses on SNP attempts at creating an all
encompassing identity.
However, I do feel that Dr Lynch falls down in one area; an area long
mistreated in Scotland. One of the contradictory aspects of Dr Lynch's
essay is its unintentional but implicit application of the Norman Tebbit
cricket test.
Yes, immigrants and their offspring must integrate into their new
circumstances. This should be an aspect of an unwritten acceptance on
the part of all immigrants. However, integration should not entail
assimiliation.
Can we not be Scottish born and remain Italian, Irish, Asian, or
Chinese? As individuals, families, and communities, so long as these
groups contribute positively to society, it should not matter if they
have little affinity for the symbols of Scottish nationhood or culture.
Personally, although not an SNP supporter, I remain open to their
cause if it can be proved to me as representing the best way forward for
Scotland. But if I did vote SNP in the future, as third-generation
Irish, I would retain my Irish identity. Voting SNP would be a political
expression unrelated to my Irish identity.
Invariably, being born here and acquiring a Scottish accent means that
I am not the same as the Irish who are born in Ireland. However, that
does not make me less Irish, nor should it mean that I am excluded from
being a full participant in multi-ethnic Scotland.
I do not pass Norman Tebbit's cricket test, nor his inferred,
football, cultural, or political test. However, I will continue to
contribute to the well-being of an as yet to emerge, plural Scotland,
and in terms which correspond to my heritage and my immigrant identity.
Joseph McGarrity,
3 Main Street,
Coatbridge.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950919-000107</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950919-000107</DOCID>
<DATE>950919</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Borrowing concern. Gap much more than expected</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>LEADER</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>976306397</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
LAST week Mr Waldegrave, who is trying to contain his colleagues'
estimates of their spending next year, warned them that lower taxation
was possible only if they heeded him. It is possible to see the cause of
his concern in yesterday's figures for public borrowing, the amount by
which the Revenue's receipts fail to meet actual spending. The gap was
much more than expected and more than this time last year. It brought
the total up to more than that of the first five months of the last
financial year, exposing how the Chancellor's hopes for this year are
already seriously adrift. The calculation that revenues would grow, and
painlessly solve his problem, now looks shaky: to do that receipts must
grow at 11%, rather than the 7.7% so far experienced.
It is usually hard to forecast August's outcome and too much need not
be read into it, but the cumulative experience of the five months is
another matter. At the very least, any tax reductions budgeted in
November should be less than the Chancellor hoped, provided he sticks to
claims to remain prudent (and anything else would seriously dent his
standing in the City -- and the standing of sterling as well). Since
politicians tend to be professional optimists, and his buoyancy has just
been increased by the Governor of the Bank of England retracting his
demand for higher interest rates, Mr Clarke will be hoping that the
months which normally yield higher returns -- October, December, and
January -- will do exceptionally well this time. At this juncture no-one
can tell, but the present outcome is undeniably bad news.
It shows how high public spending actually is, however. In spite of
all the talk about cuts, these have not taken place; and even Mr
Waldegrave is finding it almost impossible to achieve them either, in
planned future spending. The momentum is so great because in almost
every area expectations of improvement are strong -- state spending is
an index of collective improvement. If we want that, it has to be paid
for.   As in previous General Elections, this will be a big issue, and a
head-on one next time. Last week a distinguished former economic adviser
to John Smith accused his successor of misleading the country on
financing his public spending plans. If the Government's scope for
restraining public spending is so slight, will not further improvement
be costly? And how will it be financed? Tories will hope that in these
questions lie their salvation -- but the voters' mood may be much less
selfish.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950919-000108</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950919-000108</DOCID>
<DATE>950919</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Hong Kong election. Democracy before Chinese control</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>LEADER</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>976306398</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WE need not pat ourselves on the back or smile smugly at the results
from Hong Kong's first substantial democratic election in 150 years of
colonial rule. The clue to what should be justifiable feelings of shame
lies in the length of time needed for this election to take place. Nor
is it sufficient to say, as many expatriates delight in claiming, that
there was no demand for democracy during the long years of Britain's
profitable overlordship of Hong Kong. Democracy is not a function of
genetics, nor is it imbibed with mothers milk. It has to be planted,
nurtured, and encouraged and this we signally failed to do until the
1997 return to China became inevitable. No wonder many Chinese from both
Hong Kong and the mainland accuse Britain of hypocrisy. None of this is
an argument against democracy in Hong Kong. Nobody is suggesting that we
should not have bothered, that we should have simply delivered a neat
little commercial oligarchy run by Hong Kong's businessmen into the
hands of Beijing. What we should have done was to embark on the entire
exercise a good deal earlier and if this sounds like hindsight, so be
it.
What happens next in Hong Kong is fairly predictable. True, the
pro-democracy camp did well in the election but the overall turnout of
voters was predictably low. Democrats failed to seize control of the
Legislative Council for the chamber appears to be roughly split between
pro-democracy and pro-China representatives. This will have little
effect on the tactics of the Chinese who will put a parallel Legislative
Council in place in the next few months. Hong Kong Government officials
persist in their belief that the Chinese will be reluctant to dismantle
the recent reforms because they do not want to alienate the people of
Hong Kong. If only this were so. After this brief taste of democracy
Hong Kong will revert to Chinese control and to Chinese ways. We cannot
say that this could have been avoided, but we could have tried harder,
and longer to ameliorate it.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950919-000109</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950919-000109</DOCID>
<DATE>950919</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Grahams' mother denies Christmas card 'threats'</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976306399</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
FORMER neighbours of the Graham ''family from hell'' received
Christmas cards which were not in the festive spirit, Kirkcaldy Sheriff
Court was told yesterday.
One bore the message ''flit'' and another warned, ''ho, ho, ho, your
day will come, ha, ha, ha,'' it was claimed.
The cards were allegedly sent to neighbours who gave evidence against
the Grahams, formerly of Alexander Road, Glenrothes, or who spoke out
against them in the press at the time of Glenrothes Development
Corporation's successful eviction action against them.
In court was Mrs Anne Graham, 36, now of North Street, Rosehearty,
near Fraserburgh, who denies five breach of the peace charges alleging
she caused fear and alarm to householders in Glenrothes, by sending
Christmas cards containing threatening messages on December 20.
The charges allege that the victims were Mrs Ellaline Wilson of
Pinkerton Road; Mr Ron Braid of Lundin Place; Mr Agnes Carr, Alexander
Road; Mr Colin Dow, Bethune Road; and the occupants of their homes.
One of the charges alleges that Mrs Graham also sent a card and a
letter to the home of Mrs Agnes Carr, both of which contained a
threatening message to the occupants of the house at 144 Alexander Road.
Mr Dow, 58, claimed an envelope addressed to his wife simply stated
''flit''; Mr Braid, 64, said his card bore the words ''ho,ho, ho, your
day will come, ha, ha, ha''.
Mrs Penelope Carr claimed one of two envelopes wrongly addressed to
her and delivered to her mother-in-law, contained a newspaper cutting of
her photograph with the words ''cons never lie'' on it, and also a piece
of paper stamped ''Her Majesty's Prison Barlinne'' bearing the
handwritten words, ''boys kill''.
Mrs Ellaline Wilson, 43, claimed an envelope addressed to her
contained a card with ''welcome to hell'' written on it.
Police witnesses told the court they had grounds to suspect the Graham
family and called at their home on January 8 this year.
Constable Michael Ward said he asked for a sample of Mrs Graham's
handwriting and was given a letter by her husband.
During interviews, Mrs Graham denied any knowledge of the cards.
Expert police witnesses said they could not tell if the writing on the
envelopes and cards, posted in Leven on December 20, was the same as on
the letter.
Two fingerprint experts confirmed that Mrs Graham's right thumb print
was found on the back of the card allegedly sent to Mr Braid, and her
left middle finger print was on the back of one of the envelopes
allegedly received by Mrs Carr.
Sheriff McIntyre continued the case until November 8.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950919-000110</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950919-000110</DOCID>
<DATE>950919</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Federation supports tougher punishment for young offenders 'who treat system as joke'. Scottish police back boot camps</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>LACHIE KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976306400</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SCOTLAND'S police are in favour of setting up American-style boot
camps and community service squads for young offenders who laugh at the
sentencing system.
The support for a Scottish revamp of youth sentencing follows the
launch south of the Border of a pilot ''boot camp'' scheme yesterday by
Home Secretary Michael Howard.
The pilot project, for 60 offenders aged 18 to 21 at Thorn Cross Young
Offenders' Institution in Cheshire, will open next summer with an
emphasis on discipline and hard physical training and work.
It will be followed up with vocational training, post-release
supervision, and an assessment of the scheme to be undertaken in the
spring of 1997. A study of reconviction rates will follow at the end of
1997.
Mr Howard said yesterday the new regime would be ''tough and
demanding'' with ''discipline and hard work its foundation''. Living
conditions would be austere.
Last week, Scottish Secretary Michael Forsyth addressed the issue of
community service orders, telling a group of Scots businessmen that
orders ''must involve hard physical work, not brutality, but visible
effort, with offenders clearing up motorways and beaches in protective
clothing which advertises what they are''.
The Scottish Police Federation yesterday supported the Thorn Cross
camp and the proposition of harder community service orders.
Mr Douglas Keil, the federation's general secretary, said the criminal
justice system had long failed to deal adequately with young offenders.
''Many youngsters who get themselves into trouble see the whole system
as a joke, something to boast about to their pals, compare notes, and
ultimately ignore,'' he said.
''Too much emphasis has been put on keeping offenders out of jail and
not enough on deterrent and punishment.
''Something the young offender does not like should happen on the
first occasion he is convicted. In that way, hopefully he or she will
not want to come back for more.''
A spokesman for the Scottish Prison Service said last night: ''We have
no plans for boot camps at the moment but will watch any developments in
England and Wales''.
Reaction to the Thorn Cross proposal from penal reform campaigners and
probation workers was mixed yesterday.
Liberal Democrat Home Affairs spokesman Mr Alan Beith said: ''Before
Michael Howard throws public money into boot camp proposals, he should
look at all the experience which shows that they are not effective in
cutting crime''.
Prison Service director general Mr Derek Lewis was keen to stress the
differences between the new regime and the ''short, sharp shock'' system
introduced by the then-Home Secretary William Whitelaw in 1979, which
failed in the mid-1980s.
While the Thorn Cross camp would put a great emphasis on discipline,
the new system was much more sophisticated than the earlier experiment,
Mr Lewis said.
Highlights of the inmates' day will include a 6am wake-up with a full
inspection and drill half-an-hour later. The afternoon will consist of
physical education with running, circuit training, and an assault
course.
Lights-out will come at 10pm with inmates forbidden to talk to each
other or communicate in any way after that time. Smoking will be banned.
During the 26-week course, young offenders will receive anger
management training, basic education such as the 3Rs, learning
day-to-day skills like opening a bank account, and help with learning to
take responsibility for their own behaviour, particularly in group
situations.
Mr Paul Cavadino, chairman of the Penal Affairs Consortium, said it
was ''astonishingly naive'' to believe a tough physical approach and
drills would produce law-abiding citizens.
However, he said: ''In some respects, however, the regime at Thorn
Cross differs from that of American boot camps. It will be an odd
mixture of the harsh and the helpful.
''The regime will combine a hard physical approach, which will do
nothing to reduce offending, with some constructive elements of
rehabilitation, which could do so.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950919-000111</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950919-000111</DOCID>
<DATE>950919</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Extension sought on water transfer</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JOHN MACCALMAN, MUNICIPAL CORRESPONDENT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976306401</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
STRATHCLYDE councillors have been caught on the hop over the
controversial transfer of council water assets to the new West of
Scotland Water Authority.
Meeting in private yesterday to consider the transfer agreement,
members of the Labour group executive expressed dismay that they hadn't
been warned by officials of today's deadline for submitting the
agreement to the Scottish Office.
Consequently, a meeting of the council's water services committee,
called to consider the agreement, lasted only three minutes with
councillors agreeing to ask the Secretary of State for Scotland for a
week's extension of the deadline.
Opposition parties had been anxious to discuss the agreement but were
prevented by the committee chairman, Councillor Alex MacLean, who was no
doubt mindful of the fact that this, one of the most momentous decision
in the history of Strathclyde region, had not yet been considered by the
ruling Labour group.
Afterwards, council officials were frantically trying to contact the
Scottish Office, but were being hampered by the fact that yesterday was
an Edinburgh holiday.
Councillor MacLean, explained: ''I stopped discussion on the matter
and delayed it for a week because we're still seeking information on
certain aspects.''
He added: ''The matter was just thrown at us after last Wednesday's
council meeting. The timescale of having to submit the scheme by
tomorrow is far too tight; so we've asked for a week's delay, which I
don't think is unreasonable.''
Councillor MacLean confirmed the council was co-operating with the
Scottish Office on the asset transfer. In his view there was no sense in
doing other than that.
And he warned that councillors faced the possibility of surcharge
should the Secretary of State not concede the week's extension.
The acting Labour group leader, Councillor John Mullen, admitted he,
too, had not be aware of the proximity of the submission day and had
made his displeasure known to those concerned.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950919-000112</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950919-000112</DOCID>
<DATE>950919</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Dangers of the contract culture. Growing job insecurity raises fears for the next generation of pensioners</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JENNIFER CUNNINGHAM</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>13</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>TABLE</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976306402</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE expansion of private pension schemes and old-age insurance schemes
is already expanding the market for private homes, both nursing and
residential. And one of the bonuses of community care is that these
private home owners are encouraged to blur the distinction, guaranteeing
care until death for people whose dependence increases.
People with the ability to pay are obviously able to choose any kind
of care they want, but there is a growing fear that today's short-term
contract culture will result in a very different scenario for the next
generation of pensioners.
The continuing proportion of unemployed and, worryingly,
never-employed people will be unable to make provision for themselves.
If the 25% of the Glasgow population who are on Income Support need care
in their old age, how will it be funded?
Right now, the businessmen are pounding their calculators because the
immediate market is set to grow at a compound annual rate of 2.5%. The
market in this case is the number of people over the age of 85 in need
of residential care.
Without a blush, they call it the care business and point to it
getting bigger in the sense of individual companies becoming larger as
well as in the sense of general expansion. Except in Scotland. While the
demographic chart mirrors the UK rise until about 2030, with a
subsequent drop, the increase in private care will -- on present trends
-- be less steady.
A forecast in the trade journal This Caring Business points to the
need for 70,000 extra beds in the UK by the year 2001 -- with no
increase in the proportion of each age-group over 65 living in homes.
Since the assumption that the extra beds are necessary is at odds with
the aim of the community care legislation to keep people in their own
homes for as long as possible, there is room for considerable discussion
over the figures. The 1991 census revealed that even among those aged 85
and more, only one-third are in residential or nursing homes or
long-stay hospitals. For those aged between 65 and 74, the proportion
drops to 3.8%.
As the range and ratio of community services increases -- as they are
supposed to do as a result of the Act -- that proportion could
reasonably be expected to drop until only those too dependent for
sheltered housing and support from home helps and community nurses,
would move into homes.
The care home owners argue that increasing private medical insurance
and the expected improvement in the property market will enable more
people to choose to go into a home, for reasons of security and
companionship, in preference to struggling with the burdens of
maintaining a house alone.
There is already evidence that local authorities prefer to place
people in single rooms if possible and that the major companies (mostly
English) with a chain of homes across the country are using their
financial power to build new purpose-designed units rather than adapt
the traditional rambling villas.
The scandals of multi-occupied rooms of the mid-80s are well and truly
over, but some care home owners in Scotland are convinced that social
work departments are still biased against the small, private homes.
Colin Barron, chairman of the Scottish Association of Care Home Owners,
says that whereas in England and Wales the Community Care Act had the
effect of local authorities closing down their directly-run homes and
placing people in the private sector, in Scotland it has meant that
social work departments have retained their own homes and fill them up
first, using the private sector as overspill.
He says that places in council homes can cost 50% more than in private
ones. The difference is mainly in rates of pay for staff. Councils pay
union rates, giving them significantly higher costs for overtime and
weekend working, but Dr Barron says the fact that they are not required
to be registered under the Act means thay have a staffing ratio of one
to 14 residents, while the private homes they register are required to
have a ratio of one to eight.
In Scotland 425 private nursing homes provide 1600 beds while 225
residential homes provide 4664 beds.
Like the voluntary sector, Dr Barron argues that the local authorities
which tie their rates to the DSS levels (between #197 and #227 for
residential care and #295 for nursing care) are underplaying the true
cost of a place. He claims that some local authorities have underspent
their community care budget and could afford to pay more and that their
refusal to do so is putting some home owners out of business.
He criticised social work departments for not costing home-care
packages to take account of all the public money involved.
The average age on admission to residential care is now 85 -- and the
average length of stay is only two or three years.
It is a significant change, partly due to people remaining in better
health for longer but also due to the enormous advances made in
community-based provision such as sheltered housing and home helps.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950919-000113</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950919-000113</DOCID>
<DATE>950919</DATE>
<HEADLINE>No Headline Present</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>CORRESPONDENCE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>976306403</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
I WRITE to express my dismay at the spoiling action taken by the
Sports Council in submitting such comprehensive amendments to the Loch
Lomond by-laws at this late stage. Why has it not followed the example
of other bodies in co-operating with the park authority during the long
period when the by-laws were under discussion?
It would appear that the water skiers are the most powerful objectors.
What of the other water users, in particular the anglers who are the
only ones paying for using the loch?
The peace and tranquillity of Loch Lomond is one of its charms. The
noise and pollution caused by jet skiers and water skiers is a serious
matter especially to those like myself resident on the lochside.
If the present trend continues, perhaps the day must come when zoning
in its widest sense must be considered. Some lochs already impose
restrictions where power boat users must have a certificate of
competence and comprehensive insurance. Perhaps the Sports Council could
turn its attention to this and help to eliminate the hooligan element.
Meanwhile the new park authority boat, recently launched with
Government funding to meet these problems, has to stand helplessly by
powerless to take action.
I am afraid that until the park authority is given the necessary
authority and resources Loch Lomond will never reach its true potential
as an internationally recognised park. Call it national park or not, it
is the management and resources that are important.
Hannah Stirling,
Auchendarroch, Tarbet,
By Arrochar.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950919-000114</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950919-000114</DOCID>
<DATE>950919</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Screening decision. List of improvements accepted</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>LEADER</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>976306404</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WHEN the extent of the mistakes made during the cervical smear
screening programme at Inverclyde became evident there was general
disbelief. This was largely because the procedures involved were not
supposed to be particularly difficult and also because medical
programmes of this sort are invested with great faith by those who
receive their services. The inquiry into what went wrong at Inverclyde
Royal Hospital between 1987 and 1992 revealed a sorry state of affairs
which led to the re-testing of thousands of women and, almost as
importantly, a growing questioning over the methods used. Many of these
have been answered by the working party which examined the problems of
Inverclyde in detail. It is clear in retrospect that the Inverclyde
laboratory was under-staffed, under-financed, and not using the latest
techniques.
The response of the working party is to provide a long list of
improvements which should be undertaken by laboratories offering this
service. Very properly the Secretary of State for Scotland has accepted
the recommendations of the working party and has said that they will be
implemented.   Various considerations follow from this welcome decision.
The first is that public confidence in the screening programme must be
re-established while recognising that it is unrealistic to expect
perfection. What can be expected is absolute standards applied uniformly
and these will now be established. The more technical suggestions,
including the rapid re-scan of each negative smear, appear sensible and
more likely to pick up aberrations than the random one-in-10 sampling
method which did not appear particularly effective even to laymen. The
establishment of the new methods will cost money. Mr Forsyth was quick
to point out that screening services must be run efficiently and present
value for money. The real value for money is success and if the latest
measures contribute to success they must be properly funded. Moreover,
the funding which must be found for laboratories offering the screening
service must not be taken from other medical programmes. Robbing Peter
to pay Paul has become all too prevalent in the NHS; it should not apply
here.
</TEXT>
