<DOCNO>GH950919-000115</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950919-000115</DOCID>
<DATE>950919</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Where the paddles come off doon the watter</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>WILLIAM HUNTER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>976306405</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
PIE that is humble takes more chewing. Two months have passed since a
slice of the rhubarb variety had to be swallowed and digested. It
concerned morsels of information conveyed here that fell short of gross
exactness. What stuck in the teeth had to do with doon the watter.
For insisting it is a vile phrase, no apology. Dictionaries will have
nothing to do with it, nor should anybody else. Worse than fuddy-duddy,
it is phoney. Patronised by it is anybody who ever took a sail on the
Clyde estuary.
Besides, good doubts (mainly mine) persist about whether real people
ever used the words. They were never part of the patois. Nobody who
regularly went for a Clyde holiday said it was to doon the watter.
Voyagers who preferred Rothesay said they were going to Rothesay. If
Saltcoats was their pleasure, they said so.
So far, so safe.
Where the paddles came off was to suggest the expression might be of
recent invention. It was further hazarded that the words had first been
blinked into the sunshine by a journalist. They had been used by a
wordsmith who had wearied of every July using exodus for the Fair
stampede to the coast. A likely source seemed the Sunday Post.
Along with such good, sound-seeming stuff went a plea for an end to
doon the watter. It has worked a treat. For two months the dire words
have not once swum into my ken. It remains only to get through this
coming holiday weekend, and there will be clear water for the rest of
the tourist year. Frankly, it feels like a triumph of sorts.
Also frankly, success has been otherwise mixed. Marks for the rest of
the speculation amount to, say, four out of l0 -- not good, but not bad
fishing either.
Above all, the dating was wrong. Doon the watter has been a blot on
the printed page for more than a century.
From his learned shelves Adam McNaughtan, bookseller and rhymer of
this parish, showed a bound volume of Quiz weekly magazine for l884.
Leaping from its summer holiday edition, a cartoon showed a drookit
fellow under a ragged umbrella. He is being pelted upon. In italics to
emphasise the whimsy the artist has added the caption FAIR Saturday --
DOON THE WATTER.
Oddly, however, there is watter, watter nowhere else in the magazine.
Mr Quiz did not love the Fair. He liked to sneer at its mass plebeian
excesses. He chronicles with glee how a riverboat captain alleged to him
that as many as six unruly fare-paying passengers had to be put in
irons.
Yet when Mr Quiz reports the horror of the holiday he does so in
civilised language. He writes about people going to the coast. His pages
are not doused with cold watter.
Regrettably (for me) that happened only four years later in a small
epic poem entitled Doon the Watter at the Fair by a makar called Bass
Kennedy.
He tells of an elderly couple -- she a former mill lass who, bless
her, wears a Paisley shawl; he a Brigton weaver chiel -- who in the 35
years of their marriage have every July taken a holiday on the Clyde and
hope to keep doing so for as long as they are spared.
Bass Kennedy ends his work:
A twalmonth's toil in Glesca toun
Is lichtsome, I declare,
Wi' twa-three days' diversion doon
The watter at the Fair.
His poem is reprinted in Mungo's Tongues, a collection of Glasgow
poems through three centuries edited by Hamish Whyte, a librarian who
keeps adding to the cataloguing his colleagues have to do by producing
many books.
Little is known about the doon the watter perpetrator. ''Kennedy seems
to have been a kind of poet laureate of the Govan area,'' Hamish Whyte
said. It would be good to have more, if only because of the laureate's
profoundly musical name.
Other bardic offerings by him included verses for the opening of the
Elder Park, along with memorial lines about other Govanites. He could
pen poetry about a train trip to Prince's Pier. Bass Kennedy even put a
football jersey on his muse:
Glancing off the cross-bar,
Grazing either pole;
Rushing, crushing, pushing, boys --
Hurrah! another goal!
This effort in l887 won him the prize in a song competition in The
People's Friend. Maybe, my guess about the Sunday Post wasn't totally
awry. Although three out of l0 would have been nearer the mark, this has
been a most scholarly wee sail.
Except it ought to be capped by an even earlier comic epic about the
delights of estuary steamboats. In light verses it retails how all the
weans get seasick and paw falls in the water. For four days all the
family's glum faces are pressed to the window of their digs staring out
at the rain. Then a wayward daughter discovers sex. On the way home it
is vowed never again.
This masterpiece, called Down the Water by Patrick Buchan, appeared in
l842. Unhappily, although the title looks like dictionary English, the
author permits himself to rhyme water with patter. He seems bent on
hugging my grading down to a wan l0%. ''Does anybody care about all this
any more?'' Hamish Whyte asked.
</TEXT>
