<HEADLINE>Buying some time for age</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>GAVIN BELL</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>13</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>RELATIVE VALUES</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976306406</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
In day two of our series Jennifer Cunningham and Gavin Bell look at a
model community, at possible solutions to present inequities of care,
and at ways to help the pensioners of tomorrow
NELL ROSS had fun yesterday, and she can look forward to another good
day tomorrow. She may be 85 years old and a widow, but Nell knows how to
enjoy life -- and happily there is no shortage of good neighbours to
help her get the most out of it.
Every day she walks with a home help to an elegant sandstone building
on the South Side of Glasgow where she is greeted by dozens of friends.
The main recreation room on an upper floor of the building is a kind of
home from home for Nell and hundreds of other elderly folk who gather
every day for a cup of tea and a chat, a game of cards or bingo, and
regular social evenings.
It is the nucleus of a remarkable community which is highly regarded
in the voluntary sector as a model of sympathetic and effective care,
with an evolutionary approach that augurs well for the future. Founded
in 1972 as a lunch club for local elderly residents, the Dixon Community
in the Govanhill district of the city now cares for more than 1500
people with a range of services from home helps to street wardens and
residential facilities.
Its philosophy of supporting ''good neighbour'' schemes -- essentially
encouraging people to help each other -- accords with the views of
organisations such as Age Concern Scotland. Lucy Mackenzie of Age
Concern says: ''The response we usually get from elderly people is that
they want to continue living in their own homes without being a burden
to their family. So ideally we should be considering what individuals
need, and setting up a package to provide them, rather than creating
some kind of institution and saying this is what is on offer. In this
respect, the Dixon Community is a very impressive organisation.''
The woman at the heart of the organisation is Sheila Halley, an
energetic, cheerful woman who insists that the success of the venture is
due to common sense -- plus selfless devotion to others, of course.
''There is a lot of goodwill out there,'' she says. ''All we have done
is to tap into it and help to organise it. If you have a lot of elderly
people living alone and craving friendship and support, it's just common
sense to bring them together, isn't it?''
Well, yes. But what has distinguished the Dixon Community is the
extent to which it has galvanised the residents of a large area,
previously blighted by inner-city decay, into caring for each other. And
all on a shoestring budget.
''What we have been trying to do is to fill in the gaps that families
would fill if they were there,'' Ms Halley says. ''We provide a place
for them to come and enjoy companionship and entertainment if they want,
and help with chores in their own homes if they need it. I suppose the
basic aim is to enable elderly people to continue living in their own
homes as long as possible with dignity and flexible support. As people's
needs change, we can adapt.''
What that means in real terms is a day centre in the Dixon Halls -- a
splendid Victorian burgh hall erected by the owner of the Govan Iron
Works in 1879 -- which provides meals, bingo sessions, arts and crafts
classes, carpet bowls, bus excursions, and Saturday night dances and
sing-songs. A day at the centre, with meals included, costs #1.20, and
most of the activities are organised by the elderly themselves. An
adjacent building houses modern flats for 10 local people suffering from
dementia, which are staffed around the clock.
It also means 400 volunteers providing a bedding-down service in
private homes, administering late-night medication, hairdressing, doing
the shopping, collecting pensions, and just popping in occasionally for
a wee chat. These good neighbour schemes are not intended to replace
professional home helps, Ms Halley says, they are just the icing on the
cake of community care.
Having focused initially on elderly people living alone, Ms Halley
turned her attention to the carers -- the relatives and friends whose
own lives are degraded by the strains of coping with infirm dependants.
''It would do a lot of good for people to come along to our carers'
forums and listen to some of the horror stories they have to tell,'' she
says.
So a helpline was set up for carers, to provide assistance in
emergencies and offer solutions to long-term problems. To their profound
relief, many carers have been able to return to full-time employment,
secure in the knowledge that their mum or dad is quite happy during the
day making new friends at the Dixon Halls.
In the amiable confusion of the main recreation hall, it is not always
easy to distinguish between the visitors and the volunteers. Dolly
Conroy, 77, could be either, but in fact she is one of the main
organisers as chair of the members' committee. She said, ''I'd go as far
as to say there isn't a club anywhere in Britain as good.''
Mrs Conroy's use of the word ''club'' says a lot about the ambiance of
the community. So do the smiles and the greetings of folk arriving in
mini-buses for the day's activities at the day centre. The core funding
from Strathclyde Regional Council and the Greater Glasgow Health Board
is relatively small, but it is obviously well spent.
Asked to sum up the Dixon experience, she says: ''I would say here is
a community that has built up a nucleus of caring support for its
elderly, which poses the question: what is happening in other areas that
don't have it? How much loneliness and unhappiness is out there?''
Nell Ross, the sprightly 85-year-old with a zest for life, has the
answer: ''A lot of us in here would be sad cases if we didn't have the
Dixon Halls to come to. I'd be at home staring at four bare walls.''
</TEXT>
