<DATE>950919</DATE>
<HEADLINE>A cold look at crime</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ALLAN LAING</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976306407</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Allan Laing wonders why Channel 4 chose Glasgow hardman, Paul Ferris,
to appear in a new series examining gangland Britain and male violence.
FIRST things first. Paul John Ferris did not murder Arthur Thompson
Jnr. A jury cleared him of the charge at the High Court in Glasgow three
years ago. So who did? Well, someone reckoned it was Paul's mates, Joe
''Bananas'' Hanlon and Bobby Glover. Which is why the two Glasgow hoods
were executed (by persons as yet unknown) on the morning of young
Arthur's funeral.
But whatever Paul Ferris is not, he most certainly is a frighteningly
violent young man. And the chilling thing about him, when you see him on
a television screen, is the fact that he is not chilling. At least, not
to look at. He appears ordinary; you would pass him on the street
without a second glance. And that is probably just as well, for a second
glance might bring you to his attention. And you do not want to be drawn
to the attention of Paul John Ferris.
Next week, should you choose to allow it, this East End gangster will
enter your living-room late at night and, in the company of another
villain (John McVicar who, having paid his debt to society, has gone on
to become a media celebrity), he will tell you what violence means to
him. In a genuinely shocking Channel 4documentary programme, Chapter And
Verse, Ferris will claim that he is neither a bully nor a gangster.
And then he will add this sentence: ''But that doesn't mean you've to
let people stand on your toes; if they do that then you've got to jump
on their neck and break it.'' Some things are worth repeating: Paul
Ferris is a frighteningly violent young man. Listen to his words.
The picture of Glasgow painted, not so much by Ferris, but by the
production company which made the programme, is coloured blood red. It
is the stark meanness of no mean city. Though highly-stylised
(sensational, if you prefer) in its approach, it is an intense study of
a criminal mind. By using reconstruction, CCTV footage, and interviews
with relatives and key figures in Ferris's background, the film maps out
the perceived landscape of the vicious Glasgow we prefer to ignore (and,
indeed, the Glasgow which most of us seldom witness).
McVicar, in his introduction, says: ''Glasgow has a gangland murder
rate which rivals Palermo.'' Here they prefer ''making trouble to making
money.'' In the local drug trade, he adds, the violence is, ''less
personal and more business-like.''
Ferris recalls his life in an ice-cold, matter-of-fact way. Nowhere
along the line does he renounce the violence which has surrounded him.
''I've always used a weapon of sorts,'' he says, ''whether it be a
baseball bat or a knife.''
He learned early that retaliation was the best way, not only to gain
respect among his peers, but also to survive in Glasgow's criminal
underbelly. He tells McVicar that, at the age of 13, he was bullied by a
notorious local family. That taught him a lesson; that the use of
weapons was the only true and effective deterrent.
It was after a firearms conviction that Ferris came to the attention
of Arthur Thompson Snr, gangland boss, who employed him to collect
money. Seduced by the easy life, he couldn't understand why someone
should go out and earn a pittance for an honest day's work when, for
just 10 minutes of criminal enterprise, you could earn the equivalent of
six-months' wages.
Things turned ugly for Ferris when Arthur Jnr, Thompson's son and heir
to the family empire, was shot dead while on home release from an
11-year stretch for a drugs conviction. Ferris was suspected along with
Hanlon and Glover (''the brothers I never had,'' he calls them). After a
celebrated trial which put paid to any lingering hope that Glasgow was a
city of culture, he was acquitted of Arthur Jnr's murder but his two
mates were dead. The killings remain unsolved and the question remains
unanswered. Were they executed in revenge for Thompson's death or were
they killed by someone who feared that the pair would expose the real
assassins?
What is certain is the fact that, though Paul Ferris denies that his
life is in danger, he is still inclined to look over his shoulder three
years on. A sick joke, doing the rounds of the crime reporters shortly
after his acquittal springs to mind. Question -- What's the difference
between Elvis Presley and Paul Ferris? Answer -- Paul Ferris is
definitely dead.
At the end of the day he accepts that crime comes as naturally as
breathing to him. ''If anyone was born into crime, it was me. Crime is
in my blood,'' he remarks.
The documentary is part of a fortnight season of C4 programmes,
Battered Britain, which amounts to an in-depth survey of contemporary
violence. And Ferris, like the proverbial bad penny pops up again. In
the second of a series of half-hour debates broadcast every weekday
morning next week, he will join a panel of guests to discuss male
violence, a subject in which he can justifiably claim to be an expert.
Hosted by Elaine C Smith, the Living With Violence series is being
recorded in Glasgow this week.
Joining Ferris will be convicted murderer Hugh Collins, who 20 years
after the killing of a gangland enemy realises the futility of his
actions; and notorious football casual Paul Blackwell, infamously
captured on film in the act of stabbing another supporter. Also involved
in the programme are Jack Maple, the deputy police commissioner of the
NYPD, and journalist Pat Kane.
The Battered Britain season is underpinned by some new research,
specially commissioned by C4. In a special edition of Frontline the
suggestion is made that the fear of crime is often a bigger problem than
crime itself. It looks first at the lengths many people will go to
protect themselves -- the young businesswomen who take karate lessons,
the elderly pensioner who barricades herself into her home with a vast
array of locks, alarms, and chains.
Then it turns to experts in criminology who explain that such fears
are out of proportion to the reality of violence. Parents are five times
more likely to win the Lottery jackpot than to have their child abducted
by a stranger. Assaults on women are almost always perpetrated by the
man sitting next to them on the sofa. The number of serious attacks
suffered by the elderly is statistically insignificant.
According to Frontline, public anxiety is heightened and distorted by
media coverage of crime. So now we know. Paul Ferris is innocent and,
once again, it's the nasty newspapers which are to blame for society's
ills. According, of course, to Channel 4'sscrupulously non-sensational
fortnight of programmes about crime.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950919-000118</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950919-000118</DOCID>
<DATE>950919</DATE>
<HEADLINE>No quick fix</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>GAVIN BELL</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>13</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>RELATIVE VALUES</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>976306408</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THERE are solutions to the inequities of care for the elderly, but for
most of them there is a price to pay, according to Edward Richards of
the independent London Economics group.
Richards, who is conducting a study of long-term care on behalf of the
left-wing Institute for Public Policy Research, says: ''What we have at
the moment effectively penalises thrift, in that some people are faced
with losing their homes and savings to pay for long-term care while
others who have saved nothing are looked after at the state's expense.''
The first obvious solution, he says, is substantially to increase the
asset allowance of #8000 above which people must pay for their own care
costs. Mr Richards suggests a figure of #60,000, being roughly the
average value of a house, which would help many people at least to
retain possession of their homes.
The problem is that this would transfer the burden of long-term care
from the individual to the state, which would have to be paid for either
by higher taxes or cuts in other areas of public spending.
Another solution would be to make private insurance schemes cheaper
and more attractive by linking them with pensions and making them
eligible for tax relief. Again, however, there would be a cost in terms
of lost tax revenue which would have to be made up by raising taxes
elsewhere or cutting other services.
Richards has other reservations about private sector solutions: ''We
still don't know whether tax concessions would be balanced by long-term
savings on state health care. And inevitably private schemes would be
taken up by only a fairly selective group of better-off people, so they
would probably not resolve the inequity issues.''
In the longer term he says some form of compusory social insurance may
be necessary.
Richards favours a ''pay-as-you-go'' system, under which the present
older generation would be supported immediately by contributions from
today's working population, which in turn would be supported in old age
by the next generation.
''The problem with this system is that it is similar to the present
national insurance scheme, which many people feel has failed them.
''The truth is that there are no easy answers to long-term care for
the elderly.
''There is a lot of scaremongering going on. Some people are saying
the problem is spiralling out of control. That is simply not true, but
we must begin mapping out new strategies now.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950919-000119</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950919-000119</DOCID>
<DATE>950919</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Help yourself</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JENNIFER CUNNINGHAM</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>13</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>RELATIVE VALUES</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>976306409</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
PEOPLE should be responsible for themselves -- that is the view of
David Marsland, Professor of Social Sciences at Brunel University
College and one of the Adam Smith Institute's proselyters. He believes
there should be what he describes as an honest two-tier system.
''If I am paying for a nursing home out of my savings, it should be of
higher quality than that enjoyed by my idle sister who has squandered
her money,'' is how he sums it up.
''Although people like me are quite willing to say that sort of thing
in public, politicians are very reluctant. There is a constituency of
opinion there which wants to know why people should have something free
when others are going to have to pay for it, but we need a Mrs Thatcher
figure to deliver it to the public.''
Professor Marsland acknowledges that people genuinely unable to
provide for themselves need to be cared for from public resources but
says there should be a minimum standard of ''mere adequacy''.
Tinkering with the threshold of allowable assets, for example raising
the current exemption of #8000 to something in line with the average
house price, is not the real solution to the problem as he sees it. ''I
suppose people with assets above that level at the moment might be
tempted to spend them, but it is hardly something one would want to
encourage.
''If they understood that in old age they would be living in a large
place with a number of other people in each room and being cared for by
people with no more than adequate skills, they would save to get
something better. It is morally wrong even if it makes financial sense
to give money away to your children or go off and spend it on beer and
skittles or whatever to make yourself eligible for state support,'' he
said.
He is equally dismissive of compulsory social insurance. ''State
support will always be unreliable and inadequate. There is no reason why
it should not be done privately but not compulsorily. A large proportion
of people are now in occupational or personal pension schemes and there
are perfectly good insurance schemes and they will be more efficacious
than the state would be.''
Professor Marsland says there is no reason why there should be a large
proportion of people unemployed -- perhaps 10% who can be catered for by
the state system and the others can manage to make their own provision.
Despite fears about the contract culture he argues that 80% of the
population is in employment sufficiently secure to allow them to put
something aside for old age.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
