<HEADLINE>Afterlife for the haunt of spooks</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>WILLIAM RUSSELL</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>11</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976306410</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
William Russell goes behind the doors of Britain's former Secret
Services HQ to discover what lurks behind its massive walls before the
developers move into the old spy house and give it the
wine-bar-and-offices treatment
SMILEY'S people lived here; Harry Palmer fiddled his expenses
somewhere behind these massive walls; Anthony Blunt probably paid the
occasional call; James Bond may well have goosed Miss Moneypenny in the
lift; and M did whatever M was in the habit of doing.
No 1 Curzon Street, home until six months ago of the Secret Services,
MI5 and MI6, is up for sale, the latest ''surplus to requirements''
Government building to be put on the market by the Department of the
Environment for an anticipated #70m, give or take.
A thirties monstrosity of no architectural merit whatsoever, it is
virtually impossible to turn into anything other than a building fit for
spies -- or civil servants. It could never make a luxury hotel -- so low
the ceilings, so dingy the interior corridors, so narrow the staircases,
so dire the outlook.
As a freehold site with planning permission from Westminster Council,
it is very valuable indeed and the proposed redevelopment, to include
offices, shops, a wine bar, and three mews houses, has had the usual
suspects from the Middle and Far East expressing keen interest.
Nobody can remember when a site of this size last became available in
Mayfair. Triangular in shape, about an acre in area, it is flanked by
Clarges Street and Clarges Mews, while just around the corner is
Berkeley Square, where the nightingales sang for free, and across Curzon
Street lies Shepherd Market where the birds are female and the songs
expensive.
At No 1, however, officially a Ministry of Defence building since
1972, when it was vacated by the Department of Education and Science, no
birds sing. Even today just what went on in the low-ceilinged rooms,
tiny cells opening off the dismal corridor which runs the length of the
building on each floor, is shrouded in mystery because of the Official
Secrets Act.
But it was here for nearly a quarter of a century that Britain's spies
lurked behind the walls, a metre thick in the basement of the six-storey
building which has no windows at street level.
A secret interior road, with entrances at either end guarded by solid
metal gates, allows people to come and go without being seen coming in
through the main doors, and there is an annexe housing vast windowless
computer rooms so secret that even the estate agent showing me round
yesterday had not seen them before.
Off limits to most of the people working in the building, they had
only just been unlocked by the previous occupants' engineers, who had
been removing all traces of their use.
Knight, Frank and Rutley, handling the sale for the Government, say it
is 20 years since such a Mayfair property came on the market, if one
ever did in this part of London. It is out to informal tender until
September 29, after which the Government will consider the bids.
On the sixth floor is the remains of the spies' bar, provided to keep
the spooks from using the hostelries of Shepherd Market and indulging in
careless talk. The Grape and Vine or The Pig of fiction, was the Eye
Club of reality, according to a notice pinned to the wall. The bar
counter, about 30ft long, curved at one end, is made of rather nasty
veneered brown wood, and beyond the cafeteria, the fittings long gone,
stretches to infinity.
At least here the windows let in daylight. On the lower floors, where
there were computers, the air conditioning ducts block most of the
windows.
Fifth men, fourth men, faceless men, loyal men and treacherous men
have all come and gone from this building owned by the Government since
1947. Built in the late 1930s, it appears to have been requisitioned for
use during the last war. The Department of Health is believed to have
used it for a time, and Margaret Thatcher was certainly there from
1970-72 as Education Secretary.
In the empty rooms tangled power cables and telephone wires hang
sadly, the listening machines to which they were once linked no longer
there, and holes gape in the floors through which terminals were
connected to the mainframe computer.
There is little else to see, beyond a couple of lewd pin-up pictures
on the wall and the notice on one of the secure rooms inside which
people could talk without being overhead, which reads: ''The door
surround may be coated with vaseline. Be careful, it may stain your
clothing'' -- to which some wag has added ''and draw attention to your
sexual perversities''.
By the iron gate opening on to Clarges Street there is a red light,
below which a notice indicates the response should it start flashing --
''Suspected hostile activity. Consider Counter Measures.''
</TEXT>
