<HEADLINE>Nationalist tiger may maul its master</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>TOM GALLAGHER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>11</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>976306411</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Tom Gallagher considers the changing fortunes of Slobodan Milosevic,
architect of the Greater Serbian nightmare
THE wily Balkan fox Slobodan Milosevic would never have exposed
himself to the dangers that West European leaders risk on their visits
to Sarajevo: Spain's Foreign Minister, Javier Solana and, yesterday,
Malcolm Rifkind had the closest of shaves while visiting a city still in
the throes of war.
But it would only be natural if a cold realist like Milosevic was
beginning to ponder if his own end might turn out to be a violent and
ignoble one. As more and more of his pieces are swept off the Balkan
chessboard there are a growing number of Serbs, some once loyal to him,
who view him as a traitor who has brought ruin down on the Serb cause.
Even in the glory days after 1992, when Serb forces controlled 30% of
Croatia and 70% of Bosnia, there were a few Balkan experts prepared to
stick their necks out and predict that the end game would be civil war
in Serbia itself: Milosevic's audacious prize of a Serbian empire from
the Adriatic to the Danube was simply beyond the resources of the Serbs
and was bound to produce a counter-response which would shatter Serb
unity.
But until a few months ago it looked unlikely that Milosevic would be
on any losing side. He still had good cards to play. Despite the ravages
of western sanctions on his economy, he retained an efficient
bureaucracy that was loyal to him; the military had been tamed by
repeated purges and he had built up a loyal police force; the state
media told Serbs that Milosevic could do no wrong and most of those in
the small towns and villages of provincial Serbia had no reason to think
otherwise.
After all, despite sanctions, Milosevic was still courted assiduously
by the West; in July 1993 he had kept the Belgian Foreign Minister Willy
Claes (now NATO's Secretary-General) waiting in Belgrade for three days
before refusing to see him. After his mood softened and he urged his
clients in Bosnia to negotiate, Douglas Hurd and his successor as
Foreign Secretary, Malcolm Rifkind, had no hesitation about declaring
him to be the key to peace, despite being widely seen as the architect
of the Yugoslav tragedy. The current peace deal being promoted by US
envoy Richard Holbrooke would preserve most of the Serb territorial
gains in Bosnia.
Even after the fall of the Serbian Krajina to Croat forces in August,
Milosevic still seemed fireproof. Rallies in Belgrade called by
nationalists crying sell-out were thinly attended. Red Star Belgrade
football fans abused Milosevic from the terraces but then went quietly
home.
It is not just his critics who admit that this inscrutable leader has
no long-term strategy other than his own survival. He jumped on the
nationalist tiger in the late 1980s to get to the top and allow as much
of the old communist system to endure as the rest of eastern Europe
embraced democracy.
When a world horrified by ethnic cleansing in Croatia and Bosnia
carried out by Milosevic's henchmen, imposed sanctions he had a rethink.
By 1993 his aim was to reintegrate Serbia into the international
community and be left in control of half of Bosnia.
But he has been unable to bottle up the nationalist demons he released
upon going for broke in the Balkans in 1991. The rebel Serbs in Bosnia
have rejected compromise peace deals that would have prevented an exodus
of their people. Today, having foolishly goaded NATO beyond endurance,
their statelet is fragmenting as hundreds of square miles fall to their
enemy with each passing day.
The refugees from the Krajina and now from Bosnia itself pouring into
Serbia are bound to subvert his tightly-run state. It is clear that many
blame Milosevic personally for the ruination that has befallen them.
People without land, homes or prospects are easy fodder for the radical
nationalists led by Vojislav Seselj who have been gunning for Milosevic
ever since he started to play the moderate card.
The secret police and the regular police contain many officials from
Bosnia and Krajina. Whatever the precautions taken to silence dissent,
his own praetorian guard is likely to be a threat to him now.
And even Radovan Karadzic has openly accused Milosevic of turning his
back on the Serb cause.
Serbia is polarised between a tiny elite of war profiteers and mafia,
no more than 5% of the people, another 20% in the public services
shielded from hard times and thus loyal to Milosevic, and millions of
others who are quietly going hungry or selling their possessions. A
country of 10 million has only one million left in formal jobs, with
another million on upaid leave.
A diet of nationalism provided by the media stilled discontent from
liberal anti-war Serbs. But it is inevitable that challengers will soon
be after Milosevic's crown by accusing him of being a false patriot. His
record is one not without mistakes.
In 1991 he was unable to motivate the Yugoslav army into seizing
enough territory from Croatia which would have turned Greater Serbia
into a reality. In 1992 he allowed Macedonia, known as south Serbia
before 1941, to slip from Belgrade's grip and become an independent
state. In 1995 he refused to allow his own army to defend Croatian land
inhabited by Serbs for centuries, perhaps even making a deal with Zagreb
over the Krajina.
Having made his pact with the nationalist devil, the Balkan
Mephistopheles is finding it difficult to renege. He is stuck with
Karadzic, the client who became a challenger and with the butcher
General Mladic.
This week 70,000 desperate Serb refugees are milling around the
streets of Banja Luka as enemy forces close in from the north and west.
If the citadel of Bosnian Serbdom collapses, the tide of refugees into
Serbia might overwhelm Milosevic's authority and produce deadly strife
in Serbia.
The next few days may well see whether Milosevic can resist making
another somersault. Nato forces fear he will return to high-risk
nationalism by deploying his forces to prevent the fall of Banja Luka.
In a very fluid and unpredictable situation, the consequences of this
would be incalculable. A well-armed Croatia and Serbia would be in
direct confrontation; it might even be the signal for rebellion in
Muslim parts of Serbia such as Kosovo and the Sandjak. What Russia would
do if Nato engaged Serbian planes over Bosnia is anyone's guess.
If the present crisis can be ridden out, it is surely high time for
the West to stop viewing Slobodan Milosevic as a force for stability in
the Balkans. He cares more for his own skin that for the welfare of
ordinary Serbs. Hundreds of thousands have been the victims of his power
lust. It's time for the West to be rid of him.
* Tom Gallagher is a lecturer in peace studies at the University of
Bradford.
</TEXT>
