<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950919-000122</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950919-000122</DOCID>
<DATE>950919</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Game, set and match to moguls?</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>BOB CRAMPSEY</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>11</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976306412</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A world of sport awaits armchair supporters -- if they have satellite
TV. Bob Crampsey considers the cost to traditional channels and sport
itself.
THE traditional broadcasting organisations, ITV and BBC, have
retreated doggedly yet a little further on the sporting front. Next
weekend Britain and Europe may do wonders in the Ryder Cup and Paul
Gascoigne may or may not acquit himself well in his first Old Firm match
tonight. In neither case will the bulk of viewers be able to judge as
the action unfolds. Terrestrial television has lost out, as it is
increasingly doing.
The scheming moguls so feared by us traditionalists have every right
to plead consent of the victims. One sport after another has rushed to
sign contracts of long duration for large sums. The whole affair may be
nothing more than a sensible application of business principles, to wit:
* You have something we want.
* We will pay you handsomely.
* Here is what you want.
End of story.
Or it would be if we were not talking about sport and that strange 10%
which pervades it, not the agent's fee in this case but that
inconvenient, residual sentiment which is at the core of every sporting
affiliation.
If terrestrial television totally loses its ability to compete for the
great sporting event does that matter? There is a simple answer after
all; let the public speed up its hitherto glacial acquisition of
satellite and cable channel facilities.
For satellite can do things for sports that at present the traditional
broadcasters cannot. The Ryder Cup went to BSkyB because that
organisation could promise not only a contract for the contest but, in
addition, increased coverage of future golf and sponsorship of a
specific event, the British Masters.
And might it not be argued that lack of availability on ITV and BBC
will increase the number of those actually attending matches. Evidence
from America would appear to run counter to this. The citizens of
America, deprived for a full year of watching baseball on television
under any auspices, have responded on the resumption of major league
baseball by inflicting a 20% drop in attendances.
Should the great national occasions in sport which have hitherto been
held sacrosanct be preserved for BBC? On what logical lines are we going
to argue? Are Test matches such occasions? I would say yes, as are
soccer internationals, but Wimbledon is a tournament where competitors
are playing for their own hand and the same is true of the Open
Championship, and indeed all golf except the Ryder and Walker Cups, with
their female equivalents the Curtis and the Solheim.
The BBC's performance has been good but not unblemished. It covers
Test cricket admirably. But its commitment to the cradle of the game,
county cricket, is non-existent and the Sunday League has been adroitly
frozen out.
The build-up to the climax in certain events such as the Open
Championship and Test matches is inevitably almost painfully slow but
you can't leave a Test match for five minutes every hour without missing
something of moment, and these days the BBC takes the break too often.
Sponsors would probably prefer a greater ITV involvement with sport
since, despite dipping figures, the channel commands greater viewing
numbers than Sky or Eurosport can muster. Interestingly, most of ITV
subsisted quite happily in its first five or so years without sport. For
a not inconsiderable time STV was the only commercial station in Britain
to run a regular sports programme. Most of the sports-free stations did
very well and one or two might be considering that the time has come to
repeat the experiment.
The sweep of the newer channels may well be quite irresistible in the
short term but certain things will arise from it. Sport will sprawl all
across the week, as football already does. The impact of cup-tie days is
diminished since the simultaneous reception of news from all the other
matches is no longer possible. There will be a move from the match to
the staged event.
It's a safe bet that at this moment at ITV the prayer is going up:
''Oh Lord, if there be only one British survivor from the league
sections of the European Cup let it not be Rangers.'' Rules will be
strained to ensure that the rich and powerful survive. It's already
happening.
The spectator will also have to adjust; golfers will be expected
meekly to concede their Sundays to re-arrange football fixtures.
Far-travelled Old Firm supporters have to alter their New Year travel
plans at the last minute.
If the sports need the new outlets the converse is certainly true. A
prospective purchaser of satellite looking at today's newspaper cannot
but be struck by the prevalence in the sports channels of such
crowd-pullers as aerobics, decathlon, wrestling, and junior golf. A
good-going dogfight would attract more watchers than any of these.
Perhaps the non-traditionalist's most powerful argument is that
satellite is what the players want and it is unarguable that for years
their participation, without which there were no matches, went
unrewarded. Boxing promoter Frank Warren has said that ''these guys want
top money for putting their lives on the line''. Only a fool would deny
that recent bouts have had life-threatening outcomes but equally will
the public stand for some of the buffoonery which has recently passed
for title fights?
In a worst-case scenario, rugby clubs will disband their second,
third, and fourth fifteens and cricket will close down the county
championship because both cost money. In the short term, I fear that the
governing bodies of the major sports will not be able to retain control
of them. If they cannot get it back then we have a Middle Ages scenario
with powerful barons -- the moguls -- in charge of squabbling retainers
-- the players.
In the long run -- despite the fact that Alexander Cairncross, the
famous economist, pointed out that in the long run we are all dead --
I'm sufficiently hopeful to believe that the governors will once again
govern.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
