<HEADLINE>When mum is the last word</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>SUE INNES</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>BOOK REVIEW</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>976306413</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Sue Innes finds a new book presenting women's own accounts of
childbirth and motherhood leaves a number of questions unanswered
VIVIEN DEVLIN'S account of motherhood over 70 years is needed; it
illuminates a striking silence. She has drawn together from painstaking
research, letters, a questionnaire and interviews with women aged from
93 to 15, a mass of material which is sometimes revealing, often banal.
But from it she has come to no conclusions which offer insight beyond
the average magazine article.
The material, she has perhaps reasoned, must stand on its own. And
individually many of these stories are fascinating: the midwife working
in slums where the police would not escort her, fleas and bedbugs a
working hazard; the sad and honestly-faced account of a baby boy who
lived only a few hours; the pain of giving birth remembered with
intensity after 60 years; a despairing account of a mismanaged recent
labour; a mother reflecting on everyday love, beautifully and simply
expressed.
For creating a means by which women could talk about experience which
is immensely important both individually and socially, Vivien Devlin is
to be congratulated.
Talking about birth after the event and reflecting on everyday life
bringing up children is repressed and devalued in male-dominated
culture. In research for my own recent book on women's changing lives I
was startled by the absence of accounts of motherhood by mothers: there
is a massive ''how to'' literature, and mothers are studied as an
unavoidable extra to child development, but although it is central to
human life maternity as experience is hardly visible.
But Devlin claims in her introduction that she intends to look at
''what being a mother means'', to give, ''a broad social and historical
overview''. Instead meaning is drained, mainly because of the lack of
social and historical context. This is the slice-and-serve school of
editing; excerpts from interviews are packaged under a variety of
chapter headings in roughly date order, with no introduction for the
speaker or where she lived and how.
Significant and contradictory statements are not pursued; potentially
revelatory comments left hanging in the air. You wish for fewer stories
more thoroughly told.
Experience has been turned into a list and there is a limit to how
many times you can read without wearying variations on ''I used
towelling and gauze nappies . . .'' The device of breaking the tone by
including quotations from literature adds very little.
Her comment that, ''I concentrated on assessing the level of
commitment to mothering and family life'' as a means of comparison is
both arrogant and unthinking.
The chapter, Commitment to Motherhood, is about whether or not mothers
work should outside the home; that this is not a measure of commitment
to the relationship and the children, but instead that mothers who also
work outside the home and mothers who don't are managing an equal
commitment differently seems not to have occurred to Devlin, who
apparently accepts that at-home mothering is the real thing, all else
watered down.
But you are still their mother full-time, no matter what else you do.
That historically specific factors beyond women's own choices shape how
we bring up children (and how far there is any choice), including
changing family size and domestic work, economic change and changing
patterns of employment, cultural pressures and social sanctions, has
scarcely impinged.
An interesting question, for me, is why so many of the older women
need to insist that what worked for them is right and must work for
everyone. Why is their tone so judgmental and why do they need to
justify their lives? I suspect that the answer may be in the lack of
real respect given to their work as mothers, but there is no space here
to take any inquiry deeper.
Nor is there any recognition of the glow that memory may add, or that
the narratives we tell ourselves have been edited to our own purposes.
Too many are of the ''we were short of money but made the best of things
. . .'' type, which slips easily into complacency. It was a simpler,
finer world apparently then . . . But let's not pretend it's the whole
truth.
Mothering, more than must human activities, is measured against an
unrealistic template of perfection -- which turns quickly to blame.
Particularly because so many contributors are women beyond the hands-on
stage of maternity, determined to express their disapproval of mothers
today, this book may make some vulnerable mothers more so. I'd like to
see it sold with a robust disclaimer: remember, no-one gets it right
anyway.
Difficulties and dissatisfaction with motherhood, Devlin declares ''a
late twentieth-century predicament''.
Her researches, she says show ''the vast majority of women bringing up
their children between the wars and well into the 1950s and 1960s
accepted their role as wife and mother intuitively, and dedicated their
lives to their husbands and families, with pride and contentment''.
Those for whom married life did not bring ''pride and contentment''
may have been less inclined to answer her advertisement, however. And
words like intuitively, as well as phrases like ''maternal instinct''
and ''innate desire'', beg a few highly contested questions.
There is little sense that these are difficult, emotionally deep-mined
and important issues. Nor that they are highly political: central
questions about the unpaid work of caring, and the low value placed on
it on our society, in practice if not in lip-service, are scarcely
acknowledged.
There have been principles of selection and editing at work,
necessarily, but they are not made explicit. The author hides evasively
behind the material, pretending that this is objectivity. You long for
some shaping purpose beyond the valid, but clearly insufficient,
question: ''What is it like?'' There are no shortcuts to understanding.
* Motherhood From 1920 to the Present Day: Women's Voices edited by
Vivien Devlin. Polygon, #11.99.
* Sue Innes is the author of Making It Work -- Women, Change and
Challenge in the 90s (Chatto &amp; Windus, #12.99).
</TEXT>
