<HEADLINE>Death culture inheritance</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CAROLE MORIN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>PROFILE</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976306414</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
If the child of an infamous artist is allowed to inherit the sins of
the parents -- why not the success genes, asks Carole Morin of the
daughter of Sylvia Plath
AN EXHIBITION of oil paintings by an unknown artist in a gallery on
the unfashionable side of World's End has attracted an unusual number of
visitors. Frieda Hughes is known more as daughter than artist. Her
mother is the mythological suicidee Sylvia Plath. After Marilyn Monroe,
American poet Plath is the sexiest suicide of the century.
Ahead of me, in the trek down the New King's Road -- a no-man's land,
like the space in a sixties movie between the Berlin Wall and freedom --
was a group of oriental girls in MAC lipstick who are ''doing The Bell
Jar in school''. One of them giggled, ''We're into all that death stuff.
It's like, you know, real.'' The dark night of the soul's a lot of fun
when you're young. Or, as Al Alvarez (the first critic to recognise
Plath's genius) said: ''Death is a kind of pornography, at once exciting
and unreal.''
Falling into step beside me, a teenage boy said: ''Art galleries are
for w*****s but I just want to see what she's like.'' Frieda Hughes is
-- physically -- like her mother. As Sylvia Plath said, children are ''a
clean slate, with your face.'' Well, not always. Poor Victoria Sellers
seems to have inherited her father Peter's looks and her mother, Britt
Ekland's, brain.
After Sylvia Plath's first breakdown, during what she called the
platinum summer, Sylvia had the fresh face of collegiate America. It was
only later, living in depressing Devon, that the moon face of melancholy
couldn't hide from the camera any longer. Frieda Hughes, at 34, already
three years older than Plath was when she died, resembles the big-boned
girl with blocked pores instead of freckles on her nose, whom Al Alvarez
-- understandably -- didn't fancy.
The schoolboy didn't get a look at Frieda. She wasn't in the Anna-Mei
Chadwick Gallery. ''She's a very driven person; I think she's in
Australia,'' the owner said crossly. Definitely not a substitute mother
figure, Anna-Mei looks like she'd walk for miles to buy the hard paper
they used to put in school toilets.
Frieda Hughes claims not to have read her mother's poetry. Maybe she
hasn't read the remaining Journals either (the ones her father, Ted
Hughes, didn't destroy), and doesn't know that her mother called her
''The Pooker''. From the look of The Pooker's paintings, she's read her
father's poetry. Foxes, wolves, herons, and fruit bats lurk on the
landscape of sinister rustic England.
She admits: ''There's a bit of my father in the subject matter but
that's not intentional.''
The most expensive painting, The Wolf (a snip at #6500), has been
sold. It's easy to sneer that Frieda would be unlikely either to show or
sell her work if she wasn't the daughter of famous parents she refuses
to discuss. And yet who would criticise a surgeon's son for following
his father into medicine? The artist's child is allowed to inherit the
sins of the parents -- why not the success genes?
Children of famous parents have as much right to glory as anyone else.
Some -- like Isabella Rossellini, Dominic Lawson, Michael Douglas, and
Liza Minnelli -- may have used their connections at the start of their
careers, but somehow have to be better than their rivals to succeed. And
for every success story, there's a junkie politician's daughter or
actor's son. It would be wrong to criticise Frieda Hughes for painting
and writing (five children's books). It would be wrong to be kind about
her work because she grew up as a motherless child.
Frieda Hughes's paintings looked dated -- Max Ernst meets Rousseau,
with a (presumably intentional) nursery paintbox execution. They look
how you would expect the daughter of Ted (animal poems) Hughes to paint.
And yet there's a presence to both her and her work. The paintings of
big birds and rooks are almost so bad they're interesting. Is it ''her''
that evokes this unsettling aura, or is it what she's associated with?
It isn't possible or sensible to separate the self from its history.
As she says: ''You are a part of your parents whether you like it or
not.'' She can't be held responsible for other people's obsession with
her mother's suicide and her father's image as an homme fatal,
especially when she goes out of her way not to exploit it. But she can't
avoid either having her indirect place in death culture, even if she
didn't chose it.
Death is one thing that definitely interests everybody. Tilda
Swinton's imitation of a corpse attracted 21,000 voyeurs to the
Serpentine gallery last week. A large man with a chequebook looked at
the pale, serene, sleeping Swinton and asked: ''How much is the dummy in
the case?''
Tilda Swinton was merely impersonating death. Suicide is a way of
controlling death. The suicidee has the last word -- and leaves the
living repulsed, envious, and fascinated.
Fame comes and goes, but some people reach a peak on the fame
spectrum. Once this point has been passed, it's impossible to slip back
into oblivion. Princess Diana is possibly the only woman who could outdo
Plath and Monroe in the death cult war. Monroe had her beauty, Sylvia
her brains, and the alive but sometimes not well Diana has her instinct.
The pouting princess knows how to exploit death culture without dying.
Like Marilyn, she's worshipped as a blonde goddess. Like Sylvia, she's a
wounded mother whose husband was seduced by somebody else. It's easy to
imagine a copy of The Bell Jar face down on Diana's bedside table.
Anything's possible.
It's easy to remember unhappy endings. Some spoilsports claim that
Sylvia Plath's poetry isn't up to much -- she just made it memorable by
sticking her head in an oven like a chicken to be roasted (a macabre
touch in a family apparently obsessed with birds).
Frieda Hughes says: ''You cannot sit on achievement like a rock,
looking at the ocean. You must go beyond it.'' These could be words from
her mother's teenage diaries, spurring her Nietzschean will on. But
where there's a will there isn't always a way.
Autobiography is the best and worst of writing. Plath's art was to
convert apparent autobiography into something both confessional and
mysterious. Unfortunately her daughter's paintings are embarrassingly
artless.
* Frieda Hughes' exhibition is at the Anna-Mei Chadwick Gallery, 64
New King's Road, London (0171 736 1928) until Saturday.
* From next week, Family Extra moves to Mondays.
</TEXT>
