<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950919-000137</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950919-000137</DOCID>
<DATE>950919</DATE>
<HEADLINE>'Morning after' cure denounced</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JONATHAN NORTHCROFT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976306427</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A HERBAL ''morning after'' cure aimed at motorists, which claims to
flush alcohol from the bloodstream two-and-a-half hours after heavy
drinking, was roundly condemned last night by police and road safety
campaigners.
Sober-Up, a capsule remedy to be launched in the UK during the
December Christmas party season, will be sold in pub vending machines by
the Merseyside-based company Jonnies.
The firm, which specialises in pub condom sales, claims the product
will reduce blood-alcohol levels by 40% within an hour and clear the
system completely two-and-a-half hours after consumption.
The product costs 50p a dose.
Although Sober-Up's packaging depicts a car driving home in the middle
of the night, the company insists the remedy is intended for ''morning
after drivers'' and not those travelling the same night.
Co-ordinator for Campaign Against Drink Driving, Mrs Maria Cape,
called for the capsules to be banned.
She said: ''The product condones drink driving. The picture of the car
on the packet is appalling. Even if used for the day after, drivers must
learn that any alcohol in the bloodstream the next morning can affect
their perception and be fatal.''
Road safety educator Inspector Kenneth Buchanan, of Lothian and
Borders Police traffic division expressed ''grave personal concern''
about the product: ''There is no guarantee it will be effective and yet
if it doesn't work it could kill.''
Jonnies managing director Maurice Brookes said yesterday that Sober-Up
had been marketed in the US for several years under different names and
had been approved by that country's Food and Drink Authority.
Mr Brookes said he anticipated that the American certification for the
product meant it would not require further testing before it was sold.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
