<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950919-000139</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950919-000139</DOCID>
<DATE>950919</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Clergy advised to make security improvements</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JAMES ROBERTSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976306429</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MINISTERS in Scotland are to be urged to be less trusting of their
fellow man and more aware of the darker side of human nature.
The lesson will be hammered home by police in a bid to reduce the
growing number of thefts from and vandalism attacks on churches.
A special seminar on the problem has been organised for Scottish
Episcopal clergy and church officers by the Ecclesiastical Insurance
Group, the major insurer of the Church's property, with the blessing of
the Scottish bishops.
The conference on October 21 takes place five months after the rise in
theft and damage suffered by churches of all denominations was
highlighted by the Scottish Office.
The debate at the Scottish Police College at Tulliallan will be the
first of its kind in Scotland.
A spokesman for Ecclesiastical Insurance, Mr Brian King, said
yesterday: ''The clergy are not taught to be suspicious of their fellow
man at college. We and the police can give them some advice from the
more suspicious world.
''We thought it was time to help the Scottish Churches stop further
attacks. We have held 40 seminars in other parts of Britain, but this is
our first in Scotland.''
The audience will be told of the dangers of leaving church keys in
''hiding places'' and that thieves do not always look like people
imagine them to look.
Theft and malicious damage suffered by Church properties in Scotland
increased by more than 70% between 1989 and 1993.
In May the Scottish Office produced a booklet listing crime prevention
advice for Church groups.
Father Tom Connolly, Scottish spokesman for the Roman Catholic Church,
said several churches had been fitted with security cameras and alarms.
A Kirk spokesman said: ''Congregations are encouraged to take advice
from their local crime prevention officers to improve the security of
their buildings.''
Strathclyde Police crime prevention officer Inspector John O'Neill,
who will address the seminar, said: ''People have changed their views
about Church property and are willing to take anything that is
unattended. There is a lot of money to be made from the property in
churches.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950919-000140</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950919-000140</DOCID>
<DATE>950919</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Focus on BAe plant</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976306430</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
HIGH level discussions on the future of the British Aerospace plant at
Prestwick will be held in London today.
Five Ayrshire MPs, concerned about a number of recent developments
within the aviation industry in general and BAe in particular, will meet
chief executive Dick Evans.
The MPs, Mr Brian Donohoe (Cunninghame South), Mr George Foulkes
(Carrick, Cumnock and Doon Valley), Mr Phil Gallie (Ayr), Mr Willie
McKelvey (Kilmarnock), and Mr Brian Wilson (Cunninghame South) are
anxious to clear up doubts cast on Prestwick by announcements in the
past few months.
These include a deal being negotiated by BAe and China to build a new
100-seat jet, work on the Future Large Aircraft being developed as a
possible replacement for the Hercules, and implications of the venture
on turboprop planes with Italian/French consortium ATR.
There is also concern over the long term future of production of the
Jetstream 41 turboprop airliner.
There are almost 2000 people employed at Prestwick by the two BAe
subsidiaries based there -- Jetstream Aircraft and BAe Aerostructures.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950919-000141</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950919-000141</DOCID>
<DATE>950919</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Rail travellers face 'doubled' fares after privatisation</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>LACHIE KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976306431</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SCOTS rail travellers will face rocketing fares, which could double in
some cases, and restricted route choices when Britain's train services
are privatised next year.
Passenger watchdog committees are planning to fight planned proposals,
outlined in a 1000-page guide prepared by the 25 train companies and
stipulating the only routes passengers will be allowed to use between
destinations.
If the plans go ahead passengers will not be allowed to travel by
circular routes unless they pay more.
Last night Labour's rail spokesman, Mr Henry McLeish, warned: ''This
will be a disaster, a complete nightmare, and something we will
vigorously battle against.''
He added: ''There is likely to be a total explosion in rail fares. You
are talking here of private monopolies taking as much as they can from
the rail travelling public. It will be horrific. It will be a nightmare.
''It is not scaremongering to suggest fares will double and this will
drive people off the railways. It is certainly not the way to develop a
railway system for the 21st century.''
Mr Bill Ure, secretary of the Rail Transport Users Consultative
Committee for Scotland, said: ''This is a retrograde step and we would
resent the withdrawal of the facility to people allowing them to stop
off during their journey. We will be resisting it.''
Labour is already claiming that fares could more than double for
people who want to break their journey.
The party claims that a passenger travelling on a Glasgow-to-London
saver return, at a cost of #72, who wanted to travel home via Sheffield
would have to buy a single ticket from London to Sheffield at #37.50 and
one from Sheffield to Glasgow at #47, more than doubling the present
fare to #156.50.
Shadow Transport Secretary Michael Meacher said: ''The Government has
said all along that the new structure would retain all the benefits of
the pre-privatisation network. That has been blown out of the water. It
is a lunatic proposal.''
He added that he would demand a debate as soon as Parliament returned.
Major General Lennox Napier, chairman of the Central Rail Users
Consultative Committee, based in London, said the guide had been
produced because of the need to define the income of the 25 companies
into which BR has been split.
He said: ''It's a reduction in the quality of service. It's entirely
for the benefit of the fragmented industry and the apportioning of the
revenues.''
He added that he was also concerned that passengers could face long
delays or higher charges where trains take different routes at differnt
times of the day.
A spokesman for BR said: ''It will be up to the private companies to
set the fares and decide on routes.''
* RAIL passengers who got an unexpected trip to London when their
train driver forgot to stop at Slough will not be compensated, they
learned yesterday.
They were ferried back to Berkshire on another train and finally
arrived at Slough 55 minutes late -- five minutes short of the
qualifying time laid down in the Passengers' Charter.
The forgetful driver of the Cardiff-Paddington express will be
interviewed by Great Western Trains.
A spokesman said: ''It appears that the driver forgot to stop at the
station and instead continued on to Paddington.
''He apologised to his customers aboard the train and we would like to
say sorry to them as well.''
The spokesman added: ''There will not be any compensation because they
were not held up for an hour or more. The Passengers' Charter is quite
clear on the subject of compensation.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950919-000142</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950919-000142</DOCID>
<DATE>950919</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Devoted football club president suffered 'brutal and sustained' attack during robbery. Son in plea to find father's killer</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>GRAEME SMITH</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976306432</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE son of football club president Mr Harold Petrie, who died after a
''brutal and sustained'' attack during a robbery, yesterday appealed for
help to catch his father's killer.
Mr Petrie, 46, was found lying with stab wounds only yards from
Inverurie Loco Works, the football club ''he lived and died for'' after
his wife, Helen, the club treasurer, had been assaulted and robbed of
around #5000 in the early hours of Sunday morning.
Mr Petrie, described as ''one of the nicest men you could hope to
meet'', may have been murdered as he tried to stop his wife's assailant
from escaping with the club money.
His wife was not injured in the robbery and was able to call the
police. The first two officers on the scene found Mr Petrie lying on
Harlaw Road.
Yesterday, bouquets of flowers, a football club shirt, and ties marked
the spot where he was found dying.
Around 70 officers are involved in door-to-door inquiries and a search
for the murder weapon or any other clues to the killing, which has
stunned the town.
Police confirmed they were looking at the possibility of a link with
an almost identical raid at Cove Rangers FC Social Club in November.
The masked raider in that incident stabbed a club member who went to
the aid of the club steward, who was also stabbed.
It is thought the raider in the latest incident, which took place
after closing time, may also have been masked.
Mr Petrie and his wife had virtually run the club for the past year
and had been clearing up following a disco attended by about 200 people,
which finished at midnight on Saturday. The robbery took place shortly
after 2am.
The couple have a son, Michael, 24, and a daughter Louise, 20. Michael
was on his way home from a night out in Inverurie with a friend when he
saw the police activity outside the club and went to investigate. Inside
the club, his mother and grandfather broke the tragic news to him.
Michael said yesterday: ''The family are devastated. I don't have
words to say how we feel. I just hope they can catch whoever did it and
give him what he deserves.''
He appealed to anyone who might be shielding the killer, who may well
have been bloodstained, to contact the police.
He said his father was not an aggressive man and was well liked in the
community. As well as being deeply involved in the Loco Works football
team, he was a pigeon racer.
Detective Inspector Pat Shearer, who is leading the investigation,
said police were trying to establish the movements of everyone who had
attended the club on Saturday and everyone who was in the area around
the time of the incident.
''There were quite a number of cars still moving around in the
vicinity of the club at the time and we would like to speak to any of
the drivers,'' he said.
''It is very possible that someone, somewhere is shielding the
attacker and has information which may help us. We would appeal to them
to come forward because this was a brutal and sustained attack and we
must track down the person or persons responsible.''
The chairman of the club's executive committee, local baker Mr George
Ross, said the club would remain closed in the meantime as a mark of
respect to Mr Petrie.
''The officials and members of the Inverurie Loco Works FC are all
stunned and greatly saddened by the tragic death of our president,'' he
said. ''Harold was one of the nicest men you could wish to meet. Harold,
along with his wife, Helen, were heavily involved in the running of the
club and put in a tremendous amount of work, far beyond the call of
duty. Harold's contribution will be greatly missed.
''Outside his family, Harold's passion was with Inverurie Loco Works
FC. Indeed, he looked after the club as he would a member of his family.
With true paternal instincts, he cared for the club, was available for
the club whenever help was required, and protected the club.
''Tragically, he died protecting the club he loved so much.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950919-000143</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950919-000143</DOCID>
<DATE>950919</DATE>
<HEADLINE>MPs' secretary in aid fraud</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976306433</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A FORMER constituency secretary to two Liberal Democrat MPs yesterday
told a court she ''forgot'' about #76,000 of cash assets when she made
three false claims for legal aid.
Mairi Clark, 44, of Onam, Kinnairdie Avenue, Dingwall, was found
guilty after trial of making false statements about her finances when
seeking legal aid on three occasions in 1993 and 1994.
Sheriff Keir Marshall did not impose a fine but ordered her to repay
the #1253 legal aid.
Clark claimed she was ''under considerable harassment'' from her
estranged husband, Michael, when she applied to an Inverness firm of
solicitors for legal aid to institute divorce proceedings and raise an
action against him for breach of interdict.
She claimed on August 12, 1993, that her savings were #4327 whereas
she had #7469 in a building society and nearly #69,000 in an account in
Jersey.
On September 15, 1993, she said her savings were only #200 while she
had the same amount as before in the building society, #60,000 in an
offshore investment account and over #11,000 in her bank account in
Dingwall.
On January 17, 1994, after stating her savings were frozen and failing
to disclose a balance of #8000 in her building society and #54,000 in an
offshore account, she obtained emergency legal aid amounting to #1253.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950919-000144</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950919-000144</DOCID>
<DATE>950919</DATE>
<HEADLINE>#500m investment with a touch of tartan. BA brings back the luxury</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DAVID STEELE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976306434</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE largest investment ever made by an airline in the service it
offers its passengers was launched with a touch of tartan yesterday.
British Airways will spend #500m over the next three years in
improvements to its First and Club World service in a bid to establish
the carrier as the first choice airline throughout the world.
Among the innovations are a specially designed blue-and-white tartan,
patented and registered, which will be used in blankets, pillows, and
mugs in the new cabins.
A #160,000 contract connected with the relaunch of premium services,
the largest ever and being watched closely by the industry, was won by
Bridge of Weir Leather, which will supply hides for the new seats on
Boeing 747, 777, and DC10 aircraft. The company has already supplied
leather for the seats on the British Airways fleet of seven Concordes.
Among the first passengers to experience the new ''cradle'' seats in
Club World class, which offer increased legroom and comfort, will be
those travelling between Glasgow, New York, and Boston.
The return fare for the service to New York, for example, will be
between #3500 and #4000.
The airline is turning the clock back to the heyday of transatlantic
travel by offering 14 individual cabins on its 747 First service, each
of which has a 6ft 6in bed which converts into an armchair.
Personal video entertainment and lighting gives each passenger
complete privacy and control without disturbing others .
British Airways chairman Sir Colin Marshall said: ''This bold
initiative will ensure British Airways' position as the first choice
airline worldwide.''
Virgin boss Mr Richard Branson responded yesterday by offering BA
chiefs holidays on his Caribbean island if their airline could beat his
in business class figures. There was no comment from British Airways
last night.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950919-000145</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950919-000145</DOCID>
<DATE>950919</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Tangled lines led to deaths</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976306435</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
TWO men who died after their small boat capsized off the coast of a
remote Scottish island were the victims of a tragic accident, police
said yesterday.
Police and coastguards said that the three crew of the 18ft Kes, which
capsized 200 yards from Vaila on the west side of Shetland, accidentally
got their fishing lines tangled in the outboard motor's propellor.
''A mixture of fishing lines fouled around the propellor and the sea
swell was responsible for the accident,'' said Mr Neville Davis,
coastguard district controller for Shetland.
''Even though the weather conditions were not too bad there was quite
a sea running. If anything goes wrong with a boat in those conditions it
can be very dangerous.''
A spokesman for Northern Constabulary described the incident as ''a
tragic accident''.
''We are compiling a report for the Marine Accident Investigation
Branch and it will be up to them whether they want to investigate
further,'' he said.
''But from past experience it appears simply to have been a tragic
accident and will be noted as such.''
Salmon farmer Leif Einarson, 33, was still missing presumed dead
yesterday as the search for his body moved into its second day.
Mr Einarson, a father of two, from Kirkidale, Walls, is believed to
have been thrown into the water when the boat capsized.
Knitwear worker Trevor Blair, 27, also from Kirkidale, was found
attached to the upturned boat by tangled fishing gear early on Sunday
morning after a five-hour search.
The alarm was raised late on Saturday night after the men failed to
return from a three-hour fishing trip.
Mr Blair was married with an 18-month-old daughter.
Mr Blair's brother-in-law, Mr Terry Chapman, 33, of New Road, Walls,
survived the tragedy by swimming ashore.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950919-000146</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950919-000146</DOCID>
<DATE>950919</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Girl, six, dies on rope swing</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ROB ROBERTSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976306436</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A SMALL farming community was in mourning yesterday after the death of
a six-year-old girl in a rope swing accident in her garden.
Victoria Crook was found dead by her seven-year-old sister Katie. She
had become entangled in two lengths of nylon rope which made up the
home-made swing.
The incident took place at the back of the family home at Myreton
Farm, Logiealmond, Perthshire, on Saturday afternoon.
Katie ran to tell her parents, William, 43, and Elaine, 34, who had
been picking mushrooms at the front of the house, screaming: ''Mummy,
daddy, I think Vicky's dead.''
Mr Crook made desparate efforts to revive his daughter but she was
confirmed dead on arrival at Perth Royal Infirmary.
Locals in the area around the farm, on a road near Little Glenshee,
were too upset to talk about the death.
Teachers at Logiealmond Primary School, where Victoria was in primary
two, were also too distraught to comment.
The couple, as well as Katie and their other daughter, Alexandra, were
being comforted by friends last night.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950919-000147</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950919-000147</DOCID>
<DATE>950919</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Actor's #16m tourism credit</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976306437</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MEL Gibson is being credited for a #16m boost to the Scottish tourist
industry. The Loch Lomond, Stirling and Trossachs Tourist Board
estimates his movie, Braveheart, will attract the extra business over
the next 18 months.
A survey by Forth Valley Enterprise also reveals publicity for the
Stirling premiere of his film was worth #2m of free advertising for the
area.
</TEXT>
