<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950919-000157</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950919-000157</DOCID>
<DATE>950919</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Hong Kong democrats celebrate voters' slap in face for Beijing</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976306447</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Hong Kong, Monday
HONG KONG voters have slapped China in the face by handing a
convincing victory to the pro-democracy camp in the last legislative
polls before the 1997 handover of the colony to Beijing rule.
In the race to elect all 60 members of Hong Kong's Legislative Council
for the first time in 150 years of British rule, the Democratic Party,
whose leaders have denounced by China as subversives, won three times as
many seats as pro-China rivals.
Beijing's standard bearers, the Democratic Alliance for the Betterment
of Hong Kong (DAB), were further humiliated by the defeat of its top
guns, party leader Tsang Yok-sing and his two deputies.
However the victory in yesterday's election was not enough to give the
pro-democracy camp a majority in the Legislative Council and the chamber
appeared evenly split between pro-China and pro-democracy forces. The
Democrats won 19 seats while labour, independent, and other probable
allies won another 10 for a total of 29.
The DAB and its close labour allies won eight seats. The pro-business
Liberal Party, which often looks on the Democrats with suspicion, won
10. The balance of independents and small parties are mostly
conservatives or pro-China.
The DAB's poorer than expected performance, however, is expected to
anger China, which repeated its vow to dismantle the legislature when
the British leave and to replace it with an institution of its own
choosing.--Reuter.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950919-000158</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950919-000158</DOCID>
<DATE>950919</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Arab court stands by maid death sentence</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976306448</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Abu Dhabi, Monday
THE United Arab Emirates today defended the death sentence against
Filipina maid Sarah Balabagan, saying the court had enough evidence to
prove she was guilty of the premeditated murder of her Arab employer.
''The court was satisfied with the validity of the charge against the
defendant and was convinced with a clear conscience that she committed
this ugly premeditated crime,'' said the Ministry of Justice.
Working conditions of the hundreds of thousands of foreign maids in
the Gulf are under renewed scrutiny after the UAE court on Saturday
sentenced the 16-year-old to death.
Sarah said her employer was trying to rape her when she stabbed him.
She was originally sentenced to seven years' imprisonment for
manslaughter, but UAE president Sheikh Zaid Bin Sultan al-Nahayan
ordered a retrial.
The court found her guilty of murder and sentenced her to be shot by
firing squad.
In Manila, the Philippine Government tried to calm public anger over
the Balabagan case, warning that flag-burning protests might only harm
efforts to save her life.
Officials at the same time rejected proposals for a ban on the sending
of maids overseas, saying this could have a serious economic backlash
for the country.
''I understand how our countrymen feel but there is a need for calm
and sobriety,'' Foreign Secretary Domingo Siazon said.
Solicitor General Raul Goco said burning the UAE flag could boomerang
on Sarah.
''Let us not be very emotional about this,'' he said.
Some Filipino diplomats believed the death sentence might have been
partly spurred by the burning of the UAE flag recently by Filipinos
protesting against the previous sentence.
President Fidel Ramos has said he will personally write to Sheikh Zaid
in an attempt to save the maid from execution. He also ordered her
lawyers to appeal against the verdict before higher UAE courts.
Sarah's plight is the second case of its kind in six months to stir an
emotional outburst in the country.
Filipinos burned Singapore's flags in March after another maid, Flor
Contemplacion, was hanged there for double murder despite Ramos's pleas
for her life.
In other developments today, a Kuwaiti court jailed a woman for 10
years for beating her Sri Lankan maid to death, lawyers said.
The Arab Times newspaper said the accused was the wife of a police
sergeant. It did not disclose her name or nationality, but a lawyer said
she was an Arab.
The woman later asked her husband to help her dispose of the body by
throwing it into the sea, but the husband refused and told the police.
In another incident involving a maid, the family of 24-year-old
Filipina Margaret Almogela, who was allegedly killed by the Iraqi wife
of her employer, accepted #36,000 blood money to drop the charges, the
Kuwait Times reported.--Reuter.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950919-000159</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950919-000159</DOCID>
<DATE>950919</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Accused learned butchery in prison. 'Tourist from hell' to face murder trial</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976306449</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Singapore, Monday
A BRITON dubbed the ''Tourist from Hell'' was a quick learner at
butchery courses, a Singapore court was told today.
Mr John Martin Scripps, who is accused of embarking on a global
killing spree and chopping up his alleged victims' bodies after he
absconded from jail, first did a butchery course at Albany prison on the
Isle Of Wight.
He ''quickly learned the difficult task of de-boning a carcass'', said
prison officer Mr James Quigley, who helped teach a six-week course in
April 1993 which Mr Scripps completed.
Mr Scripps is the first Briton in Singapore to face death by hanging
for the alleged murder of South African brewery engineer Mr Gerald Lowe,
whose body was found chopped up in plastic bags, floating in Singapore
harbour in March.
Mr Scripps, 35, from London, is also wanted in Thailand for the
alleged murder of Canadian Sheila Damude and her 23-year-old son Daren.
Mr Scripps is also wanted in connection with the death of Briton
Timothy McDowall, from South London, in Mexico earlier this year.
According to witnesses, Scripps used his alleged victims' credit
cards.
In Singapore the day after he allegedly murdered Mr Lowe he used the
South African's passport and credit card to withdraw #5600. A shop
assistant claimed he boasted that he spent the night getting drunk at
Singapore's famous Raffles Hotel.
He is also alleged to have bought a video camera and hi-fi speakers.
Prosecutor Jennifer Marie presented 20 boxes of grisly evidence which
filled one side of the court. They included 333 photographs of body
parts.
On a table tools allegedly used by Mr Scripps for the murders were
laid out. They included an electric stun gun, a hammer, handcuffs, a can
of mace spray, and knives.
The prosecutor took five hours presenting statements from 77 witnesses
from Singapore, Britain, Thailand, and South Africa.
A hotel receptionist described how the pair had booked into the River
View Hotel on March 8 and how Mr Scripps said he had kicked Mr Lowe out
of the room after he made a homosexual pass.
A security guard claimed that on March 11 at 6.30am, he watched Mr
Scripps drag a heavy black suitcase out of the hotel only to return
empty-handed 15 minutes later.
Mr Scripps, wearing a blue floral silk shirt, jeans, and black shoes,
sat impassively throughout the hearing.
Police and coastguard officials described their grisly find of Mr
Lowe's body parts floating off Cliffords Pier in Singapore Harbour. When
they checked Mr Scripps's room, they found bloodstains in the bathroom
and on sheets.
Dr Michael John Barber, a British forensic scientist, said in a
written statement that after examining the samples he ''found extreme
support that blood from Lowe's body parts was the same as that found in
the hotel''.
After the statements were read Mr Scripps' lawyer, Mr Edmond Pereira,
said he would give no submissions nor enter a plea.
Mr Scripps spoke only to say: ''I wish to reserve my defence until my
trial.''
After the five-hour hearing, Magistrate Karolyn Gin said there were
sufficient grounds for the accused to face trial for murder and Mr
Scripps was taken to the Taneh Merah top security prison.
The trial is expected to begin early next month.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950919-000160</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950919-000160</DOCID>
<DATE>950919</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Kashmir kidnappers 'under fire'</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976306450</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Srinagar, Monday
KASHMIRI kidnappers who have killed one Western hostage and hold four
others, including two Britons, today claimed that Indian army commandos
had attacked their base in the Himalayas and that they could no longer
ensure their captives' safety.
Meanwhile, officials close to the negotiations said the Indian
Government had offered the rebel group Al-Faran up to 40 million rupees
(more than #800,000) to release the remaining Westerners seized in July.
The militants said in a telephone call to a news agency in Srinagar:
''Indian commandos attacked one of our bases in the Pahalgam area and
there was a gun battle.
''There are casualties, but we don't have the details,'' said the
caller. ''We have reached a conclusion that the government of India is
not keen to get the foreign tourists freed safely.''
However a government spokesman told the United News of India he had no
information about a conflict.
Al-Faran kidnapped six Westerners in early July as they trekked
through the Himalayan mountains. American John Childs escaped, but the
decapitated body of Hans Christian Ostro of Norway was found last month.
The reported ransom would be the first time the government has offered
money for the captives' freedom.
The four captives are Britons Keith Mangan, 33, and Paul Wells, 23;
American Donald Hutchings, 42; and German Dirk Hasert, 26.--Reuter/AP.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950919-000161</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950919-000161</DOCID>
<DATE>950919</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Nuclear watchdog criticises France and China for testing</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976306451</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Vienna, Monday
FRANCE and China came under fire today for recent nuclear tests when
the United Nations atomic watchdog agency began its annual meeting and
11 nations launched a petition to halt the testing.
Without naming France and China, whose recent nuclear tests have drawn
worldwide rebukes, the group of mostly Pacific nations put forth a
resolution to the International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA) calling for
a moratorium.
''The general conference deplores the resumption of nuclear tests and
urges those states which have active nuclear testing programmes in place
to desist from testing,'' the resolution said.
It was signed by Australia, New Zealand, Chile, Ecuador, Indonesia,
Malaysia, Mexico, the Philippines, Thailand, Venezuela, and Vietnam.
The resolution is not expected to get far because key countries such
as the United States and Britain, two of the world's five official
nuclear powers, would not openly criticise France's nuclear policies,
officials said.
Others among the 103 member states attending the conference at IAEA
headquarters in Vienna were also critical of the testing.
''It is most regrettable that nuclear tests are still being conducted
in defiance of a strong global desire for the cessation of testing,''
said Yasuoki Urano, the leader of Japan's delegation.
''Japan emphatically calls for the cessation of all nuclear testing,''
he said to loud applause.
No immediate comment was available from France or China, both of which
have delegations at the week-long conference.
President Bill Clinton, in a statement read to the assembly, did not
mention China or France but said he was committed to a test ban and
nuclear disarmament.
BREST: New Zealanders protesting against French nuclear testing in the
South Pacific sailed yachts into the port of Brest today near the main
base of France's nuclear missile-armed submarine fleet.
The boats sailed near a military area of the port in north-western
France but without venturing to the nearby Ile Longue island where
France's nuclear submarines are based.
Other New Zealanders were in Strasbourg today to meet members of the
European Parliament.--Reuter.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950919-000162</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950919-000162</DOCID>
<DATE>950919</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Serb bullet welcomes the Foreign Secretary's party</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CHRISTOPHER REEKIE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976306452</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A BULLET passed within 30 metres of British Foreign Secretary Malcolm
Rifkind's party in Sarajevo yesterday, stealing the thunder of his first
visit to the besieged Bosnian capital.
In a city where getting wounded instead of killed is counted a good
day by many residents, commenting on a bullet which passed 30 metres
distant might be viewed as bad form.
Not so for members of the London press corps travelling with Rifkind,
who know a good story when it goes bang.
Veteran combat cameramen covering the Foreign Secretary were unaware
anything had happened until their agencies began getting calls based on
news stories emanating from London.
UN officials familiar with the incident, which occurred while the
Foreign Secretary was visiting a development project funded by the UK
Government, said the shooting was sparked by a vehicle in the motorcade
which parked in plain view of Serb front lines.
They said a single shot was fired at the vehicle from the Serb side of
the line, after which a UN soldier went to move the car and was himself
fired upon.
That triggered a burst of machine-gun fire at the Serbs from Bosnian
government soldiers in the area, after which the shooting stopped.
''Mr Rifkind was never in any danger and we believe that the entire
incident has been somewhat blown out of proportion,'' said one official.
Mr Rifkind, if he was aware of the incident, appeared unruffled and
continued with his programme.
The Foreign Secretary also visited British peacekeepers in Sarajevo
and met the Bosnian President and Foreign Minister.
The Bosnian government used the opportunity to propose opening a
dialogue with ''responsible'' Serb leaders.
Mr Rifkind welcomed the initiative and said the UK Government would
assist in any way possible.
''I very much welcome the thinking behind it (the government proposal)
and we hope it could provide the basis for an effective ceasefire
throughout Bosnia Herzegovina,'' he told a news conference.
Meanwhile,the deliberate decision by Mr Rifkind to do without a flak
jacket while in Sarajevo was last night described as ''an act of faith''
by the head of a Scots charity who has just returned from a mercy
mission to the city, writes Christopher Reekie.
Dr Denis Rutovitz, chairman of Edinburgh Direct Aid, himself wounded
in the shoulder by a bullet last April, said the front line positions
were ''very dangerous''.
''I think he is a brave man and I salute him,'' he added.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950919-000163</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950919-000163</DOCID>
<DATE>950919</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Third South African serial killer at large</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976306453</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Boksburg, Monday
A SOUTH African police reservist hunting rabbits stumbled over the
body of a murdered black woman and detectives today found the remains of
nine more.
Police commissioner George Fivaz told reporters the first body was
discovered at the weekend on the outskirts of Boksburg, east of
Johannesburg. Searches uncovered the others today.
''All indications are that it is the work of a serial killer,'' he
said. Police believe the first killing took place about a month ago and
the most recent last week.
Violent crime has surged in post-apartheid South Africa. President
Nelson Mandela said recently a serious crime was committed somewhere in
the country every 17 seconds. Another report said there were 55 murders
each day.
Fivaz offered a #91,000 reward for information leading to an arrest
and conviction.
He plans to call in experts from Scotland Yard and the FBI to help in
the hunt.
There were no indications that the women were murdered by the
so-called Atteridgeville Strangler, a serial killer believed to have
killed 15 women and a boy near Pretoria.
In June, a Cape Town judge jailed Norman Afzal Simons for 25 years for
murdering a boy. Police suspect Simons of being the so-called Station
Strangler, who was believed to have murdered 22 people over eight years.
NEW YORK: Former landscape gardener Joel Rifkin, 36, who admitted
killing 17 women and having sex with their bodies before dismembering
them, was today given maximum sentences of 25 years to life for two of
the murders. He is already serving 27 years to life for murdering
another woman.--Reuter.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950919-000164</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950919-000164</DOCID>
<DATE>950919</DATE>
<HEADLINE>US urges troops out of Cyprus</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976306454</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WASHINGTON: Congress yesterday approved a resolution describing
Turkish military occupation of north Cyprus as unacceptable and calling
for demilitarisation of the divided island.
The House of Representatives urged the US and United Nations to solve
the dispute through incentives for talks and sanctions, and called for
all foreign troops to be withdrawn.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950919-000165</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950919-000165</DOCID>
<DATE>950919</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Mass DNA tests may help find teenager's killer</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976306455</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
POLICE hunting the killer of Naomi Smith said yesterday they would
consider wholescale DNA testing of the local community.
Naomi, 15, had her throat slashed and was sexually mutilated last
Thursday just yards from her home in Nuneaton, Warwickshire, as she went
to post a letter.
Her body was found by her father, Brian, 47, and her best friend,
15-year-old Emma Jones.
Detective Superintendent Tony Bayliss said forensic experts would know
within 24 hours whether there was enough information from the scene of
the crime to use in an attempt to identify the killer.
He said: ''If we were fortunate enough to obtain DNA profiles, we
would consider mass screening. We have still to hear whether it will be
possible to profile any particular sample.''
Detectives in Nuneaton have been working with Derbyshire Police, who
hold an index of all murders of children and young people since 1960.
The database is being used to draw up a picture of the killer. More than
300 people have been interviewed by police and 50 detailed witness
statements have been taken.
Mr Bayliss said Naomi's parents had given detectives detailed
statements and were ''supported by my officers over the weekend''. He
added: ''They are now being helped by Victim Support, who will arrange
specialist counselling if required.
''They have gone through several phases of grief and are now in a
quiet period of reflection, coming to terms with their loss.''
Police working on the murder inquiry have still not eliminated a red
Escort car and a spiky-haired man seen running from the scene.
Officers are also looking for three young men seen outside Naomi's
home and near the playground where her body was found.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950919-000166</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950919-000166</DOCID>
<DATE>950919</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Classic vessel causes ripple in yachting circles</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DAVID STEELE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976306456</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
YACHT owners at a leading marina have been accused of forgetting their
heritage and refusing to welcome one of the world's oldest steam vessels
as it cruises the Firth of Clyde.
A letter from the management of the Largs Yacht Marina to the Scottish
Maritime Museum at Irvine, home of the steam yacht Carola, indicated the
vessel was not welcome because some yachts had been affected by soot and
smoke from its funnel.
The Carola was built at Bowling in the 1890s and was one of the
classic steam yachts of its day.
Mr Jim Tildesley, director of the Scottish Maritime Museum, said: ''It
is a pity that this has happened as we found the Largs Yacht Haven
facilities very useful when in the area and always had the impression
that the management enjoyed having one of the classic yachts of the
golden age of Clyde yachting sitting alongside today's craft.
''We understand the problem which the marina management is having with
their customers but, as far as the yachtsmen are concerned, any damage
that Carola caused would have been of a very temporary nature and a
bucket of water and some soap would have put things right.
''Perhaps on modern yachts you don't swab the decks any more.''
But, after approaches from The Herald, the management at Largs
appeared ready to welcome the vessel back.
Haven Master Bob Jenkins said: ''I think there has been a bit of a
misunderstanding here as the Carola is a welcome visitor and is popular
with berth holders and visitors alike. She is a fine craft and turns
heads wherever she goes.
''On one occasion I understand there was a problem with the engine and
more soot and smoke than usual came out of the funnel. That was a
one-off and I believe it has been sorted out.
''The Carola and her crew are welcome visitors here under normal
circumstances.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950919-000167</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950919-000167</DOCID>
<DATE>950919</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Tribunal told that part of missing cash was found in bank's toilet</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976306457</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AN industrial tribunal was told yesterday how #43,000 disappeared from
the Clydesdale Bank's Glasgow head office in November 1992 and, seven
months later, following a meeting between a senior bank manager and a
police detective, #3000 was discovered hidden in the bank.
The money was found in June 1993, after bank employee Austen Campbell
allegedly confessed to police about the theft, following the meeting. He
also allegedly told police that he had stolen another #8000 from the
bank in June 1992.
Mr Campbell, of The Auld Road, Cumbernauld Village, is claiming he was
unfairly dismissed by the bank.
The tribunal was told that suspicion for the #43,000 theft fell on Mr
Campbell, who was the last person to handle the money.
Mr Allan Ramsay, 37, a lending services manager with the bank's Credit
Bureau, carried out the investigation into the loss.
He was told on the morning of Thursday, 19 November, 1992, that one of
12 cases -- containing approximately #43,000 -- being transported to the
head office cash centre from the Scottish Exhibition Centre branch had
gone missing two days earlier.
He began to inteview staff at the cash centre, and the first person
questioned was Mr Campbell.
Mr Ramsay said: ''We had been advised Austen Campbell was the member
of staff who had received the money from Securicor.''
Mr Campbell, according to Mr Ramsay, admitted breaching the bank's
guidelines by collecting the money from the Securicor van on his own.
At another interview, Mr Campbell admitted that he bought and sold
cars and, allegedly, admitted lying to the bank when applying for a
personal loan to buy a car.
Mr Ramsay finally prepared his report on the affair late in December
1992, and he told the tribunal: ''We were not able to trace the cash.''
Mr Ramsay admitted that he was unable to rule out any of the cash room
staff as suspects because of the ''general lack of control'' over the
money.
Asked for his opinion on who was responsible, Mr Ramsay said: ''We
considered Austen Campbell was the most likely member of staff to have
been involved.''
He said that Mr Campbell had been dismissed because of his dishonesty
on the personal loan application, and because of a general lack of
confidence in him as a member of the bank's staff, but later, on appeal,
was reinstated.
Mr Colin Campbell, the Clydesdale's audit manager, told the tribunal
how, after meeting Detective Constable Robert Wardlaw at the bank in
June 1993, on another matter, Mr Austen Campbell's name was mentioned.
He then recieved a telephone call from Mr Wardlaw to say there had
been a development and Mr Austen Campbell had confessed to two thefts
from the bank, and also revealed that some money was still hidden there.
Mr Colin Campbell then searched the hiding space in the roof of the
bank toilets and found two #1000 bundles of #10 notes and foreign
currency.
Earlier this year, Mr Austen Campbell was freed by a court after a
charge of stealing #40,000 from the Clydesdale was found not proven.
Mr Austen Campbell, who was sacked after failing to attend a
disciplinary hearing in July 1993, will give evidence today.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950919-000168</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950919-000168</DOCID>
<DATE>950919</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Report reveals mounting hardship. Students go to soup kitchens</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>BARCLAY MCBAIN, EDUCATION CORRESPONDENT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976306458</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
STUDENTS who are going hungry because they cannot afford food are
visiting soup kitchens for sustenance, according to the Scottish
Association of Citizens Advice Bureaux.
In a report on growing financial hardship among under-graduates and
post-graduates published today, the association gives details of a
student who visited a citizens advice bureau in Lothian region for debt
counselling.
He had taken out a student loan and had sought a bank overdraft, but
travelling to arrange his father's funeral had left him penniless.
At his institution he had asked for help from its access fund --
designed to give financial assistance to students suffering great
hardship -- but it had been exhausted.
''When the client visited the bureau he had no money for the weekend
and had not eaten for two days. The client seemed to have approached all
possible sources of finance but none was available. The bureau gave the
client a list of places providing free food for the needy,'' the report
states.
It concludes that ''debt is a live issue for almost every student''.
Based on recent data, it shows that students without private means are
left with about #20 a week to spend on food, heat, books, and travel
after paying rent.
Weekly student income from maintenance grants and student loans rises
significantly when it covers a 38-week academic year rather than a full
calendar one, but the association points out that most students live in
private tenancies and must pay rent for 52 weeks to hold on to flats.
It says that more than 75% of students struggle to get by on a limited
income from maintenance grant and student loans, which are being
equalised in terms of their value to ease the pressure on the public
purse.
The remainder manage to secure part-time work which provides them with
badly-needed funds. But the association said: ''While the Government has
made clear that the availability of student grants and loans are to be a
contribution to a student's living expenses, it is difficult to see how
these funds can be supplemented.''
As access to higher education is opened up, more students are coming
from poorer backgrounds. But the report says their parents are coming
under pressure because they cannot make contributions to their
children's maintenance, and their offspring are unlikely to be able to
borrow money from them.
Matters are no better for mature students aged 21 and over, or for
students with families or who are single parents, says the report.
The association argues that barring the vast majority of students from
receiving state benefits and recently removing the allowance for mature
students add up to a bleak financial prospect which is leading more
young people and adults to reject higher education as an option.
''While students should not have to rely on benefit, it is difficult
to see how they can afford to make the investment in their own higher
education required when all the odds are stacked against them,'' it
said.
Ms Lin McLean, of the student advisory and counselling service at
Strathclyde University in Glasgow, said the report's findings were in
line with the results of a survey from university heads which suggested
that a 30% rise in drop-out rates had been caused by financial pressures
on students.
She said: ''A student graduating in 1997 after a four-year Scottish
honours degree will be paying back the student loan at #100 a month for
five years.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950919-000169</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950919-000169</DOCID>
<DATE>950919</DATE>
<HEADLINE>OAP sold cannabis</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976306459</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A PENSIONER who supplied drugs to children was jailed for nine months
yesterday.
Two youngsters at a children's centre in Inverness had admitted going
to the home of 68-year-old George Wilson to buy cannibas.
Police later found four camera film containers filled with wrapped
pieces of cannabis, weighing a total of 19 grammes.
Inverness Sheriff Court heard diaries containing cash figures and
comments, scales, and more than #200 were found in the house, in Upper
Kessock Street, Inverness.
Questioned by police during the search, Wilson said: ''A couple of
nine-year-olds came by wanting some but I chased them away.'' However,
in a taped interview with police, he admitted supplying 14 and
15-year-olds from his house.
Wilson admitted supplying cannabis at his home between September 4 and
October 4 last year. Sheriff William Fulton deferred sentence three
weeks ago for background reports. Defence agent Mr David Sutherland
claimed his client had made little or no money from the scheme.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950919-000170</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950919-000170</DOCID>
<DATE>950919</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Pay awards move 'could hit council tax bills'</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>FRANCES HORSBURGH, LOCAL GOVERNMENT CORRESPONDENT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976306460</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Government's refusal to fund public sector pay awards means that
council tax payers in Fife face either an average increase of #70 in
their bills next year or cuts in local services, the new council's
Labour leader has warned.
Mr Alex Rowley said yesterday the non-statutory services which could
be hit include nursery education, concessionary fares, and free home
helps.
He was challenging Scottish Secretary Michael Forsyth over his
insistence council staff pay rises must be funded out of ''efficiency
savings''.
In a letter to Mr Forsyth, he said the cost of funding pay awards in
Fife over the last two years had amounted to #12.5m. This meant a direct
transfer of costs from national taxation to a rise in average council
tax of more than #116.
Funding a pay award in line with the current rate of inflation next
year would cost the new unitary council more than #7m, he claimed.
Councillor Rowley also called for councils to be given direct control
over local taxes. At present the Scottish Office controlled 85% of
council budgets and only 15% was raised locally.
The Scottish Secretary's recent claims to be promoting local democracy
and local accountability would only become credible if he returned
control of local taxes to local councils, he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950919-000171</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950919-000171</DOCID>
<DATE>950919</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Bowie to tour UK</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976306461</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SINGER David Bowie is expected to announce his first British tour for
five years this week.
However, fans of such hits as Jean Genie, Heroes, and Let's Dance are
likely to be disappointed as Bowie has refused to play any of his older
songs since 1990.
Instead, on his current US tour Bowie, 48, has bewildered audiences
with a barrage of noise from his experimental new album, Outside -- The
Voyeur of Utter Destruction.
Despite lukewarm reaction from some critics, that is what he is
determined to do when he visits Britain later this year.
Bowie has weaved some older songs into the US sets but the only one
which is really well-known is Man Who Sold The World.
His 1990 Sound and Vision world tour was a reprise of all the hits but
critics said then he had joined the nostalgia industry. A Bowie
spokeswoman denied he had any hard-and-fast policy about songs.
Bowie's single, The Heart's Filthy Lesson, entered this week's record
sales charts at number 35.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950919-000172</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950919-000172</DOCID>
<DATE>950919</DATE>
<HEADLINE>An unwilling partner has his say</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>STEPHEN MCGREGOR</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<FLAG>ANNUAL CONFERENCE</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976306462</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
LIBERAL Democrat president Robert Maclennan yesterday produced a
barnstorming conference speech which belied his image as, to use his own
words, ''very slightly pedantic'' and ''another nervous lawyer,''
(writes Stephen McGregor)
Mr Maclennan, MP for Caithness and Sutherland, attacked both Labour
and the Tories as he left the conference in no doubt that he believes
his party should continue to set out its own, alternative agenda.
He mocked Tony Blair's Shadow Cabinet team as looking like a ''group
of synchronised swimmers . . . cautious ''till you could scream''.
He said Labour had needed to moderate its views. However, now it
lacked passionate belief and a constructive will to reform.
Election victories came only to those parties not afraid to proclaim
their commitment to reform.
''If Labour wins by sidling in without priorities or commitments, they
will flounder in the marshes. It would be a deserved fate for a party
which betrayed hope.''
Shadow Chancellor Gordon Brown was described as a ''sleekit, cowering,
timorous beastie,'' but a great deal of Mr Maclennan's vitriol was
reserved for the Tories.
He said: ''The only powers the Tories have given up willingly are the
powers to regulate scandal. They will not regulate Cedric Brown, they
will regulate no carnivorous utility company.
''With the Tories, less government has meant more power drawn from
local government to Whitehall. Less government has meant more power
drawn from elected bodies to unelected quangos.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950919-000173</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950919-000173</DOCID>
<DATE>950919</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Tough measures on  North Sea pollution backed</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ROBBIE DINWOODIE, SCOTTISH POLITICAL CORRESPONDENT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<FLAG>ANNUAL CONFERENCE</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>976306463</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE North Sea must be protected from pollution and the dumping of
former oil installations, the conference agreed yesterday, (writes
Robbie Dinwoodie).
It backed a strong package of measures proposed by Scottish party
leader Jim Wallace, on the basis that the Brent Spar saga showed that as
long as environmental risks remained there should be strict controls.
Mr Wallace, who spoke with the experience of an MP representing Orkney
and Shetland, said a ''flush and forget'' attitude to dumping in the sea
should be consigned to history.
''The Greenpeace apology this month should be seen as a frank
admission of error in calculating the volume of oil left on the Brent
Spar,'' said Mr Wallace. However, he added that some had made too much
of this.
''To listen to the reaction of the oil industry to the over-the-top
comments of Energy Minister Tim Eggar, you would have thought that
Greenpeace had conceded the whole case for dumping the Brent Spar at
sea. Not a bit of it.''
Mr Wallace argued that if it was unacceptable for ordinary vessels to
dump garbage at sea it could not be acceptable to dump an entire
structure which had no independent inventory of the waste on board and
where there had been a wholly inadequate assessment of the marine
environment involved.
He said: ''If the Brent Spar was to be dumped at sea against that
background of risk, it would be a gross violation of the precautionary
principle and would set a quite unacceptable precedent.
''For too long we have allowed a flush and forget attitude to our seas
involving sewerage, toxic waste and hazardous substances. All have
contributed to the pollution of our marine environment and that attitude
must be consigned to history.''
The conference accepted an amendment to a reference to reducing
pollution from British vessels, deleting the word British to include all
international shipping but it refused to accept a call to delete a
clause banning the dumping of oil installations at sea called for by
some who said this was too dogmatic a position.
There was an intervention in the debate by veteran Liberal activist
Ludovic Kennedy, who suggested that what was missing from the motion
before the conference was recognition that this was precisely the kind
of matter which should be dealt with by a Scottish parliament rather
than by Westminster legislation.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950919-000174</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950919-000174</DOCID>
<DATE>950919</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Party to fight tax cuts in Budget. We'll vote against short-termelection 'bribes', says Bruce</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>STEPHEN MCGREGOR,PARLIAMENTARY CORRESPONDENT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<FLAG>ANNUAL CONFERENCE</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976306464</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
LIBERAL Democrats' economic affairs spokesman Malcolm Bruce won a
lengthy standing ovation from the conference yesterday when he pledged
the party to vote against any tax cuts in this year's Budget and
promised the return of Railtrack to majority public ownership.
With the Government under pressure to produce tax cuts if it is to
have any hope of winning the next General Election, Mr Bruce was clear
that his party would have nothing to do with what would be viewed as a
cynical election tax bribe.
Mr Bruce announced the launch of a Liberal Democrat petition -- forms
were placed on every seat in the conference hall -- aimed at making
education this year's Budget priority.
The Liberal Democrats have said they are prepared to put 1p on income
tax to fund further spending on education, and yesterday it was clear
the policy had the overwhelming backing of party members.
Mr Bruce said: ''My message to Kenneth Clarke today is that long-term
investment in education must come before cynical short term bribes, and
lower interest rates should come before higher borrowing.
''Tax cuts cannot be right when public borrowing is heading for almost
#30bn this year. Each income tax payer in this country is already paying
almost #1000 per year interest on our Government's accumulated debts.
That is the Tories' tax bombshell.''
Mr Bruce said the obsession with short-term tax cuts left most people
cold, and argued that irresponsible tax cuts now now would endanger the
prospects for lower interest rates, which both hard-pressed homeowners
and business urgently needed.
He told the conference: ''Sound fiscal policy could bring down
interest rates by one or even two per cent -- but it will not happen if
irresponsible tax cuts take place instead.
Mr Bruce restated the party's backing for an independent UK reserve
bank, European monetary union and a single currency.
''Only we can be trusted on tax. Vote Conservative and you are in for
the tax bombshell of low growth. Vote Labour and you're signing a blank
cheque on taxation.
''Vote Liberal Democrat and you get no promises without the bill
attached, no taxation without explanation and no more asked of from you
until we have demonstrated that government can do with less.''
The Liberal Democrats' line meant that it would vote against tax cuts
in this year's Budget, and on a day of tension between the Liberal
Democrats and Labour, Mr Bruce issued a challenge to Labour leader Tony
Blair: ''If you really want co-operation, then join with us in the
lobbies and vote for our children's future.''
On the future of the railways, Mr Bruce said there could be no better
example than railway privatisation of dogma, not logic, determining
policy.
''Railway privatisation is the bridge, tunnel and track too far for
this Government. Make no mistake. This would not be private enterprise,
it would be the biggest privately-owned lame duck ever created.
Dependent for ever on public hand-outs but accountable first to private
shareholders. It would be higher fares for the many and higher salaries
for the few.''
* During a debate on transport, party spokesman Paul Tyler said no
sane investor would put money into the sell-off of Railtrack if it was
made clear that an in-coming government would take back a controlling
51% stake.
If Mr Blair would give the nation just one straight promise for once,
''the threat of a successful sell-off of the rail network before polling
day would be halted in its tracks'', Mr Tyler said.
He warned the privatisation would derail plans for a coherent network
attracting more passengers and freight.
He claimed a ''war of attrition'' had started over the sell-off, with
services being cut in the winter passenger timetable which comes into
effect later this month.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950919-000175</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950919-000175</DOCID>
<DATE>950919</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Deal on Scottish assembly numbers faces test</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>STEPHEN MCGREGOR</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<FLAG>ANNUAL CONFERENCE</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>976306465</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE deal struck recently by the Liberal Democrats' Scottish leader Jim
Wallace and Labour's Shadow Scottish Secretary George Robertson over
plans for a Scottish parliament will come under scrutiny at the
conference today (writes Stephen McGregor).
This agreement produced a joint declaration that they supported a
parliament of 129 MPs, to be elected by a form of proportional
representation, breaking what was seen as a deadlock in discussion of
the issue.
The motion for this morning's debate commends the Scottish party on
the progress made in recent weeks within the Scottish Constitutional
Convention towards the final establishment of a scheme for a Scottish
parliament.
However, Labour is criticised for its retreat from proposing elected
assemblies for the regions of England, and for the ''endorsement by the
Labour Party in Wales of unfair, first-past-the-post voting in its
watered down plans for a Welsh Assembly.''
The Tories also are criticised for their ''rejection of any
significant constitutional development, except in the proposals for an
assembly for Northern Ireland.''
The debate is being seen largely as a rubber-stamping exercise for the
agreement reached between Mr Robertson and Mr Wallace -- an example of
the two parties working together -- but there may be some signs of
discontent from the conference floor because some activists feel there
has not been enough consultation.
Mr Wallace said yesterday that it was a matter of regret that neither
the SNP nor the Tories had come into the Convention and now were sniping
from the sidelines. He said it would have been better if everyone had
been able to be constructive.
Party president and Caithness and Sutherland MP Bob Maclennan, in a
swipe at Labour, said: ''A parliament for Scotland 'Yes,' but to make no
change in Scottish representation in Westminster is to butter your
bannock on both sides and it simply isn't on.
''An assembly for Wales with the old voting system entrenching
minority rule? That will not do. Nor will regional talking shops for
councillors dressed up as regional government. The truth is that we know
the shape of reform, but those who favour it must get the detail right
if it is to reach and stand secure on the statute book.''
* As he welcomed the conference's 1500 representatives to the city,
Glasgow's Labour Lord Provost Tommy Dingwall skirted around any direct
remarks about his party's relationship with the Liberal Democrats.
However, Sir Russell Johnston, MP for Inverness, Nairn and Lochaber,
could not resist a dig at Labour when he replied.
''I don't know if you are old Labour or new Labour,'' he told Mr
Dingwall. ''Our problem is that we aren't quite sure how far beneath the
skin the difference goes.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950919-000176</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950919-000176</DOCID>
<DATE>950919</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Little agreement -- but  republican and loyalist meet</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ROBBIE DINWOODIE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<FLAG>ANNUAL CONFERENCE</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>976306466</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SENIOR republican and loyalist politicians shared a platform in
Glasgow last night, having been brought together through the efforts of
the Liberal Democrats and the Alliance Party in Northern Ireland,
(writes Robbie Dinwoodie).
Sinn Fein chairman Mitchel McLaughlin and Ulster Democratic Party
leader Gary McMichael sat on either side of the Liberal Democrats'
Northern Ireland spokesman Lord Holme in what is believed to be the
first such public reconciliation since the ceasefire started over a year
ago.
Although neither side gave anything away in terms of its policy
positions, Liberal Democrat organisers said the mere fact of their
coming together at a conference fringe meeting was encouraging for the
peace process.
They were joined on the platform of a packed meeting by Dr John
Alderdice, the Alliance Party leader, and a political scientist from the
University of Ulster, Professor Paul Arthur.
Lord Holme said earlier that he had kept the Government informed of
the intention to bring together representatives of the political wings
of the IRA and UDA and there had been no objection.
Mr McLaughlin told the meeting that the obstacle to peace came from
the British Government, which continued to pursue by various means the
military victory over the IRA which had eluded them for 25 years, and
added: ''Is decommissioning of weapons so critical that the cessation of
hostilities should be threatened?''
Mr McLaughlin expressed caution with the way things were going.
He said: ''We do not yet have peace, we do not yet have peace talks
and no one can be confident that we will ever have peace talks.''
Mr McMichael pointed out that his own father had been murdered by the
IRA, but he said that everyone in Northern Ireland had the right to seek
self-determination and Sinn Fein had the right to argue its case.
However he insisted that it had to make a start on decommissioning and
said: ''Sinn Fein must find a way to prove they are committed to
peaceful means. No one is asking the IRA to surrender, merely to engage
in a process of decommissioning.''
Dr Alderdice said that one year on, those who felt most elated by the
ceasefire now felt most depressed by the stand off. He said most people
in Northern Ireland did not care about the terms talks, substantive
talks or formal negotiations, they just wanted their leaders to get on
with it.
Lord Holme afterwards described the meeting it as ''good''.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950919-000177</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950919-000177</DOCID>
<DATE>950919</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Benefit transfer to help jobless urged</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<FLAG>ANNUAL CONFERENCE</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>976306467</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Liberal Democrats yesterday backed a plan to switch benefit
payments from the unemployed to employers to provide an incentive for
firms to take on jobless people.
However, some representatives complained that the proposal to tackle
long-term unemployment was not radical enough.
Liberal Democrat Employment spokesman David Chidgey, introducing the
motion, said: ''Long-term unemployment is creating division in our
society and we must set an agenda to create social cohesion.''
THE conference yesterday endorsed moves to establish a Bill of Rights
for disabled people. Representatives voted unanimously to adopt the
Access for All disability policy paper. This would enforce a quota-levy
system to penalise businesses which do not fill their quota of disabled
employees and institutionalise civil rights for disabled people through
a Human Rights Commission. Liberal Democrat spokesman on disability Liz
Lynne MP said the Government's Disability Discrimination Bill had been
''too little, too late''.
BIG cuts in vehicle excise duty for low-powered cars were demanded by
the Liberal Democrats in a bid to cut pollution.  The conference backed
a motion to reduce the tax from #135 to as little as #5 for cars below
1500cc.  Coupled with higher taxes on petrol, the aim would be to
encourage people to switch to smaller, more fuel-efficient cars.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
