<DOCNO>GH950919-000193</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950919-000193</DOCID>
<DATE>950919</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Red card bets ruled off-side</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>KEITH SINCLAIR</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976306483</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Scottish Football League (SFL) has warned bookmakers they could
have their licences withdrawn if they take bets on the possibility of
Rangers footballer Paul Gascoigne being sent off during the first Old
Firm match of the season tonight.
The SFL said yesterday it was not aware of any specific cases of such
bets for tonight's game, but some Glasgow bookmakers had come up with a
series of novelty bets, including a 16-1 bet on Gascoigne being
red-carded twice before Christmas.
An SFL spokesman said: ''There were a couple of bookmakers offering
bets of this nature. We have contacted the bookies concerned and told
them we found this type of bet wholly unacceptable.
''Obviously, taking bets on any player being sent off, and not just
Paul Gascoigne, can have serious ramifications, not least for
referees.''
The spokesman added: ''We warned the bookies that we have the power to
withdraw licences from them which we issue at the start of each season.
And, if the offence is serious enough, we could withdraw the licence
immediately.''
A spokesman for John Smith bookmakers said: ''We will not take bets on
any player being sent off for any game.''
Coral bookmakers have made Rangers favourites for tonight's game. They
are 6-4, while Celtic are 13-8.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
