<DOCNO>GH950919-000195</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950919-000195</DOCID>
<DATE>950919</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Blair scoffs at 'tittle-tattle'. Prescott people said to feel alienated.</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>BENEDICT BROGAN, POLITICAL REPORTER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976306485</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
LABOUR leader Tony Blair moved to quash rumours of a split with his
deputy John Prescott by telling his Shadow Cabinet yesterday he will
respond to his critics with a detailed list of policy commitments in his
address to party conference next month.
He dismissed as ''silly'' persistent suggestions that he has offended
Mr Prescott after excluding him from a number of strategy discussions
attended by Mr Blair's close aides, who have been criticised by the left
of the party for being unelected and too right-wing.
Mr Prescott's supporters within the party are said to be dismayed by
the extent to which decision-making, in particular on Labour's General
Election strategy, has become centred on a small group of Mr Blair's
advisers who are considered unsympathetic to some of Labour's
traditions.
But yesterday Mr Blair praised Mr Prescott for his role in helping to
secure victory for the leadership earlier this year in its campaign to
change Clause 4 of the party constitution.
Mr Blair said: ''You should remember it was John Prescott and I who
put through the biggest change in the Labour Party's constitution in
history. That is the best testament I can put.''
Personality issues had no place in the work of the Shadow Cabinet, he
said, while his office pointed out Mr Prescott has been asked to make
the crucial speech winding up the conference.
''People are not interested in tittle-tattle. What they want to know
about a Labour Government is what it is going to do about the economy,
education, the health service, crime, and law and order on our
streets,'' Mr Blair said.
''Whatever noise is going on off-stage is not going to deflect us from
that because that is the people's agenda and that is what the people
want to be able to hear.''
Mr Blair told a meeting of the Shadow Cabinet, called to finalise
plans for the conference, that he would use his speech to define his
vision of new Britain.
''New Labour was never going to be enough. It's new Britain that
matters. This conference is about the kind of specific commitments we
are going to make, honour, and carry through in government,'' he said.
A Labour source said afterwards that Mr Blair's speech would contain
''specific policy commitments in key areas'', but that he would stick to
Labour's policy of making no pre-election spending commitments that
might be seized on by the Tories.
The Shadow Cabinet also listened to a polling presentation which
suggested that despite a string of summer setbacks, in which party
members attacked Mr Blair for modernising too fast, the party remains in
the position it was at the beginning of the summer.
Earlier, Mr Blair ridiculed suggestions that he was prepared to offer
Shadow Social Security secretary Donald Dewar the post of Labour Chief
Whip in his anticipated reshuffle of the Shadow Cabinet.
He told a London press conference yesterday: ''No decisions have been
taken on who is the Chief Whip. That is one of the many stories giving
me cause for amusement this morning.''
Mr Blair is to meet representatives of Scottish business and industry
in Edinburgh as part of a nationwide tour aimed at improving the party's
image with a sector that is traditionally suspicious of its policies.
The initiative, dubbed the ''bacon and eggs offensive'', echoes
Labour's ''prawn cocktail offensive'' before the 1992 General Election,
when MPs embarked on a round of meetings in the City to ease doubts
about the effects of Labour's tax plans.
Mr Blair, along with Shadow Chancellor Gordon Brown, Shadow Foreign
Secretary Robin Cook, who chairs the party's National Policy Forum, and
Shadow Trade and Industry secretary John Cunningham, will tour the
country to meet business leaders and hear their concerns.
This week he will address 600 businessmen and women in Birmingham, and
a similar number in Crawley. His visit to Edinburgh is expected in the
late autumn.
Labour will publish a White Paper next year on its plans for business,
based on what it hears during the tour.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
