<HEADLINE>Doctors cleared over 'car park rage'</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CAMERON SIMPSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976306486</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A NEUROLOGICAL consultant who allegedly flew into a rage after finding
his car boxed in at a car park was found not guilty yesterday of breach
of the peace and vandalism.
Dr Goran Jamal, 42, who works at the Southern General Hospital in
Glasgow, was acquitted at the end of the second day of his trial at
Bearsden and Milngavie District Court. His wife, Vian, 33, a pathologist
at the Royal, was also found not guilty of breach of the peace.
The couple hugged briefly before leaving court. Dr Jamal told
reporters they were pleased with the result. The case, he added, had not
been necessary. ''However, justice has been done,'' he said.
The court had heard from Mrs Pamela Baird, of Morven Road, Bearsden,
that the Jamals had subjected her and her four-year-old daughter to a
terrifying experience after wrongly accusing her of boxing in his car
last year at the Glebe car park in Bearsden.
Mrs Baird alleged that Dr Jamal, of Camstradden Drive West, Bearsden,
had been abusive, bullying and intimidating. He had told her he had
called the police and that she must wait for them to come. As she began
to drive away he had smashed her windscreen with his fist.
She alleged that Mrs Jamal had also been very angry and that she had
repeatedly banged on the bonnet of her car.
Yesterday, however, Dr Jamal challenged Mrs Baird's and other
witnesses' version of events.
He told defence solicitor William Macreath that Mrs Baird had been
patronising towards him. He told her he had telephoned the police and
that she should wait until they arrived. At this time he put his hand on
the car door. ''She shut the door trapping my hand. I was in
excruciating pain.''
As Mrs Baird started to reverse he began banging on her windscreen
with his left hand to let her know that his right one was trapped. His
wife rushed forward and started thumping Mrs Baird's bonnet, again to
let her know of his predicament.
Mr Macreath asked: ''Did you swear?'' Dr Jamal: ''Absolutely not.''
He said that by this time he and his wife were shouting to each other
in Kurdish. She told him to pull his hand free and he managed to do so.
Ms Waldron put it to him that the injury to his hand might have been
self-inflicted to explain his behaviour. Dr Jamal replied: ''I do not
accept that.''
Dr Patrick Grant, accident and emerency consultant at the Western,
told the court that he had seen Dr Jamal about two-and-a-half hours
after the incident. The injuries were consistent with his fingers being
crushed between two firm surfaces, Dr Grant said.
Asked whether they could be consistent with a fist striking a car
windscreen, Dr Grant replied: ''I would not have said so.''
Returning his verdict, magistrate William Dudgeon told the Jamals that
he was not satisfied beyond reasonable doubt that they had committed the
offences.
Last night Mrs Baird, who was not in court, said: ''I feel quite
outraged by the verdict.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
