<DOCNO>GH950919-000198</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950919-000198</DOCID>
<DATE>950919</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Random sampling is 'meaningless'. Double-check review urged for negative smear tests</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ALAN MACDERMID, MEDICAL CORRESPONDENT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976306488</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ALL negative cervical cancer slides should be double-checked for
accuracy, a Scottish Office report on quality control in laboratories
recommended yesterday.
A committee of experts said that random one-in-10 sampling --
traditionally used in many laboratories -- was a meaningless way of
monitoring error rates.
Instead, it recommended that each slide judged negative in the first
instance should be given a 30-second rapid re-scan by another
cytologist.
These rapid reviews should be carried out first thing in the morning
''when eyes are fresh'' before starting on the new day's workload.
Slides judged unsatisfactory -- obscured or with inadequate material --
should also be dealt with in this way.
The 10-member working party was set up to report on internal quality
control for cervical cytology laboratories in the wake of the problems
at Inverclyde Royal Hospital, Greenock, when 20,000 slides had to be
reviewed after deficiencies were found in the laboratory there.
Medical experts from both sides of the Border sat on the committee,
whose recommendations are expected to be taken up throughout the UK.
Cervical cancer kills about 1800 women in Britain every year and the
report says 90% of invasive squamous cervical cancer can be avoided
among those who are regularly screened.
About 80% of the eligible population take part in the programme.
The report makes clear that no screening programme can provide 100%
protection from disease and that public expectations of perfection are
unrealistic.
''Health education programmes should state this explicitly,'' it said.
''The interpretation of cervical smears is a subjective assessment of
minor variations of cell colour, shape, size, and density, in which some
diversity of opinion is inevitable.
''However, this in no way diminishes the responsibility of service
providers to ensure that the programme meets, and preferably exceeds,
defined standards.''
Although guidelines were available from professional bodies, the
absence of absolute standards had handicapped the committee's work.
It said: ''It is the task of professioal bodies to set and review such
standards, and of purchasers to ensure their inclusion in service
specifications.''
The report was launched yesterday by Scottish Secretary Michael
Forsyth at the British Society for Clinical Cytology's annual scientific
meeting in Crieff, Perthshire.
He said: ''Implementation of the recommendations of this report will
result in significant improvements in the quality of the service
provided.''
The working party acknowledged that implementing its report would
increase costs but could not say by how much, since it would vary from
laboratory to laboratory.
Some may already have adopted most of the recommendations but for
others the cost implications might be significant.
However, it considers this is justified by the improved service to
patients, the savings in cost of expensive look-back exercises of the
type that had to be carried out at Inverclyde, and savings in other
areas, such as repeat tests and unnecessary referrals.
Dr Alistair Robertson, consultant pathologist and clinical director of
the Department of Pathology at Ninewells Hospital, Dundee, and a member
of the working party, said: ''I think we in Scotland can be quietly
confident that most laboratories are complying with most of the
recommendations.
''However, all laboratories will have to re-examine their procedures
in the light of this report. One big change that will affect a number of
labs is the change in the method of checking. In the past, we did a 10%
sample -- now we are recommending 100%.''
''We have to ensure that we have the highest quality of staff. This
report should not be seen in isolation from the external quality control
measures that are already in place, which ensure that all staff involved
in reporting on smears undergo a proficiency test twice a year.
''One of the report's most important messages is that screening cannot
be 100% effective. There will always be the occasional woman who has a
negative smear and goes on to develop cancer.
''That means that any woman who has had a negative smear and then
develops symptoms should have them seen to, and not assume that it can't
be cervical cancer.''
Labour's Scottish spokesman on health, Mr John McAllion, said: ''If
this is the best advice of the experts, and the Government is going to
implement it, then obviously that is welcome.
''But they can't run away from the resource implications. You can't
provide high-quality public services by cutting resources,'' added the
MP for Dundee East.
The report main recommendations are:
* Clear, documented lines of accountability in laboratories, with
someone explicitly responsible for quality control.
* Contractual responsibility for the consultant in charge to deliver a
service to an agreed specification.
* Standard operating procedures should be documented for every
laboratory process.
* Laboratory procedures should be routinely monitored.
* One or two individuals should supervise technical and clerical
procedures.
* All laboratories should be computerised, with electronic transfer of
results to health boards, and software to record internal quality
control. In the meantime, those which are not must maintain efficient
manual records.
* Slides and documentation on IQC should be retained for at least 10
years.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
