<HEADLINE>Tory tax and the Budget dilemma</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>GEOFFREY PARKHOUSE, POLITICAL EDITOR</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976306489</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
TWO stark warnings from the Chancellor and Governor of the Bank of
England have highlighted the desperate Whitehall battle on state
spending and borrowing -- a struggle still unresolved.
The prospect of tax cuts in the November 28 Budget receded yesterday
as Chancellor Kenneth Clarke was obliged to issue figures which left him
#700m short on his target to reduce the colossal government borrowing.
This is central to his room for manoeuvre on both interest rates and
reduction in taxation.
Mr Eddie George, Governor of the Bank of England, underlined the
Chancellor's dilemma for his Budget. The borrowing rate should remain at
6.75% in the circumstances, he said in Manchester. A reduction might
also threaten increased inflation.
Mr Clarke who is struggling with his Cabinet colleagues to find real
cuts in the #300bn public expenditure, took the first step yesterday in
remedial measures. He announced that public sector workers must be
constrained to pay rises next year below the level of inflation and that
more efficiencies must be produced to meet this.
To ram the message home to his Cabinet spending colleagues, he made it
clear the Government's contingency reserve fund cannot be raided to
finance pay settlements in the public sector.
The two statements signal a truce in the two men's dispute over the
last three months about interest rates.
Mr George now concedes Mr Clarke was right in refusing his demands for
an increase in the borrowing rate for both business and individuals.
He told Manchester businessmen: ''I understand the current
uncertainties, the patchiness of the economy with important sectors
still struggling, having so far been hardly touched by the expansion.
''I understand the wider fears of a more general slow-down in output
and employment growth, and I understand the temptation to look for more
stimulus in the short term.''
Such a stimulus has been rejected by the Cabinet as recently as last
week at its special political strategy meeting. State borrowing is still
too high and is likely to keep interest rates from being cut.
In the approach to the Tory Party conference in Blackpool next month,
when the Prime Minister hopes his colleagues can orchestrate a Tory
revival, yesterday's figures were a setback.
Furthermore, the Chancellor's edict yesterday on public sector pay
provides Mr Blair with ammunition to attack a continuing policy which
affects workers from nurses to High Court judges. Mr Clarke insisted the
pay review bodies must make their assessments on ''an affordable
basis''.
Corporation tax receipts next month may redress the balance of public
sector borrowing, but the figures issued jointly yesterday by the
Treasury and the Central Statistical Office revealed the Government had
to borrow #4600m to plug the gap between its spending and income in
August. It took the cumulative PSBR for the first five months of the tax
year to #16.7bn, #700m more than the same period last year.
The shortfall was much bigger than the #3500m expected.
</TEXT>
