<HEADLINE>Siamese twins 'doing well' after life-saving surgery</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976306490</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SIAMESE twins Chloe and Nicole Astbury were last night ''doing very
well'' after an 11-hour life-saving operation which left doctors
uncertain over their future.
Surgeons at St Mary's Hospital, Manchester, decided to operate on the
girls to separate a shared bowel after tests and scans showed their
lives were at risk.
Last night, the girls' parents, Melanie, 25, and Brian, 26, were said
to be bearing up well after the ordeal of waiting for the results of the
marathon operation on their daughters.
''The only way I can describe how they feel is to say relief,'' said
family solicitor Ms Andrea McWatt.
''The hospital tonight say the girls are stable and as well as can be
expected. It is unbelievable how they have come through after 11 hours
in surgery.
''They are both tough little ladies and have come through it all.''
Cards, flowers, and messages have continued to pour into the hospital
from around the country -- many of them from strangers.
The medical team caring for the girls admitted the surgery on Sunday
had raised questions over what they hoped would be a future operation to
separate the twins, born on Thursday last week.
Scots surgeon Mr Alan Dickson said: ''The extent of the bowel damage
is a disappointment to us. Clearly, this has implications for the future
but I am not prepared to speculate on that.''
The babies were on ventilators last night and will have to remain on
drip feeds for up to one year. Mr Dickson said they had lost a
significant part of their upper bowel. But he did say he was still
''cautiously optimistic'' about the future.
Doctors discovered during surgery that the liver and bowel were the
only organs shared by the girls.
But Mr Dickson said: ''The liver join is very complicated. The whole
join is very complicated.''
The decision to operate was made on Saturday night because the twins'
bowel was obstructed and there was a risk of a fatal perforation.
The problems probably arose half-way through Mrs Astbury's pregnancy
as a result of the two babies' bowel being loose and able to wrap
themselves around each other.
Mr Dickson said the operation was performed without losing any more of
the bowel than had already been damaged.
He said what the medical team discovered about the extent of the join
in the twins' liver during the operation meant separation of it would be
a ''surgical challenge''.
Mr Dickson said of the twins: ''We have some concerns, certainly in
the short term. These children have lost a very significant part of the
upper part of the bowel. This will have implications for their
nutrition. How long for is pure speculation.
''But we are pleased with the twins' present situation and hope they
make a recovery.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950919-000201</DOCNO>
