<HEADLINE>Nato force likely for Bosnia</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976306491</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
UNITED Nations Secretary-General Boutros Boutros-Ghali said yesterday
UN troops in Bosnia should be replaced by an international coalition
whether or not current efforts lead to a peace accord.
His comments signalled the first step towards sending a Nato-led force
to the war-torn country.
In a letter to the Security Council, Mr Boutros-Ghali said that if a
peace agreement were concluded he would propose that it authorise ''an
ad hoc coalition of member states'' acting with appropriate regional
organisations to implement such a plan.
Equally, if the current US peace initiative does not succeed and the
council takes more ''enforcement action'', he would recommend the
31,000-strong UN force be replaced.
He did not specify the multinational force but it was clear he had
Nato in mind.
''In either case urgent action would be required to prepare for an
expeditious handover by UN Protection Force to the multinational force
that would be established by member states so authorised by the
council,'' he said.
His comments came as British Foreign Secretary Malcolm Rifkind left
Bosnia having failed to convince leaders to halt military offensives in
western Bosnia that threaten to end peace moves and create a
humanitarian disaster.
Bosnian Foreign Minister Muhamed Sacirbey had offered a surprise
initiative of talks with moderate Serb leaders over the fate of the
stronghold of Banja Luka.
Despite an urgent call from the UN Security Council for an immediate
halt to the fighting, the Bosnians said offensives would continue.
Mr Boutros-Ghali also pointed out yesterday that the UN had a limited
capacity to manage large-scale operations, particularly those using
force, and noted again the failure of member states to pay peacekeeping
contributions on time.
He said there were difficulties in ''co-ordinating the operations of
military personnel and civilian personnel with different mandates and
different chains of command''.
However, he said the UN could still play a useful peacekeeping role in
Croatia and in Macedonia. The Croatian operation of 14,000 troops is
currently being reduced to 2500 and Macedonia has about 1100
peacekeepers.
There was no immediate concrete reaction from council members.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950919-000202</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950919-000202</DOCID>
<DATE>950919</DATE>
<HEADLINE>'Bullying boss' wins tribunal case</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976306492</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A WOMAN boss branded ''a bully'' has won an industrial tribunal case
raised by her secretary.
The secretary, Mrs Sheila McKerron, told the tribunal that career
woman Karen Stewart, 33, was ''bullying, dominant, guilty of blame
transference'', and treated her like an office junior.
But yesterday, mother of three Mrs McKerron, 48, lost her claim for
unfair dismissal against her boss's organisation, The Quality Scotland
Foundation, which promotes ''quality management'' among more than 100
top Scottish companies and is aiming to recruit several hundred more.
Mrs McKerron also complained her boss referred to her as ''McKerron''
instead of by her first name, or calling her Mrs McKerron.
Mrs Stewart hit back by claiming that the secretary she hired for her
pleasing personality made mistakes, and that when they were memoed she
was aggressive and abusive.
Mrs McKerron was finally sacked by Edinburgh-based Quality Scotland
chief executive David Justice, only four months into the job, after the
secretary ignored a suggestion by him that she take a few days off work
to allow the situation in the small, two woman office in Inverness to
cool down. Instead she continued working.
''I was absolutely flabbergasted at being sacked,'' Mrs McKerron told
the Inverness tribunal.
She was unable to take Quality Scotland, who are involved in the
''Investors in People'' scheme, to the tribunal in the normal manner
because she lacked the necessary two years' employment.
Instead she invoked a section of the Employment Protection Act,
claiming that health and safety issues were involved in the loss of her
#10,000 a year job.
She claimed she had been ordered by Mrs Stewart, of Culduthel Park,
Inverness, to connect up the computer where there were loose wires and
screws ''like Spaghetti Junction''.
But Mrs Stewart and Mr Justice claimed she had never raised health and
safety matters with them.
Mrs McKerron's husband, Colin, of South Street, Elgin -- health and
safety manager with United Distillers -- told the tribunal he noticed
Mrs Stewart was ''overtly aggressive'' in her manner with his wife at a
two-day seminar. And he had previously warned his wife not to tamper
with electrical equipment.
</TEXT>
