<HEADLINE>Ashdown blanks out Blair offer.  Lib-Dem anger at hint of links.</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>STEPHEN MCGREGOR, PARLIAMENTARY CORRESPONDENT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976306493</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
FURIOUS Liberal Democrat leader Paddy Ashdown yesterday told Labour to
come up with some clear policies if there is to be any prospect of
co-operation between the two parties.
He particularly challenged Labour leader Tony Blair to prove his offer
of closer links was genuine by backing Lib-Dem opposition to any tax
cuts in November's Budget.
Mr Ashdown and his senior colleagues were clearly angered by comments
from Mr Blair in which he said he was prepared to discuss key policies
with the Liberal Democrats before an election and to discuss legislation
with them afterwards.
However, Mr Ashdown accused Labour of having no clear policies. ''You
can't negotiate with a blank piece of paper,'' he said.
At a Westminster news conference, Mr Blair appeared to soften his
line, though the offer of some sort of co-operation still was there.
''We are a strong, independent party with our policies and programmes,
but if there are areas where, in the interests of the country, we can
agree and co-operate then we will do that.''
The Liberal Democrats at all levels feel Mr Blair has moved
deliberately to overshadow their conference, at which they are trying to
set out their own, distinctive agenda. On Sunday the conference passed a
strategy document which said: ''Our opposition to this Conservative
Government will not mean cosying up to Labour.''
Mr Ashdown said yesterday that three years ago he had led the calls
for an end to the squabbling among political parties and more
co-operation, but he made clear that at this stage he did not believe
the Labour Party had anything to offer. On the conference floor,
feelings against Mr Blair and Labour bordered on the vitriolic.
The view is that Mr Blair is trying to steal the Liberal Democrats'
clothes, if not their votes, and Mr Ashdown, who is bound to refer to
the matter in his keynote conference address today, has issued a clear
''come and get me'' message to Mr Blair.
He argued that his party this week was producing clear-cut policies on
a range of issues, but so far, ''Labour has simply failed to come up to
the mark''. He said it was going the wrong way on such key issues as
regional government and reform of the House of Lords, and added: ''You
can't negotiate with a blank piece of paper.''
Lib-Dem president, Caithness and Sutherland MP Robert Maclennan,
issued a strong rebuff to Labour's overtures. He told the conference
that Mr Blair's extension of the hand of friendship was a ''well-merited
tribute'' to the Liberal Democrats' achievements, but described Labour
as a party ''paralysed since the defeat of 1992'' and desperate not to
give offence.
He said: ''Has a kind message from a friend altered our resolve? I
think not.
''As we said yesterday, say again today and will go on saying to
whoever may pay us the compliment of giving us a call, the Liberal
Democrats are an independent, growing party with a distinctive political
and policy agenda for Britain. That is our unambiguous reply.''
Mr Malcolm Bruce, the party's spokesmen on Treasury affairs, said that
when the Tories set out their tax bribes stall this year, Labour would
be left speechless, ''all soundbite and no substance''.
He went on: ''For many years we said we wanted to get rid of the
Labour Party, now Tony Blair is doing it. He tries to steal all our best
ideas. But although Mr Blair may think he is creating the basis for a
Labour victory he is really composing a recipe for what would, in
Government, be a split and directionless party.''
Lord Holme, chairman of the party's General Election team, said:
''Although I would by no means rule out Labour and the Liberal Democrats
working together to implement an agreed programme to change Britain for
the better, I certainly do not want the parties to amalgamate because I
believe we have different analyses, different values and a different
perspective on Britain's future.
</TEXT>
