<HEADLINE>Manager denies Faldos are to split</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976306494</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
GOLFER Nick Faldo's manager yesterday denied that the European Ryder
Cup team member was divorcing his second wife Gill.
Mr John Simpson said: ''Nick and Gill are not getting divorced. I find
the whole thing extraordinary. All Nick is concentrating on at the
moment is winning back the Ryder Cup.''
Mrs Faldo, 37, was angered by the newspaper speculation as she flew
from London's Heathrow airport with the European team to join her
husband, already in America.
Looking tearful and upset, she told reporters: ''I have absolutely no
comment to make.''
The golfer's manager hit out at the media for running stories saying
that the Faldo marriage of nine years was on the rocks. The Sun led the
field with an exclusive headlined ''Faldo's #10m divorce shocker''.
He said: ''There is not a direct quote from Nick or Gill in any of the
stories. I don't know where they came from. All I can say is that Nick
and Gill are not getting a divorce.''
European captain Bernard Gallagher said he did not think the publicity
about Nick's marriage would affect the team's chances of wresting the
Ryder Cup from the Americans this weekend. The three-day tournament is
being staged in Rochester, New York State.
He conceded the pressure of playing top level golf did put a strain on
marriages. ''History proves it does,'' he said. ''They do spend a lot of
time away.''
The Faldos married in 1986, after his first marriage, to former sports
journalist Melanie, ended in 1984, after five years.     Mrs Faldo has
helped build her husband's businesses, and is a director of Nick Faldo
International. It is estimated he earned #4m last year.
</TEXT>
