<HEADLINE>Back to the future of the SECC</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976306495</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
COMEDIAN Tony Roper and former Govan MP Mr Andy McMahon re-trod old
ground yesterday at a ceremony to begin the construction of a
controversial futuristic extension to the SECC at Queen's Dock, Glasgow.
The #30m building, made of eight aluminium clad bands and dubbed 'the
Armadillo' by critics of its appearance, features a 3000-seater
auditorium and will make the SECC among the largest conference complexes
in Europe.
Mr McMahon, 75, who spent 28 years as a shipwright at Queen's Dock and
for whom Mr Roper was an apprentice, called the building ''a new
milestone in the development of Glasgow''.
SECC chief executive Mr Mike Closier said the facilities, designed by
Sir Norman Foster and due for completion in 1997, would double the
centre's existing conference capacity, enabling it to generate 2800 jobs
and an annual #70m for the economy of Greater Glasgow.
</TEXT>
